  3  * The global CCC namespace. 
  4  * 
  5  * @namespace
  6  */
  7 pvc = {};

  9 /**
 10  * The CCC options namespace.
 11  * <p>
 12  * All types of this namespace,
 13  * as well as of the namespaces below this one, 
 14  * are 
 15  * <b>documentation</b> types -
 16  * they do not exist, in code, 
 17  * and serve only to document the structure of the options objects 
 18  * that each chart type accepts in its constructor.
 19  * 
 20  * <p>
 21  * The following code shows how to 
 22  * create and configure a very simple CCC Bar chart:
 23  * 
 24  * <pre>// Options are placed in a plain JS object
 25  * var options = {
 26  *     title:  "A CCC Bar chart",
 27  *     legend: true,
 28  *     crosstabMode: false
 29  * };
 30  * 
 31  * var data = {
 32  *     metadata: [
 33  *         {colIndex: 0, colType: "String", colName: "Series"}, 
 34  *         {colIndex: 1, colType: "String", colName: "Category"}, 
 35  *         {colIndex: 2, colType: "String", colName: "Value"}
 36  *     ],
 37  *     resultset: [
 38  *         ["London", "2010-01-02", 1],
 39  *         ["London", "2010-01-03", 2],
 40  *         ["London", "2010-01-04", 3],
 41  *         ["London", "2010-01-05", 2],
 42  *         ["Paris",  "2010-01-01", 3],
 43  *         ["Paris",  "2010-01-02", 6],
 44  *         ["Paris",  "2010-01-04", 1],
 45  *         ["Paris",  "2010-01-05", 7],
 46  *         ["Lisbon", "2010-01-01", 3],
 47  *         ["Lisbon", "2010-01-02", 2],
 48  *         ["Lisbon", "2010-01-03", 1],
 49  *         ["Lisbon", "2010-01-04", 5]
 50  *     ]
 51  * };
 52  * 
 53  * new pvc.BarChart(options)
 54  * .setData(data)
 55  * .render();
 56  * </pre>
 57  * Note that the options object is a plain JavaScript object,
 58  * and not a {@link pvc.options.charts.BarChart}
 59  * 
 60  * <p>
 61  * 
 62  * @namespace
 63  */
 64 pvc.options = {};
 65 
 66 /**
 67  * The namespace of CCC chart extension point classes. 
 68  * 
 69  * @namespace
 70  */
 71 pvc.options.ext = {};
 72 
 73 /**
 74  * The namespace of chart options classes. 
 75  * 
 76  * @namespace
 77  */
 78 pvc.options.charts = {};
 79 
 80 /**
 81  * The options documentation class of the basic chart facet.
 82  * 
 83  * <h2>Default Data Format</h2>
 84  * <p>
 85  * This section describes, in general, the data format accepted by CCC charts.
 86  * Most of what is here presented applies to all chart types.
 87  * <p>
 88  * The option {@link #crosstabMode} is by far the most important,
 89  * as it makes the top-level choice between the
 90  * two data formats: 
 91  * <i>relational</i> and 
 92  * <i>crosstab</i>.
 93  * <p>
 94  * Each of this formats has its own variants and,
 95  * also, both have some configuration options in common.
 96  * 
 97  * <h3>Relational Format</h3>
 98  * <p>
 99  * This format is a regular tabular format where each column of the data source
100  * corresponds to a different property of the described entity.
101  * <p>
102  * Each entity is described in a single row.
103  * Although not required,
104  * usually, one or more of the columns together identify the entity.
105  * 
106  * <h4>Example relational dataset</h4>
107  * 
108  * <pre>
109  * {
110  *     "metadata": [
111  *         {"colName": "city",  "colType": "String",  "colLabel": "City"},
112  *         {"colName": "date",  "colType": "String",  "colLabel": "Date"},
113  *         {"colName": "quant", "colType": "Numeric", "colLabel": "Quantity"}
114  *     ],
115  *     "resultset": [
116  *         ["London", "2011-06-05", 72],
117  *         ["London", "2011-06-06", 50],
118  *         ["Paris",  "2011-06-05", 27],
119  *         ["Paris",  "2011-06-06",  5],
120  *         ["Lisbon", "2011-06-05", 30],
121  *         ["Lisbon", "2011-06-12", 60]
122  *     ]
123  * }
124  *             
125  * </pre>
126  * 
127  * <h3>Crosstab Format</h3>
128  * <p>
129  * The cross-tabular format goes away from the one-to-one correspondence
130  * between 
131  * <i>row</i> and 
132  * <i>entity</i>, and 
133  * <i>column</i> and 
134  * <i>property</i>.
135  * <p>
136  * Instead, it provides a grouped and aggregated view of the entities and their properties:
137  * 
138  * <ul>
139  * 
140  * <li>One row is spawned per distinct combination of the values of the "rows" properties</li>
141  * 
142  * <li>One column is spawned per distinct combination of the values of the "columns" properties</li>
143  * 
144  * <li>One cell contains a single somehow aggregated value, or 
145  * <tt>null</tt>, corresponding to its row and column's value</li>
146  * </ul>
147  * <p>
148  * The way in which a cross-tabular form is encoded in a single-tabular structure is, in kind words, 
149  * <i>sui generis</i>.
150  * The first 
151  * <i>N</i> columns are "rows" properties, and maintain the column-property correspondence.
152  * The following columns, however, each correspond to a distinct combination of the 
153  * <i>values</i> of the "columns" properties.
154  * This leads to the 
155  * <i>values</i> of the "columns" properties being placed in a column's 
156  * <tt>colName</tt> attribute (see example, below).
157  * 
158  * <h4>Downsides</h4>
159  * <p>
160  * This form of encoding is nice and concise,
161  * but achieves that at the cost of occupying the space intended for metadata
162  * and, thus, resulting in absent metadata for the underlying entities "columns" and "measures" properties.
163  * <p>
164  * Because of this reason, unfortunately,
165  * CCC could never really rely on the values of the "colName" and "colLabel" metadata attributes.
166  * We do try to use these, when they actually contain metadata,
167  * to default dimensions' labels (see {@link #dataIgnoreMetadataLabels}).
168  * 
169  * <h4>Example crosstab dataset with one property per group</h4>
170  * This is a crosstab dataset with one "rows", one "columns" and one "measures" property.
171  * 
172  * <pre>
173  * {
174  *     "metadata": [
175  *         {"colName": "date",   "colType": "String",  "colLabel": "Date"  },
176  *         {"colName": "London", "colType": "Numeric", "colLabel": "London"},
177  *         {"colName": "Paris",  "colType": "Numeric", "colLabel": "Paris" },
178  *         {"colName": "Lisbon", "colType": "Numeric", "colLabel": "Lisbon"}
179  *     ],
180  *     "resultset": [
181  *         ["2011-06-05", 72,     27,   30],
182  *         ["2011-06-06", 50,      5, null],
183  *         ["2011-06-12", null, null,   60]
184  *     ]
185  * }
186  *             
187  * </pre>
188  * 
189  * <h4>Example crosstab dataset with two properties per discrete group</h4>
190  * This is a crosstab dataset with two "rows" properties, two "columns" properties and one "measures" property.
191  * 
192  * <pre>
193  * {
194  *     "metadata": [
195  *         {"colName": "date",   "colType": "String",  "colLabel": "Date"          },
196  *         {"colName": "family", "colType": "String",  "colLabel": "Product Family"},
197  *         {"colName": "London~Ready",      "colType": "Numeric", "colLabel": "London~Ready"      },
198  *         {"colName": "London~InProgress", "colType": "Numeric", "colLabel": "London~In Progress"},
199  *         {"colName": "Paris~Ready",       "colType": "Numeric", "colLabel": "Paris~Ready"       },
200  *         {"colName": "Paris~InProgress",  "colType": "Numeric", "colLabel": "Paris~In Progress" },
201  *         {"colName": "Lisbon~InProgress", "colType": "Numeric", "colLabel": "Lisbon~In Progress"}
202  *     ],
203  *     "resultset": [
204  *         ["2011-06-05", "Cars",     52,    0,   15,    2,   15],
205  *         ["2011-06-05", "Planes",   10,   10    10,    0,   15],
206  *         ["2011-06-06", "Cars",     10,   10,    1,    3, null],
207  *         ["2011-06-06", "Planes",   10,   20,    0,    1, null],
208  *         ["2011-06-12", "Cars",   null, null, null, null,   58],
209  *         ["2011-06-12", "Planes", null, null, null, null,    2]
210  *     ]
211  * }
212  *             
213  * </pre>
214  * 
215  * <h4>Example crosstab dataset with two properties in every group</h4>
216  * This is a crosstab dataset with two "rows" properties, two "columns" properties and two "measures" property.
217  * Yep. Sales are just ten times the quantity...
218  * <p>
219  * For this example to work,
220  * both options {@link #isMultiValued} and {@link #dataMeasuresInColumns} must be set to 
221  * <tt>true</tt>.
222  * 
223  * <pre>
224  * {
225  *     "metadata": [
226  *         {"colName": "date",   "colType": "String",  "colLabel": "Date"          },
227  *         {"colName": "family", "colType": "String",  "colLabel": "Product Family"},
228  *         {"colName": "London~Ready~quant",      "colType": "Numeric", "colLabel": "London~Ready~Quantity"      },
229  *         {"colName": "London~Ready~sales",      "colType": "Numeric", "colLabel": "London~Ready~Sales"         },
230  *         {"colName": "London~InProgress~quant", "colType": "Numeric", "colLabel": "London~In Progress~Quantity"},
231  *         {"colName": "London~InProgress~sales", "colType": "Numeric", "colLabel": "London~In Progress~Sales"   },
232  *         {"colName": "Paris~Ready~quant",       "colType": "Numeric", "colLabel": "Paris~Ready~Quantity"       },
233  *         {"colName": "Paris~Ready~sales",       "colType": "Numeric", "colLabel": "Paris~Ready~Sales"          },
234  *         {"colName": "Paris~InProgress~quant",  "colType": "Numeric", "colLabel": "Paris~In Progress~Quantity" },
235  *         {"colName": "Paris~InProgress~sales",  "colType": "Numeric", "colLabel": "Paris~In Progress~Sales"    },
236  *         {"colName": "Lisbon~InProgress~quant", "colType": "Numeric", "colLabel": "Lisbon~In Progress~Quantity"},
237  *         {"colName": "Lisbon~InProgress~sales", "colType": "Numeric", "colLabel": "Lisbon~In Progress~Sales"   }
238  *     ],
239  *     "resultset": [
240  *         ["2011-06-05", "Cars",     52,  520,    0,    0,  15,  150,    2,    20,  15,   150],
241  *         ["2011-06-05", "Planes",   10,  100,   10   100,  10,  100,    0,     0,  15,   150],
242  *         ["2011-06-06", "Cars",     10,  100,   10,  100,   1,   10,    3,    30, null, null],
243  *         ["2011-06-06", "Planes",   10,  100,   20,  200,   0,    0,    1,    10, null, null],
244  *         ["2011-06-12", "Cars",   null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null,   58,  580],
245  *         ["2011-06-12", "Planes", null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null,    2,  200]
246  *     ]
247  * }
248  *             
249  * </pre>
250  * 
251  * <h3>Physical Column Groups</h3>
252  * Traditionally, cross-tabular data contains "categories" in "rows" and "series" in "columns".
253  * Because of this, when in the context of the crosstab format,
254  * these terms end up being used interchangeably.
255  * <p>
256  * The separation of columns, at the data format layer,
257  * results in (what is referred to in this text as) 
258  * <i>physical column groups</i>.
259  * Three physical groups are identified: "series", "categories" and "measures".
260  * 
261  * <h4>Crosstab Format</h4>
262  * As explained, in the 
263  * <i>crosstab</i> format,
264  * the separation is physical, structural, unchangeable.
265  * <p>
266  * Remember, however,
267  * that the the "categories" 
268  * <i>physical group</i> is defined above as
269  * "the first 
270  * <i>N</i> columns are rows properties".
271  * By default, 
272  * <i>N</i> is determined as the number of initial, consecutive columns with a "string" type.
273  * If that is not the case, option {@link #dataCategoriesCount} allows stating otherwise.
274  * 
275  * <h4>Relational Format</h4>
276  * In the 
277  * <i>relational</i> format, however,
278  * the separation between "series" and "categories" is not physical, but, simply, convenient.
279  * As you'll see below, the separation helps in automatically loading data into common CCC's dimensions.
280  * <p>
281  * By default,
282  * when a data source contains a single discrete column,
283  * it is a considered a column of the "categories" 
284  * <i>physical group</i>.
285  * Otherwise, if it contains more discrete columns,
286  * the first is considered of the "series" 
287  * <i>physical group</i>,
288  * and all the remaining of the "categories" 
289  * <i>physical group</i>.
290  * This division is arbitrary.
291  * If you want more control, the option {@link #dataCategoriesCount}
292  * allows limiting the number of columns globbed by the "categories" 
293  * <i>physical group</i>.
294  * 
295  * <h4>Series in Rows, please</h4>
296  * It is common enough to want to swap the columns of the "series" and "categories" 
297  * <i>physical groups</i>.
298  * The option {@link #seriesInRows} exists for just that.
299  * 
300  * <h3>Logical Table</h3>
301  * The 
302  * <i>logical table</i>, or, in some contexts, the 
303  * <i>logical row</i>,
304  * is a reorganization of the source data
305  * into a logical format in which columns
306  * are properties of the underlying described entity
307  * and each entity is described in a single row.
308  * This is true, independently of the data source format being 
309  * <i>crosstab</i> or 
310  * <i>relational</i>.
311  * <p>
312  * In the 
313  * <i>relational</i> format, this is already the case.
314  * In the 
315  * <i>crosstab</i> format, however, a logical row contains information
316  * from one of the source rows and one of the source "columns" columns.
317  * <p>
318  * Apart from this restructuring,
319  * the columns of a logical row are also organized according to their
320  * source 
321  * <i>physical group</i>:
322  * 
323  * <style>
324  * .logicalrow {
325  * border-spacing: 0;
326  * margin: 1em 0;
327  * }
328  * .logicalrow td {
329  * border:  solid 1px;
330  * padding: 5px;
331  * }
332  * </style>
333  * 
334  * <table class='logicalrow' style='font-style: italic;'>
335  * 
336  * <tr>
337  * 
338  * <td>series</td>
339  * 
340  * <td>categories</td>
341  * 
342  * <td>measures</td>
343  * </tr>
344  * </table>
345  * <p>
346  * Because of this reordering,
347  * in the 
348  * <i>relational</i> format,
349  * the logical row can differ from the source row,
350  * when, in the latter,
351  * the columns of type "string" are not all before the columns of type "number".
352  * 
353  * <h3>Default Dimension Mapping</h3>
354  * Many chart types,
355  * like the pie, bar and point family, heat grid and box plot,
356  * automatically define and load dimensions —
357  * CCC's data column concept —
358  * for each of the 
359  * <i>logical table</i>'s 
360  * <i>physical groups</i>,
361  * with names from the corresponding 
362  * <i>dimension groups</i>:
363  * "series", "category" and "value". For example,
364  * if there are two columns of the "series" 
365  * <i>physical group</i>,
366  * two of the "categories" 
367  * <i>physical group</i> and
368  * one of the "measures" 
369  * <i>physical group</i>,
370  * the logical row would have its columns mapped
371  * to dimensions in the following way:
372  * 
373  * <table class='logicalrow'>
374  * 
375  * <tr>
376  * 
377  * <td>series</td>
378  * 
379  * <td>series2</td>
380  * 
381  * <td>category</td>
382  * 
383  * <td>category2</td>
384  * 
385  * <td>value</td>
386  * </tr>
387  * </table>
388  * <p>
389  * Other chart types,
390  * like the metric-point, bullet, sunburst, treemap charts,
391  * only rely on the discrete/continuous separation of the 
392  * <i>logical table</i> columns
393  * and automatically generate dimensions, from available columns, in other custom ways.
394  * See each chart type's options documentation page for information on its data format.
395  * 
396  * <h3>Explicit Dimension Mapping</h3>
397  * Whenever the default dimension mapping does not satisfy your needs,
398  * the {@link #readers} option allows mapping each position of the
399  * 
400  * <i>logical row</i> explicitly and independently.
401  * <p>
402  * For example, one could obtain the mapping:
403  * 
404  * <table class='logicalrow'>
405  * 
406  * <tr>
407  * 
408  * <td>category</td>
409  * 
410  * <td>series</td>
411  * 
412  * <td>series2</td>
413  * 
414  * <td>value</td>
415  * 
416  * <td>category2</td>
417  * </tr>
418  * </table>
419  * by specifying the following 
420  * <i>readers</i> value:
421  * 
422  * <pre>
423  * {
424  *     readers: ["category", "series", "series2", "value", "category2"]
425  * }
426  * 
427  * </pre>
428  * Another use of the 
429  * <i>readers</i> option is to be able to
430  * specify business names for the names of dimensions.
431  * For example, for the last crosstab format example,
432  * "crosstab dataset with two properties in every group",
433  * one would achieve the same effect, but using business dimension names,
434  * with the mapping:
435  * 
436  * <table class='logicalrow'>
437  * 
438  * <tr>
439  * 
440  * <td>city</td>
441  * 
442  * <td>orderState</td>
443  * 
444  * <td>date</td>
445  * 
446  * <td>family</td>
447  * 
448  * <td>quantity</td>
449  * 
450  * <td>sales</td>
451  * </tr>
452  * </table>
453  * by specifying the following 
454  * <i>readers</i> and probable 
455  * <i>visual roles</i> values:
456  * 
457  * <pre>
458  * {
459  *     readers: ["city", "orderState", "date", "family", "quantity", "sales"],
460  *     visualRoles: {
461  *         series:   "city, orderState",
462  *         category: "date, family",
463  *         value:    "quantity"
464  *     }
465  * }
466  * 
467  * </pre>
468  * 
469  * @class
470  * @abstract
471  */
472 pvc.options.charts.BasicChart = function(){};
473         
474         
475         
476         
477 /**
478  * A callback function that is called
479  * when the user clicks on a visual element.
480  * 
481  * @returns {undefined}
482  * @method
483  * @this pvc.visual.Context
484  * @param {pvc.visual.Scene} scene
485  * The scene associated with the visual item.
486  * 
487  * @category Chart > Actions
488  */
489 pvc.options.charts.BasicChart.prototype.clickAction = function(){};
490 /**
491  * A callback function that is called
492  * before the chart is rendered,
493  * but after if has been pre-rendered.
494  * <p>
495  * You can use this action to:
496  * 
497  * <ul>
498  * 
499  * <li>use the 
500  * <i>mark events</i> API on time-series categorical charts</li>
501  * 
502  * <li>extend in special ways the already created protovis marks.</li>
503  * </ul>
504  * 
505  * @returns {undefined}
506  * @method
507  * @this pvc.visual.Context
508  * @param {pvc.visual.Scene} scene
509  * The scene associated with the visual item.
510  * 
511  * @category Chart > Actions
512  */
513 pvc.options.charts.BasicChart.prototype.renderCallback = function(){};
514 /**
515  * A callback function that is called after the chart has finished rendering, including any animations.
516  * 
517  * @returns {undefined}
518  * @method
519  * @this pvc.visual.Context
520  * @param {pvc.visual.Scene} scene
521  * The scene associated with the visual item.
522  * 
523  * @category Chart > Actions
524  */
525 pvc.options.charts.BasicChart.prototype.renderedCallback = function(){};
526 /**
527  * An array of dimensions calculations.
528  * <p>
529  * Can be specified to calculate the values of certain dimensions.
530  * 
531  * @type list(pvc.options.DimensionsCalculation)
532  * @category Chart > Data
533  */
534 pvc.options.charts.BasicChart.prototype.calculations = undefined;
535 /**
536  * A map whose keys are
537  * the dimension type group names and whose values are
538  * the default dimension type group options.
539  * <p>
540  * A dimension type group is
541  * a group of dimension types
542  * that have a common non-numeric prefix in its name.
543  * <p>
544  * This property does not define any dimension types, per si,
545  * but allows specifying default values
546  * for dimension types of a group,
547  * that apply in case they are effectively used.
548  * 
549  * @type map(string : pvc.options.DimensionType)
550  * @category Chart > Data
551  */
552 pvc.options.charts.BasicChart.prototype.dimensionGroups = undefined;
553 /**
554  * A map whose keys are
555  * the dimension type names and whose values are
556  * the dimension type options.
557  * <p>
558  * You don't need to define dimensions
559  * unless you want to change their name or properties.
560  * Charts automatically define default dimensions
561  * to satisfy their visual roles' requirements.
562  * <p>
563  * Dimension options can be partial,
564  * so that it is possible to override only certain options.
565  * 
566  * @type map(string : pvc.options.DimensionType)
567  * @category Chart > Data
568  */
569 pvc.options.charts.BasicChart.prototype.dimensions = undefined;
570 /**
571  * The chart's format provider.
572  * 
573  * @type pvc.options.format.FormatProvider
574  * @category Chart > Data
575  */
576 pvc.options.charts.BasicChart.prototype.format = undefined;
577 /**
578  * The separator used to join the labels of the values of
579  * a multi-dimensional visual role.
580  * <p>
581  * For example, if a visual role,
582  * has the dimensions "Territory" and "ProductType",
583  * a compound value could be shown as "EMEA ~ Classic Cars".
584  * <p>
585  * See also {@link #dataSeparator}.
586  * 
587  * @type string
588  * @default ' ~ '
589  * @category Chart > Data
590  */
591 pvc.options.charts.BasicChart.prototype.groupedLabelSep = undefined;
592 /**
593  * Indicates if datums
594  * whose value in every measure dimension is null
595  * are ignored.
596  * <p>
597  * A dimension is considered a measure dimension if
598  * there is at least one measure visual role currently bound to it.
599  * 
600  * @type boolean
601  * @default true
602  * @category Chart > Data
603  */
604 pvc.options.charts.BasicChart.prototype.ignoreNulls = undefined;
605 /**
606  * A function that formats the 
607  * <i>non-null</i> values of 
608  * <i>numeric</i> dimensions.
609  * <p>
610  * When this property is specified,
611  * it sets also the
612  * {@link pvc.options.format.FormatProvider#number} format of the chart's format provider,
613  * {@link pvc.options.charts.BasicChart#format}.
614  * Consequently, its value is inherited by the number dimension types'
615  * {@link pvc.options.DimensionType#format}.
616  * <p>
617  * Conversely, if the chart's format provider
618  * {@link pvc.options.format.FormatProvider#number} format is specified,
619  * its value sets this property, {@link pvc.options.charts.BasicChart#valueFormat}.
620  * <p>
621  * When both are specified, the one in the chart's format provider has precedence.
622  * <p>
623  * Note: in a previous CCC version this property applied only to
624  * dimensions named 
625  * <tt>value</tt>, 
626  * <tt>value2</tt>, etc.
627  * It now applies to any numeric dimensions.
628  *

637  * @category Chart > Data

651 /**
652  * The number of columns of the "categories" 
653  * <i>physical group</i> that the data source contains.
654  * 
655  * <h4>Relational format</h4>
656  * Allows splitting the discrete columns between the
657  * "series" and "category" 
658  * <i>physical groups</i>, in a custom way.
659  * <p>
660  * By default, if only a single discrete column exists, it is a "category".
661  * Otherwise, the first column is a "series" column and all the remaining are "category" columns.
662  * 
663  * <h4>Crosstab format</h4>
664  * This is taken to be the number of consecutive discrete columns,
665  * from the first, or 
666  * <tt>1</tt>, if there are none.
667  * 
668  * @type number
669  * @category Chart > Data Source
670  */

675  * as defaults for the labels of dimensions that are directly
676  * loaded from those columns.
677  * <p>
678  * The capability to use the data source's provided metadata labels
679  * is most useful in the relational format, i.e., when {@link #crosstabMode} is 
680  * <tt>false</tt>.
681  * The crosstab format does not provide metadata information for the series/columns data.
682  * Also, only when both {@link #isMultiValued} and
683  * {@link #dataMeasuresInColumns} are 
684  * <tt>true</tt>,
685  * is there label information for the measures metadata.

696  * <tt>true</tt>.
697  * <p>
698  * When 
699  * <tt>true</tt>,
700  * the data source contains columns for each combination of "series" columns' values 
701  * <b>and</b> measure dimension.

1740 /**
1741  * The data part value of the subset of data that the plot consumes.
1742  * <p>
1743  * This option can only be used in code,
1744  * from within {@link pvc.options.charts.BasicChart#plots}.
1745  * <p>
1746  * By default, for internal plots,
1747  * like 
1748  * <i>main</i> and 
1749  * <i>plot2</i>,
1750  * data is partitioned into two data parts,
1751  * 
1752  * <tt>"0"</tt> and 
1753  * <tt>"1"</tt>,
1754  * respectively,
1755  * according to the chart's
1756  * 
1757  * <tt>plot2Series</tt>, or 
1758  * <tt>plot2SeriesIndexes</tt>, options
1759  * (depending on the chart type,
1760  * {@link pvc.options.charts.BarChart#plot2Series}, or
1761  * {@link pvc.options.charts.PointChart#plot2Series}).
1762  * <p>
1763  * The internal 
1764  * <i>trend</i> plot, by default, represents the data part value 
1765  * <tt>"trend"</tt>.
1766  * <p>
1767  * For external plots, the default data part value is 
1768  * <tt>"0"</tt>.
1769  * <p>
1770  * See {@link pvc.options.charts.BasicChart#dataPartRole} for more information.
1771  * 
1772  * @type string
1773  * @category Data
1774  */
1775 pvc.options.plots.Plot.prototype.dataPart = undefined;
1776 /**
1777  * The name of the plot being defined or configured.
1778  * <p>
1779  * This option can only be used in code,
1780  * from within {@link pvc.options.charts.BasicChart#plots}.
1781  * <p>
1782  * To configure an internal plot, its reserved name is specified:
1783  * 
1784  * <dl>
1785  * 
1786  * <dt>
1787  * <i>main</i></dt>
1788  * 
1789  * <dd>the main plot of a chart; for example, a bar chart has a main plot of type 
1790  * <tt>bar</tt></dd>
1791  * 
1792  * <dt>
1793  * <i>plot2</i></dt>
1794  * 
1795  * <dd>the special second plot;
1796  * this is the plot that, in applicable chart types,
1797  * is activated when the option 
1798  * <i>plot2</i> is 
1799  * <tt>true</tt>;
1800  * configuring the second plot this way implicitly activates it,
1801  * and the value of option 
1802  * <i>plot2</i> is ignored.
1803  * </dd>
1804  * 
1805  * <dt>
1806  * <i>trend</i></dt>
1807  * 
1808  * <dd>the special trend plot;
1809  * this is the plot that, in applicable chart types,
1810  * is activated when other plots specify one of the options 
1811  * <i>trend</i> or 
1812  * <i>trendType</i>.
1813  * </dd>
1814  * </dl>
1815  * <p>
1816  * In this case, if {@link pvc.options.plots.Plot#type} is also specified,
1817  * it must match the plot type of the corresponding internal plot.
1818  * <p>
1819  * To define a new plot, specify a {@link pvc.options.plots.Plot#type}
1820  * and, no name, or one that is not reserved.
1821  * <p>
1822  * The name of a plot cannot have dot (".") character in it.
1823  * 
1824  * @type string
1825  * @category General
1826  */
1827 pvc.options.plots.Plot.prototype.name = undefined;

2077 /**
2078  * Fixates the height of each 
2079  * <i>small</i> chart, in pixel units or as a percentage.
2080  * <p>
2081  * A value of type 
2082  * <tt>number</tt>,
2083  * or of type 
2084  * <tt>string</tt>, but with numeric content,
2085  * is interpreted as being in pixel units.
2086  * <p>
2087  * A value of type 
2088  * <tt>string</tt>,
2089  * with numeric content that is suffixed by a "%" character,
2090  * is interpreted as a percentage of the initially available content height.
2091  * <p>
2092  * This property may cause the 
2093  * <i>small multiples</i> chart
2094  * to take up a greater width than the one specified in {@link #height}.
2095  * <p>
2096  * When this property is unspecified,
2097  * its value depends on the evaluation of the
2098  * {@link #smallWidth} property,
2099  * which may impose it a value.
2100  * If after the evaluation of {@link #smallWidth}
2101  * this property remains unspecified,
2102  * it is determined as follows.
2103  * <p>
2104  * If the layout will have a single column
2105  * and the property {@link #multiChartSingleColFillsHeight}
2106  * is 
2107  * <tt>true</tt> (it is by default)
2108  * then the height will be the initially available content height.
2109  * <p>
2110  * If the layout will have a single row
2111  * and the property {@link #multiChartSingleRowFillsHeight}
2112  * is 
2113  * <tt>true</tt> (it is by default)
2114  * then the height will be the initially available content height.
2115  * <p>
2116  * Otherwise, the property {@link #smallAspectRatio} is
2117  * used to determine the height of the small chart from its determined width.
2118  * <p>
2119  * The aspect ratio is defaulted to a value that depends on the chart type,
2120  * but is something around 
2121  * <tt>4/3</tt>.
2122  * 
2123  * @type number|string
2124  * @category Chart - Multi > Layout
2125  */
2126 pvc.options.charts.PieChart.prototype.smallHeight = undefined;
2127 /**
2128  * The margins of a 
2129  * <i>small</i> chart.
2130  * <p>
2131  * See {@link pvc.options.varia.Sides} for information about
2132  * the different supported data types.
2133  * 
2134  * @type number|string|pvc.options.varia.Sides
2135  * @default '2%'
2136  * @category Chart - Multi > Layout
2137  */
2138 pvc.options.charts.PieChart.prototype.smallMargins = undefined;
2139 /**
2140  * The paddings of a 
2141  * <i>small</i> chart.
2142  * <p>
2143  * See {@link pvc.options.varia.Sides} for information about
2144  * the different supported data types.
2145  * 
2146  * @type number|string|pvc.options.varia.Sides
2147  * @default 0
2148  * @category Chart - Multi > Layout
2149  */
2150 pvc.options.charts.PieChart.prototype.smallPaddings = undefined;
2151 /**
2152  * Fixates the width of each 
2153  * <i>small</i> chart, in pixel units or as a percentage.
2154  * <p>
2155  * A value of type 
2156  * <tt>number</tt>,
2157  * or of type 
2158  * <tt>string</tt>, but with numeric content,
2159  * is interpreted as being in pixel units.
2160  * <p>
2161  * A value of type 
2162  * <tt>string</tt>,
2163  * with numeric content that is suffixed by a "%" character,
2164  * is interpreted as a percentage of the initially available content width.
2165  * <p>
2166  * This property may cause the 
2167  * <i>small multiples</i> chart
2168  * to take up a greater width than the one specified in {@link #width}.
2169  * <p>
2170  * When this property is unspecified,
2171  * a specified finite value, or a defaulted value, of the property {@link #multiChartColumnsMax} is
2172  * used to determine it:
2173  * by dividing the initially available content width
2174  * by the maximum number of charts in a row that 
2175  * <i>actually</i> occur
2176  * (so that if there are less small charts than
2177  * the maximum that can be placed in a row,
2178  * these, nevertheless, take up the whole width).
2179  * <p>
2180  * When an infinite value is specified for
2181  * {@link #multiChartColumnsMax},
2182  * the small charts are laid out in a single row,
2183  * and so the width is calculated from the height {@link #smallHeight},
2184  * using the aspect ratio {@link #smallAspectRatio}.
2185  * The height is defaulted to the initially available content height.
2186  * The aspect ratio is defaulted to a value that depends on the chart type,
2187  * but is something around 
2188  * <tt>4/3</tt>.
2189  * The width is then calculated.
2190  * 
2191  * @type number|string
2192  * @category Chart - Multi > Layout
2193  */
2194 pvc.options.charts.PieChart.prototype.smallWidth = undefined;

2211 /**
2212  * The 
2213  * <tt>multiChart</tt> visual role is a chart-level visual role that
2214  * allows turning a chart into a 
2215  * <i>small multiples</i> chart,
2216  * {@link http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Small_multiple}.
2217  * <p>
2218  * Almost all main chart types support being shown
2219  * as a small multiples chart.
2220  * Currently, the exceptions are the charts:
2221  * 
2222  * <i>Heat Grid</i>,
2223  * 
2224  * <i>Bullet</i>,
2225  * 
2226  * <i>Data Tree</i> and
2227  * 
2228  * <i>Parallel Coordinates</i>.
2229  * <p>
2230  * The 
2231  * <tt>multiChart</tt> visual role
2232  * can be bound to any number of dimensions,
2233  * that are, or will be turned into, discrete.
2234  * <p>
2235  * The 
2236  * <tt>multiChart</tt> visual role automatically binds to
2237  * every dimension whose name has the 
2238  * <tt>multiChart</tt> prefix.
2239  * <p>
2240  * One 
2241  * <i>small</i> chart is generated per
2242  * unique combination of the values of the bound dimensions
2243  * that is present in the source data.
2244  * Each small chart then receives as its data
2245  * the partition of the source data that shares its
2246  * unique combination of values.
2247  * <p>
2248  * See {@link pvc.options.VisualRole}
2249  * for more information on supported data types.
2250  * 
2251  * @type string|pvc.options.VisualRole
2252  * @category Chart > Visual Roles
2253  */
2254 pvc.options.charts.PieChart.prototype.multiChartRole = undefined;

3044 /**
3045  * The options documentation class of the 
3046  * <b>Treemap</b> chart.
3047  * <p>
3048  * Treemap charts display hierarchical data using nested rectangles.
3049  * They excel in revealing the location of valuable areas buried in a deep hierarchy.
3050  * 
3051  * <p>
3052  * The root data node is represented by the root rectangle,
3053  * which occupies the whole plot area.
3054  * </p>
3055  * 
3056  * <p>
3057  * The area of a leaf node is proportional to
3058  * the percentage of the 
3059  * <i>size</i> dimension over its sibling nodes.
3060  * The area of a non-leaf node is the sum of the areas of its child nodes.
3061  * If no 
3062  * <i>size</i> dimension is specified,
3063  * then all sibling-leaf nodes will have identical areas.
3064  * </p>
3065  * 
3066  * <p>
3067  * Rectangles are usually colored so that siblings have the same color.
3068  * This way, it is easy to identify sibling nodes and compare their relative sizes.
3069  * In this way, the colors that are shown are the colors of leaf nodes' parents.
3070  * </p>
3071  * 
3072  * <h3>Default Data Format</h3>
3073  * <p>
3074  * For general information on the supported 
3075  * <b>data formats</b>
3076  * see {@link pvc.options.charts.BasicChart}.
3077  * <p>
3078  * The treemap chart employs a non-default 
3079  * <i>logical row</i> to dimensions mapping:
3080  * 
3081  * <ol>
3082  * 
3083  * <li>
3084  * All of the free 
3085  * <i>discrete</i> columns of the 
3086  * <i>logical table</i>
3087  * generate and load free dimensions of the "category" 
3088  * <i>dimension group</i>:
3089  * "category", "category2", "category4", ...
3090  * </li>
3091  * 
3092  * <li>The first free 
3093  * <i>continuous</i> column of the 
3094  * <i>logical table</i>
3095  * generates and loads the "size" dimension, if free.
3096  * </li>
3097  * </ol>
3098  * 
3099  * <style>
3100  * .dataformat {
3101  * border-spacing: 0;
3102  * margin: 1em 0;
3103  * }
3104  * .dataformat td {
3105  * border:  solid 1px;
3106  * padding: 3px;
3107  * width:   80px;
3108  * }
3109  * </style>
3110  * <p>
3111  * The following is a possible default layout and dimension assignment:
3112  * 
3113  * <table class='dataformat'>
3114  * 
3115  * <tr>
3116  * <td>
3117  * <b>Index</b></td>
3118  * <td>0</td>
3119  * <td>1</td>
3120  * <td>2</td>
3121  * <td>3</td></tr>
3122  * 
3123  * <tr>
3124  * <td>
3125  * <b>Dimension</b></td>
3126  * <td>category</td>
3127  * <td>category2</td>
3128  * <td>category4</td>
3129  * <td>size</td></tr>
3130  * 
3131  * <tr>
3132  * <td>
3133  * <b>DataType</b></td>
3134  * <td>string</td>
3135  * <td>string</td>
3136  * <td>string</td>
3137  * <td>number</td></tr>
3138  * </table>
3139  * <p>
3140  * Note that the dimension "category3" was not assigned to index 3, hypothetically because it was not free (was explicitly bound to some index, using a reader).
3141  * 
3142  * <h3>How To Bind The Color Visual Role</h3>
3143  * The Treemap's 
3144  * <tt>color</tt> visual role can only be bound to discrete dimensions.
3145  * <p>
3146  * By default, the 
3147  * <tt>color</tt> role is bound to the
3148  * dimensions of the 
3149  * <tt>category</tt> role — its default 
3150  * <i>source role</i>.
3151  * <p>
3152  * The 
3153  * <tt>color</tt> role can also be bound to other discrete dimension(s), explicitly.
3154  * 
3155  * <h4>Solution 1</h4>
3156  * One possibility is to 
3157  * <i>switch</i> one of the automatically fed "category" dimensions
3158  * to the 
3159  * <tt>color</tt> visual role.
3160  * For example:
3161  * 
3162  * <pre>
3163  * categoryRole: "category", // steal one here
3164  * colorRole:    "category2" // and assign it here
3165  * 
3166  * </pre>
3167  * 
3168  * <h4>Solution 2</h4>
3169  * Another possibility is to configure the {@link pvc.options.charts.BasicChart#readers}
3170  * with the actual layout, using the default dimension names of
3171  * the desired visual roles.
3172  * For example:
3173  * 
3174  * <pre>
3175  * readers: "color, category, category2, size"
3176  * 
3177  * </pre>
3178  * 
3179  * <h4>Solution 3</h4>
3180  * Of course, you can (and probably should) use actual business names for the names of dimensions.
3181  * To that end, both the readers and the visual roles' mappings need to be specified:
3182  * 
3183  * <pre>
3184  * readers:      "orderType, productFamily, productType, sales"
3185  * categoryRole: "productFamily, productType",
3186  * colorRole:    "orderType",
3187  * sizeRole:     "sales"
3188  * 
3189  * </pre>
3190  * 
3191  * <h3></h3>
3192  * 
3193  * @class
3194  * @extends pvc.options.charts.Chart
3195  */
3196 pvc.options.charts.TreemapChart = function(){};

3303  * <i>content panel</i> of a 
3304  * <i>small</i> chart.
3305  * <p>
3306  * See {@link pvc.options.varia.Sides} for information about
3307  * the different supported data types.
3308  * 
3309  * @type number|string|pvc.options.varia.Sides
3310  * @default 0
3311  * @category Chart - Multi > Layout
3312  */
3313 pvc.options.charts.TreemapChart.prototype.smallContentPaddings = undefined;
3314 /**
3315  * Fixates the height of each 
3316  * <i>small</i> chart, in pixel units or as a percentage.
3317  * <p>
3318  * A value of type 
3319  * <tt>number</tt>,
3320  * or of type 
3321  * <tt>string</tt>, but with numeric content,
3322  * is interpreted as being in pixel units.
3323  * <p>
3324  * A value of type 
3325  * <tt>string</tt>,
3326  * with numeric content that is suffixed by a "%" character,
3327  * is interpreted as a percentage of the initially available content height.
3328  * <p>
3329  * This property may cause the 
3330  * <i>small multiples</i> chart
3331  * to take up a greater width than the one specified in {@link #height}.
3332  * <p>
3333  * When this property is unspecified,
3334  * its value depends on the evaluation of the
3335  * {@link #smallWidth} property,
3336  * which may impose it a value.
3337  * If after the evaluation of {@link #smallWidth}
3338  * this property remains unspecified,
3339  * it is determined as follows.
3340  * <p>
3341  * If the layout will have a single column
3342  * and the property {@link #multiChartSingleColFillsHeight}
3343  * is 
3344  * <tt>true</tt> (it is by default)
3345  * then the height will be the initially available content height.
3346  * <p>
3347  * If the layout will have a single row
3348  * and the property {@link #multiChartSingleRowFillsHeight}
3349  * is 
3350  * <tt>true</tt> (it is by default)
3351  * then the height will be the initially available content height.
3352  * <p>
3353  * Otherwise, the property {@link #smallAspectRatio} is
3354  * used to determine the height of the small chart from its determined width.
3355  * <p>
3356  * The aspect ratio is defaulted to a value that depends on the chart type,
3357  * but is something around 
3358  * <tt>4/3</tt>.
3359  * 
3360  * @type number|string
3361  * @category Chart - Multi > Layout
3362  */
3363 pvc.options.charts.TreemapChart.prototype.smallHeight = undefined;
3364 /**
3365  * The margins of a 
3366  * <i>small</i> chart.
3367  * <p>
3368  * See {@link pvc.options.varia.Sides} for information about
3369  * the different supported data types.
3370  * 
3371  * @type number|string|pvc.options.varia.Sides
3372  * @default '2%'
3373  * @category Chart - Multi > Layout
3374  */
3375 pvc.options.charts.TreemapChart.prototype.smallMargins = undefined;
3376 /**
3377  * The paddings of a 
3378  * <i>small</i> chart.
3379  * <p>
3380  * See {@link pvc.options.varia.Sides} for information about
3381  * the different supported data types.
3382  * 
3383  * @type number|string|pvc.options.varia.Sides
3384  * @default 0
3385  * @category Chart - Multi > Layout
3386  */
3387 pvc.options.charts.TreemapChart.prototype.smallPaddings = undefined;
3388 /**
3389  * Fixates the width of each 
3390  * <i>small</i> chart, in pixel units or as a percentage.
3391  * <p>
3392  * A value of type 
3393  * <tt>number</tt>,
3394  * or of type 
3395  * <tt>string</tt>, but with numeric content,
3396  * is interpreted as being in pixel units.
3397  * <p>
3398  * A value of type 
3399  * <tt>string</tt>,
3400  * with numeric content that is suffixed by a "%" character,
3401  * is interpreted as a percentage of the initially available content width.
3402  * <p>
3403  * This property may cause the 
3404  * <i>small multiples</i> chart
3405  * to take up a greater width than the one specified in {@link #width}.
3406  * <p>
3407  * When this property is unspecified,
3408  * a specified finite value, or a defaulted value, of the property {@link #multiChartColumnsMax} is
3409  * used to determine it:
3410  * by dividing the initially available content width
3411  * by the maximum number of charts in a row that 
3412  * <i>actually</i> occur
3413  * (so that if there are less small charts than
3414  * the maximum that can be placed in a row,
3415  * these, nevertheless, take up the whole width).
3416  * <p>
3417  * When an infinite value is specified for
3418  * {@link #multiChartColumnsMax},
3419  * the small charts are laid out in a single row,
3420  * and so the width is calculated from the height {@link #smallHeight},
3421  * using the aspect ratio {@link #smallAspectRatio}.
3422  * The height is defaulted to the initially available content height.
3423  * The aspect ratio is defaulted to a value that depends on the chart type,
3424  * but is something around 
3425  * <tt>4/3</tt>.
3426  * The width is then calculated.
3427  * 
3428  * @type number|string
3429  * @category Chart - Multi > Layout
3430  */
3431 pvc.options.charts.TreemapChart.prototype.smallWidth = undefined;
3432 /**
3433  * The indexes of columns of the 
3434  * <i>logical table</i> that are to feed the
3435  * default
3436  * 
3437  * <tt>multiChart</tt>,
3438  * 
3439  * <tt>multiChart2</tt>, ...
3440  * dimensions.
3441  * <p>
3442  * See {@link pvc.options.charts.BasicChart#readers} for related information.
3443  * 
3444  * @type number|string|list(number|string)
3445  * @category Chart > Data Source
3446  */
3447 pvc.options.charts.TreemapChart.prototype.multiChartIndexes = undefined;
3448 /**
3449  * The 
3450  * <tt>multiChart</tt> visual role is a chart-level visual role that
3451  * allows turning a chart into a 
3452  * <i>small multiples</i> chart,
3453  * {@link http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Small_multiple}.
3454  * <p>
3455  * Almost all main chart types support being shown
3456  * as a small multiples chart.
3457  * Currently, the exceptions are the charts:
3458  * 
3459  * <i>Heat Grid</i>,
3460  * 
3461  * <i>Bullet</i>,
3462  * 
3463  * <i>Data Tree</i> and
3464  * 
3465  * <i>Parallel Coordinates</i>.
3466  * <p>
3467  * The 
3468  * <tt>multiChart</tt> visual role
3469  * can be bound to any number of dimensions,
3470  * that are, or will be turned into, discrete.
3471  * <p>
3472  * The 
3473  * <tt>multiChart</tt> visual role automatically binds to
3474  * every dimension whose name has the 
3475  * <tt>multiChart</tt> prefix.
3476  * <p>
3477  * One 
3478  * <i>small</i> chart is generated per
3479  * unique combination of the values of the bound dimensions
3480  * that is present in the source data.
3481  * Each small chart then receives as its data
3482  * the partition of the source data that shares its
3483  * unique combination of values.
3484  * <p>
3485  * See {@link pvc.options.VisualRole}
3486  * for more information on supported data types.
3487  * 
3488  * @type string|pvc.options.VisualRole
3489  * @category Chart > Visual Roles
3490  */
3491 pvc.options.charts.TreemapChart.prototype.multiChartRole = undefined;

3498  * <tt>multiChart</tt> visual role.

3500  * @type pvc.options.panels.ChartTitlePanel
3501  * @category Panels - Multi

3794 pvc.options.plots.TreemapPlot.prototype.valuesOptimizeLegibility = undefined;
3795 /**
3796  * The behavior to apply when the text of a value label does not fit within the bounds of its associated rectangle.
3797  * <p>
3798  * This option applies only when {@link pvc.options.plots.Plot#valuesVisible} is true.
3799  * <p>
3800  * Moreover, it also applies only for certain configurations of value label placement,
3801  * relative to the associated rectangle. Presently, the supported placements are:
3802  * 
3803  * <ul>
3804  * 
3805  * <li>
3806  * <b>non-negative text margin</b>,
3807  * {@link pvc.options.marks.LabelExtensionPoint#textMargin}.
3808  * </li>
3809  * 
3810  * <li>
3811  * <b>horizontal or vertical text</b> —
3812  * Text is horizontal when
3813  * {@link pvc.options.marks.LabelExtensionPoint#textAngle}
3814  * is such that 
3815  * <tt>sin(textAngle) = 0</tt> (example: 
3816  * <tt>0</tt>).
3817  * Text is vertical when
3818  * {@link pvc.options.marks.LabelExtensionPoint#textAngle}
3819  * is such that 
3820  * <tt>cos(textAngle) = 0</tt> (example: 
3821  * <tt>Math.PI/2</tt>, 
3822  * <tt>-Math.PI/2</tt>, 
3823  * <tt>3*Math.PI/2</tt>, ...).
3824  * </li>
3825  * </ul>
3826  * <p>
3827  * When an unsupported placement occurs, the label is shown.
3828  * <p>
3829  * Note that for the purposes of hiding and trimming,
3830  * the value of {@link pvc.options.marks.LabelExtensionPoint#textMargin}
3831  * is used for more that the distance between the anchor points of the label and the rectangle.
3832  * <p>
3833  * It is included as a required margin in all of the sides of the label.
3834  * 
3835  * @type pvc.options.varia.ValuesOverflow
3836  * @default 'hide'
3837  * @category Style
3838  */
3839 pvc.options.plots.TreemapPlot.prototype.valuesOverflow = undefined;

3857 /**
3858  * The extension points of the treemap plot type.
3859  * <p>
3860  * Plot extension points can be specified:
3861  * 
3862  * <ul>
3863  * 
3864  * <li>at the plot level, in the 
3865  * <i>extensionPoints</i> property,
3866  * without need to prefix the extension point with the
3867  * plot id or name.
3868  * </li>
3869  * 
3870  * <li>at the plot options level, directly,
3871  * without need to prefix the extension point with the
3872  * plot id or name.
3873  * </li>
3874  * 
3875  * <li>
3876  * if it is an internal plot (
3877  * <i>main</i>, 
3878  * <i>plot2</i> or 
3879  * <i>trend</i>),
3880  * at the chart options level, directly.
3881  * </li>
3882  * </ul>
3883  * <p>
3884  * To use an extension point you must find its full name, by joining:
3885  * 
3886  * <ol>
3887  * 
3888  * <li>plot property name (ex: 
3889  * <tt>treemap</tt>)</li>
3890  * 
3891  * <li>extension property (ex: 
3892  * <tt>leaf</tt>)</li>
3893  * 
3894  * <li>the "_" character</li>
3895  * 
3896  * <li>extension sub-property (ex: 
3897  * <tt>strokeStyle</tt>)</li>
3898  * </ol>
3899  * and obtaining, for the examples, the camel-cased name: 
3900  * <tt>treemapLeaf_strokeStyle</tt>
3901  * (see {@link http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CamelCase}).
3902  * <p>
3903  * The extension points of the 
3904  * <i>main plot</i> of a chart
3905  * may be used without the plot property name prefix.
3906  * In the example, when the 
3907  * <tt>treemap</tt> plot is the main plot,
3908  * the extension point can be written as 
3909  * <tt>leaf_strokeStyle</tt>.
3910  * 
3911  * @class
3912  */
3913 pvc.options.ext.TreemapPlotExtensionPoints = function(){};

4009 /**
4010  * The options documentation class of the 
4011  * <b>Bullet</b> chart.
4012  * <p>
4013  * This chart type was only partially updated,
4014  * to support some of the new CCC v.2 features.
4015  * 
4016  * <h3>Default Data Format</h3>
4017  * For general information on the supported 
4018  * <b>data formats</b>
4019  * see {@link pvc.options.charts.BasicChart}.
4020  * <p>
4021  * Note that, unlike most chart types,
4022  * the bullet chart has a default
4023  * {@link #dataTypeCheckingMode}
4024  * of {@link pvc.options.varia.DataTypeCheckingMode#Extended}.
4025  * <p>
4026  * Also, the bullet chart employs a non-default 
4027  * <i>logical row</i> to dimensions mapping:
4028  * 
4029  * <ol>
4030  * 
4031  * <li>The first free 
4032  * <i>discrete</i> column of the 
4033  * <i>logical table</i>
4034  * generates and loads the "title" dimension, if free.
4035  * </li>
4036  * 
4037  * <li>The second free 
4038  * <i>discrete</i> column of the 
4039  * <i>logical table</i>
4040  * generates and loads the "subTitle" dimension, if free.
4041  * </li>
4042  * 
4043  * <li>Free 
4044  * <i>continuous</i> columns of the 
4045  * <i>logical table</i> generate and load,
4046  * in order, skipping the dimension when not-free,
4047  * the following numeric 
4048  * <i>dimensions</i>:
4049  * 
4050  * <ol>
4051  * 
4052  * <li>value</li>
4053  * 
4054  * <li>marker</li>
4055  * 
4056  * <li>range</li>
4057  * 
4058  * <li>range2</li>
4059  * 
4060  * <li>range3</li>
4061  * 
4062  * <li>...</li>
4063  * </ol>

4596 /**
4597  * The extension points of the bullet plot type.
4598  * <p>
4599  * Plot extension points can be specified:
4600  * 
4601  * <ul>
4602  * 
4603  * <li>at the plot level, in the 
4604  * <i>extensionPoints</i> property,
4605  * without need to prefix the extension point with the
4606  * plot id or name.
4607  * </li>
4608  * 
4609  * <li>at the plot options level, directly,
4610  * without need to prefix the extension point with the
4611  * plot id or name.
4612  * </li>
4613  * 
4614  * <li>
4615  * if it is an internal plot (
4616  * <i>main</i>, 
4617  * <i>plot2</i> or 
4618  * <i>trend</i>),
4619  * at the chart options level, directly.
4620  * </li>
4621  * </ul>
4622  * <p>
4623  * This 
4624  * <b>bullet</b> chart type was only partially updated,
4625  * to support some of the new CCC v.2 features.
4626  * <p>
4627  * To use an extension point you must find its full name, by joining:
4628  * 
4629  * <ol>
4630  * 
4631  * <li>plot property name (ex: 
4632  * <tt>bullet</tt>)</li>
4633  * 
4634  * <li>extension property (ex: 
4635  * <tt>panel</tt>)</li>
4636  * 
4637  * <li>the "_" character</li>
4638  * 
4639  * <li>extension sub-property (ex: 
4640  * <tt>strokeStyle</tt>)</li>
4641  * </ol>

4841 /**
4842  * The options documentation class of the 
4843  * <b>Sunburst</b> chart.
4844  * <p>
4845  * Sunburst charts display hierarchical data using series of rings.
4846  * They are great to quickly drill down trough a deep hierarchy, while still maintaining the notion
4847  * of its dimension.
4848  * 
4849  * <p>
4850  * Each ring represents the children of the ring it
4851  * encloses and the area of each slice corresponds to its 
4852  * <i>value</i>.
4853  * </p>
4854  * 
4855  * <h3>Default Data Format</h3>
4856  * For general information on the supported 
4857  * <b>data formats</b>
4858  * see {@link pvc.options.charts.BasicChart}.
4859  * <p>
4860  * The sunburst chart employs a non-default 
4861  * <i>logical row</i> to dimensions mapping:
4862  * 
4863  * <ol>
4864  * 
4865  * <li>
4866  * All of the free 
4867  * <i>discrete</i> columns of the 
4868  * <i>logical table</i>
4869  * generate and load free dimensions of the "category" 
4870  * <i>dimension group</i>:
4871  * "category", "category2", "category4", ...
4872  * </li>
4873  * 
4874  * <li>The first free 
4875  * <i>continuous</i> column of the 
4876  * <i>logical table</i>
4877  * generates and loads the "size" dimension, if free.
4878  * </li>
4879  * </ol>
4880  * 
4881  * <style>
4882  * .dataformat {
4883  * border-spacing: 0;
4884  * margin: 1em 0;
4885  * }
4886  * .dataformat td {
4887  * border:  solid 1px;
4888  * padding: 3px;
4889  * width:   80px;
4890  * }
4891  * </style>
4892  * <p>
4893  * The following is a possible default layout and dimension assignment:
4894  * 
4895  * <table class='dataformat'>
4896  * 
4897  * <tr>
4898  * <td>
4899  * <b>Index</b></td>
4900  * <td>0</td>
4901  * <td>1</td>
4902  * <td>2</td>
4903  * <td>3</td></tr>
4904  * 
4905  * <tr>
4906  * <td>
4907  * <b>Dimension</b></td>
4908  * <td>category</td>
4909  * <td>category2</td>
4910  * <td>category4</td>
4911  * <td>size</td></tr>
4912  * 
4913  * <tr>
4914  * <td>
4915  * <b>DataType</b></td>
4916  * <td>string</td>
4917  * <td>string</td>
4918  * <td>string</td>
4919  * <td>number</td></tr>
4920  * </table>
4921  * <p>
4922  * Note that the dimension "category3" was not assigned to index 3, hypothetically because it was not free (was explicitly bound to some index, using a reader).
4923  * 
4924  * <h3>How To Bind The Color Visual Role</h3>
4925  * The Sunburst's 
4926  * <tt>color</tt> visual role can only be bound to discrete dimensions.
4927  * <p>
4928  * By default, the 
4929  * <tt>color</tt> role is bound to the
4930  * dimensions of the 
4931  * <tt>category</tt> role — its default 
4932  * <i>source role</i>.
4933  * <p>
4934  * The 
4935  * <tt>color</tt> role can also be bound to other discrete dimension(s), explicitly.
4936  * 
4937  * <h4>Solution 1</h4>
4938  * One possibility is to 
4939  * <i>switch</i> one of the automatically fed "category" dimensions
4940  * to the 
4941  * <tt>color</tt> visual role.
4942  * For example:
4943  * 
4944  * <pre>
4945  * categoryRole: "category", // steal one here
4946  * colorRole:    "category2" // and assign it here
4947  * 
4948  * </pre>
4949  * 
4950  * <h4>Solution 2</h4>
4951  * Another possibility is to configure the {@link pvc.options.charts.BasicChart#readers}
4952  * with the actual layout, using the default dimension names of
4953  * the desired visual roles.
4954  * For example:
4955  * 
4956  * <pre>
4957  * readers: "color, category, category2, size"
4958  * 
4959  * </pre>
4960  * 
4961  * <h4>Solution 3</h4>
4962  * Of course, you can (and probably should) use actual business names for the names of dimensions.
4963  * To that end, both the readers and the visual roles' mappings need to be specified:
4964  * 
4965  * <pre>
4966  * readers:      "orderType, productFamily, productType, sales"
4967  * categoryRole: "productFamily, productType",
4968  * colorRole:    "orderType",
4969  * sizeRole:     "sales"
4970  * 
4971  * </pre>
4972  * 
4973  * @class
4974  * @extends pvc.options.charts.Chart
4975  */
4976 pvc.options.charts.SunburstChart = function(){};

5094 /**
5095  * Fixates the height of each 
5096  * <i>small</i> chart, in pixel units or as a percentage.
5097  * <p>
5098  * A value of type 
5099  * <tt>number</tt>,
5100  * or of type 
5101  * <tt>string</tt>, but with numeric content,
5102  * is interpreted as being in pixel units.
5103  * <p>
5104  * A value of type 
5105  * <tt>string</tt>,
5106  * with numeric content that is suffixed by a "%" character,
5107  * is interpreted as a percentage of the initially available content height.
5108  * <p>
5109  * This property may cause the 
5110  * <i>small multiples</i> chart
5111  * to take up a greater width than the one specified in {@link #height}.
5112  * <p>
5113  * When this property is unspecified,
5114  * its value depends on the evaluation of the
5115  * {@link #smallWidth} property,
5116  * which may impose it a value.
5117  * If after the evaluation of {@link #smallWidth}
5118  * this property remains unspecified,
5119  * it is determined as follows.
5120  * <p>
5121  * If the layout will have a single column
5122  * and the property {@link #multiChartSingleColFillsHeight}
5123  * is 
5124  * <tt>true</tt> (it is by default)
5125  * then the height will be the initially available content height.
5126  * <p>
5127  * If the layout will have a single row
5128  * and the property {@link #multiChartSingleRowFillsHeight}
5129  * is 
5130  * <tt>true</tt> (it is by default)
5131  * then the height will be the initially available content height.
5132  * <p>
5133  * Otherwise, the property {@link #smallAspectRatio} is
5134  * used to determine the height of the small chart from its determined width.
5135  * <p>
5136  * The aspect ratio is defaulted to a value that depends on the chart type,
5137  * but is something around 
5138  * <tt>4/3</tt>.
5139  * 
5140  * @type number|string
5141  * @category Chart - Multi > Layout
5142  */
5143 pvc.options.charts.SunburstChart.prototype.smallHeight = undefined;
5144 /**
5145  * The margins of a 
5146  * <i>small</i> chart.
5147  * <p>

5149  * the different supported data types.
5150  *

5152  * @default '2%'
5153  * @category Chart - Multi > Layout
5154  */
5155 pvc.options.charts.SunburstChart.prototype.smallMargins = undefined;

5168 /**
5169  * Fixates the width of each 
5170  * <i>small</i> chart, in pixel units or as a percentage.
5171  * <p>
5172  * A value of type 
5173  * <tt>number</tt>,
5174  * or of type 
5175  * <tt>string</tt>, but with numeric content,
5176  * is interpreted as being in pixel units.
5177  * <p>
5178  * A value of type 
5179  * <tt>string</tt>,
5180  * with numeric content that is suffixed by a "%" character,
5181  * is interpreted as a percentage of the initially available content width.
5182  * <p>
5183  * This property may cause the 
5184  * <i>small multiples</i> chart
5185  * to take up a greater width than the one specified in {@link #width}.
5186  * <p>
5187  * When this property is unspecified,
5188  * a specified finite value, or a defaulted value, of the property {@link #multiChartColumnsMax} is
5189  * used to determine it:
5190  * by dividing the initially available content width
5191  * by the maximum number of charts in a row that 
5192  * <i>actually</i> occur
5193  * (so that if there are less small charts than
5194  * the maximum that can be placed in a row,
5195  * these, nevertheless, take up the whole width).
5196  * <p>
5197  * When an infinite value is specified for
5198  * {@link #multiChartColumnsMax},
5199  * the small charts are laid out in a single row,
5200  * and so the width is calculated from the height {@link #smallHeight},
5201  * using the aspect ratio {@link #smallAspectRatio}.
5202  * The height is defaulted to the initially available content height.
5203  * The aspect ratio is defaulted to a value that depends on the chart type,
5204  * but is something around 
5205  * <tt>4/3</tt>.
5206  * The width is then calculated.
5207  * 
5208  * @type number|string
5209  * @category Chart - Multi > Layout
5210  */
5211 pvc.options.charts.SunburstChart.prototype.smallWidth = undefined;

5228 /**
5229  * The 
5230  * <tt>multiChart</tt> visual role is a chart-level visual role that
5231  * allows turning a chart into a 
5232  * <i>small multiples</i> chart,
5233  * {@link http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Small_multiple}.
5234  * <p>
5235  * Almost all main chart types support being shown
5236  * as a small multiples chart.
5237  * Currently, the exceptions are the charts:
5238  * 
5239  * <i>Heat Grid</i>,
5240  * 
5241  * <i>Bullet</i>,
5242  * 
5243  * <i>Data Tree</i> and
5244  * 
5245  * <i>Parallel Coordinates</i>.
5246  * <p>
5247  * The 
5248  * <tt>multiChart</tt> visual role
5249  * can be bound to any number of dimensions,
5250  * that are, or will be turned into, discrete.
5251  * <p>
5252  * The 
5253  * <tt>multiChart</tt> visual role automatically binds to
5254  * every dimension whose name has the 
5255  * <tt>multiChart</tt> prefix.
5256  * <p>
5257  * One 
5258  * <i>small</i> chart is generated per
5259  * unique combination of the values of the bound dimensions
5260  * that is present in the source data.
5261  * Each small chart then receives as its data
5262  * the partition of the source data that shares its
5263  * unique combination of values.
5264  * <p>
5265  * See {@link pvc.options.VisualRole}
5266  * for more information on supported data types.
5267  * 
5268  * @type string|pvc.options.VisualRole
5269  * @category Chart > Visual Roles
5270  */
5271 pvc.options.charts.SunburstChart.prototype.multiChartRole = undefined;

5278  * <tt>multiChart</tt> visual role.
5279  * 
5280  * @type pvc.options.panels.ChartTitlePanel
5281  * @category Panels - Multi
5282  */
5283 pvc.options.charts.SunburstChart.prototype.smallTitle = undefined;
5284 /**
5285  * The first color axis' options.

5454 /**
5455  * The 
5456  * <tt>multiChart</tt> visual role is a chart-level visual role that
5457  * allows turning a chart into a 
5458  * <i>small multiples</i> chart,
5459  * {@link http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Small_multiple}.
5460  * <p>
5461  * Almost all main chart types support being shown
5462  * as a small multiples chart.
5463  * Currently, the exceptions are the charts:
5464  * 
5465  * <i>Heat Grid</i>,
5466  * 
5467  * <i>Bullet</i>,
5468  * 
5469  * <i>Data Tree</i> and
5470  * 
5471  * <i>Parallel Coordinates</i>.
5472  * <p>
5473  * The 
5474  * <tt>multiChart</tt> visual role
5475  * can be bound to any number of dimensions,
5476  * that are, or will be turned into, discrete.
5477  * <p>
5478  * The 
5479  * <tt>multiChart</tt> visual role automatically binds to
5480  * every dimension whose name has the 
5481  * <tt>multiChart</tt> prefix.
5482  * <p>
5483  * One 
5484  * <i>small</i> chart is generated per
5485  * unique combination of the values of the bound dimensions
5486  * that is present in the source data.
5487  * Each small chart then receives as its data
5488  * the partition of the source data that shares its
5489  * unique combination of values.
5490  * <p>
5491  * See {@link pvc.options.VisualRole}
5492  * for more information on supported data types.
5493  * 
5494  * @type string|pvc.options.VisualRole
5495  * @category Chart > Visual Roles
5496  */
5497 pvc.options.visualRoles.SunburstChartVisualRoles.prototype.multiChart = undefined;

5570  * <p>
5571  * The current algorithm varies the text color so that it has enough contrast
5572  * for the known background color.
5573  * <p>
5574  * It is applied only when a value label is considered to be 
5575  * <i>inside</i> its
5576  * associated slice. Presently, it is considered to be inside, if the center point
5577  * of the label is within the bounds of the slice.
5578  * 
5579  * @type boolean
5580  * @default true
5581  * @category Style

5583 pvc.options.plots.SunburstPlot.prototype.valuesOptimizeLegibility = undefined;
5584 /**
5585  * The behavior to apply when the text of a value label does not fit within the bounds of its associated slice.
5586  * <p>
5587  * This option applies only when {@link pvc.options.plots.Plot#valuesVisible} is true.
5588  * <p>
5589  * Moreover, it also applies only for certain configurations of value label placement,
5590  * relative to the associated slice. Presently, the supported placements are:
5591  * 
5592  * <ul>
5593  * 
5594  * <li>
5595  * <b>non-negative text margin</b>,
5596  * {@link pvc.options.marks.LabelExtensionPoint#textMargin}.
5597  * </li>
5598  * 
5599  * <li>
5600  * <b>text align is center</b> —
5601  * {@link pvc.options.marks.LabelExtensionPoint#textAlign}
5602  * is
5603  * {@link pvc.options.varia.TextAlignment#Center},
5604  * </li>
5605  * 
5606  * <li>
5607  * <b>text is aligned with the middle angle of the slice</b> —
5608  * the label has a
5609  * {@link pvc.options.marks.LabelExtensionPoint#textAngle}
5610  * (modulo) equal to the middle angle of the slice.
5611  * </li>
5612  * </ul>
5613  * <p>
5614  * When an unsupported placement occurs, the label is shown.
5615  * <p>
5616  * Note that for the purposes of hiding and trimming,
5617  * the value of {@link pvc.options.marks.LabelExtensionPoint#textMargin}
5618  * is used for more that the distance between the anchor points of the label and the slice.
5619  * It is also included as a required margin at the opposite side of the
5620  * configured text alignment.
5621  * Also, half of the text margin is included on the bottom and top sides.
5622  * 
5623  * @type pvc.options.varia.ValuesOverflow
5624  * @default 'hide'
5625  * @category Style
5626  */
5627 pvc.options.plots.SunburstPlot.prototype.valuesOverflow = undefined;

5645 /**

5647  * <p>

5649  * 
5650  * <ul>

5661  * </li>

5673  *

5677  * <tt>sunburst</tt>)</li>
5678  *

5688  * <tt>sunburstLeaf_strokeStyle</tt>

5690  * <p>
5691  * The extension points of the

5694  * In the example, when the 
5695  * <tt>sunburst</tt> plot is the main plot,

6042 /**
6043  * The 
6044  * <tt>series</tt> visual role is a plot-level visual role that represents a
6045  * 
6046  * <i>series</i> of connected data points.
6047  * <p>
6048  * Most cartesian charts represent graphically
6049  * the connectedness of data points of a given series in some way,
6050  * by connecting points with a line,
6051  * by giving them all the same color,
6052  * or, simply,
6053  * by the order in which they are drawn,
6054  * and when overlapped, some stay on top of others.
6055  * <p>
6056  * The 
6057  * <tt>series</tt> visual role automatically binds to
6058  * every dimension whose name has the 
6059  * <tt>series</tt> prefix.
6060  * <p>
6061  * The visual role itself is optional,
6062  * yet, when unbound,
6063  * a dimension with a "series" prefix
6064  * is automatically created for it,
6065  * and all datums will have the value 
6066  * <tt>null</tt>
6067  * in that dimension.
6068  * <p>
6069  * See {@link pvc.options.VisualRole}
6070  * for more information on supported data types.
6071  * 
6072  * @type string|pvc.options.VisualRole
6073  * @category Visual Roles
6074  */
6075 pvc.options.visualRoles.CartesianPlotVisualRoles.prototype.series = undefined;

6139 /**
6140  * The 
6141  * <tt>category</tt> visual role is a plot-level visual role that
6142  * represents a generic 
6143  * <i>logical grouping</i> of the data points.
6144  * <p>
6145  * Category data may be discrete or continuous.
6146  * The relevant characteristic is that
6147  * data with equal category values is grouped and
6148  * summarized in some way.
6149  * <p>
6150  * So,
6151  * if more that one data point exists for a given
6152  * series and category values combination,
6153  * nevertheless,
6154  * only one visual element is generated for the whole group.
6155  * <p>
6156  * Some chart types support
6157  * showing continuous category types, in a continuous scale.
6158  * Others,
6159  * turn continuous dimension types bound to the 
6160  * <tt>category</tt>
6161  * visual role into discrete dimension types,
6162  * and then show the continuous categories in a discrete scale.
6163  * <p>
6164  * The 
6165  * <tt>category</tt> visual role automatically binds to
6166  * every dimension whose name has the 
6167  * <tt>category</tt> prefix.
6168  * <p>
6169  * The visual role itself is optional,
6170  * yet, when unbound,
6171  * a dimension with a "category" prefix
6172  * is automatically created for it,
6173  * and all datums will have the value 
6174  * <tt>null</tt>
6175  * in that dimension.
6176  * <p>
6177  * See {@link pvc.options.VisualRole}
6178  * for more information on supported data types.
6179  * 
6180  * @type string|pvc.options.VisualRole
6181  * @category Visual Roles
6182  */
6183 pvc.options.visualRoles.CategoricalPlotVisualRoles.prototype.category = undefined;

6315 /**
6316  * Fixates the height of each 
6317  * <i>small</i> chart, in pixel units or as a percentage.
6318  * <p>
6319  * A value of type 
6320  * <tt>number</tt>,
6321  * or of type 
6322  * <tt>string</tt>, but with numeric content,
6323  * is interpreted as being in pixel units.
6324  * <p>
6325  * A value of type 
6326  * <tt>string</tt>,
6327  * with numeric content that is suffixed by a "%" character,
6328  * is interpreted as a percentage of the initially available content height.
6329  * <p>
6330  * This property may cause the 
6331  * <i>small multiples</i> chart
6332  * to take up a greater width than the one specified in {@link #height}.
6333  * <p>
6334  * When this property is unspecified,
6335  * its value depends on the evaluation of the
6336  * {@link #smallWidth} property,
6337  * which may impose it a value.
6338  * If after the evaluation of {@link #smallWidth}
6339  * this property remains unspecified,
6340  * it is determined as follows.
6341  * <p>
6342  * If the layout will have a single column
6343  * and the property {@link #multiChartSingleColFillsHeight}
6344  * is 
6345  * <tt>true</tt> (it is by default)
6346  * then the height will be the initially available content height.
6347  * <p>
6348  * If the layout will have a single row
6349  * and the property {@link #multiChartSingleRowFillsHeight}
6350  * is 
6351  * <tt>true</tt> (it is by default)
6352  * then the height will be the initially available content height.
6353  * <p>
6354  * Otherwise, the property {@link #smallAspectRatio} is
6355  * used to determine the height of the small chart from its determined width.
6356  * <p>
6357  * The aspect ratio is defaulted to a value that depends on the chart type,
6358  * but is something around 
6359  * <tt>4/3</tt>.
6360  * 
6361  * @type number|string
6362  * @category Chart - Multi > Layout
6363  */
6364 pvc.options.charts.CategoricalNumericChart.prototype.smallHeight = undefined;
6365 /**
6366  * The margins of a 
6367  * <i>small</i> chart.
6368  * <p>
6369  * See {@link pvc.options.varia.Sides} for information about
6370  * the different supported data types.
6371  * 
6372  * @type number|string|pvc.options.varia.Sides
6373  * @default '2%'
6374  * @category Chart - Multi > Layout
6375  */
6376 pvc.options.charts.CategoricalNumericChart.prototype.smallMargins = undefined;
6377 /**
6378  * The paddings of a 
6379  * <i>small</i> chart.
6380  * <p>
6381  * See {@link pvc.options.varia.Sides} for information about
6382  * the different supported data types.
6383  * 
6384  * @type number|string|pvc.options.varia.Sides
6385  * @default 0
6386  * @category Chart - Multi > Layout
6387  */
6388 pvc.options.charts.CategoricalNumericChart.prototype.smallPaddings = undefined;
6389 /**
6390  * Fixates the width of each 
6391  * <i>small</i> chart, in pixel units or as a percentage.
6392  * <p>
6393  * A value of type 
6394  * <tt>number</tt>,
6395  * or of type 
6396  * <tt>string</tt>, but with numeric content,
6397  * is interpreted as being in pixel units.
6398  * <p>
6399  * A value of type 
6400  * <tt>string</tt>,
6401  * with numeric content that is suffixed by a "%" character,
6402  * is interpreted as a percentage of the initially available content width.
6403  * <p>
6404  * This property may cause the 
6405  * <i>small multiples</i> chart
6406  * to take up a greater width than the one specified in {@link #width}.
6407  * <p>
6408  * When this property is unspecified,
6409  * a specified finite value, or a defaulted value, of the property {@link #multiChartColumnsMax} is
6410  * used to determine it:
6411  * by dividing the initially available content width
6412  * by the maximum number of charts in a row that 
6413  * <i>actually</i> occur
6414  * (so that if there are less small charts than
6415  * the maximum that can be placed in a row,
6416  * these, nevertheless, take up the whole width).
6417  * <p>
6418  * When an infinite value is specified for
6419  * {@link #multiChartColumnsMax},
6420  * the small charts are laid out in a single row,
6421  * and so the width is calculated from the height {@link #smallHeight},
6422  * using the aspect ratio {@link #smallAspectRatio}.
6423  * The height is defaulted to the initially available content height.
6424  * The aspect ratio is defaulted to a value that depends on the chart type,
6425  * but is something around 
6426  * <tt>4/3</tt>.
6427  * The width is then calculated.
6428  * 
6429  * @type number|string
6430  * @category Chart - Multi > Layout
6431  */
6432 pvc.options.charts.CategoricalNumericChart.prototype.smallWidth = undefined;

6449 /**
6450  * The 
6451  * <tt>multiChart</tt> visual role is a chart-level visual role that
6452  * allows turning a chart into a 
6453  * <i>small multiples</i> chart,
6454  * {@link http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Small_multiple}.
6455  * <p>
6456  * Almost all main chart types support being shown
6457  * as a small multiples chart.
6458  * Currently, the exceptions are the charts:
6459  * 
6460  * <i>Heat Grid</i>,
6461  * 
6462  * <i>Bullet</i>,
6463  * 
6464  * <i>Data Tree</i> and
6465  * 
6466  * <i>Parallel Coordinates</i>.
6467  * <p>
6468  * The 
6469  * <tt>multiChart</tt> visual role
6470  * can be bound to any number of dimensions,
6471  * that are, or will be turned into, discrete.
6472  * <p>
6473  * The 
6474  * <tt>multiChart</tt> visual role automatically binds to
6475  * every dimension whose name has the 
6476  * <tt>multiChart</tt> prefix.
6477  * <p>
6478  * One 
6479  * <i>small</i> chart is generated per
6480  * unique combination of the values of the bound dimensions
6481  * that is present in the source data.
6482  * Each small chart then receives as its data
6483  * the partition of the source data that shares its
6484  * unique combination of values.
6485  * <p>
6486  * See {@link pvc.options.VisualRole}
6487  * for more information on supported data types.
6488  * 
6489  * @type string|pvc.options.VisualRole
6490  * @category Chart > Visual Roles
6491  */
6492 pvc.options.charts.CategoricalNumericChart.prototype.multiChartRole = undefined;

6594  * <i>small</i> chart is generated per
6595  * unique combination of the values of the bound dimensions
6596  * that is present in the source data.
6597  * Each small chart then receives as its data
6598  * the partition of the source data that shares its
6599  * unique combination of values.
6600  * <p>
6601  * See {@link pvc.options.VisualRole}
6602  * for more information on supported data types.
6603  * 
6604  * @type string|pvc.options.VisualRole
6605  * @category Chart > Visual Roles
6606  */

6732 /**
6733  * The options documentation class of the 
6734  * <b>Box plot</b> chart.
6735  * 
6736  * <h3>Default Data Format</h3>
6737  * For general information on the supported 
6738  * <b>data formats</b>
6739  * see {@link pvc.options.charts.BasicChart}.
6740  * <p>
6741  * The boxplot chart employs a non-default 
6742  * <i>logical row</i> to dimensions mapping:
6743  * 
6744  * <ol>
6745  * 
6746  * <li>All of the free columns of the "series" 
6747  * <i>physical group</i>
6748  * generate and load free dimensions of the "series" 
6749  * <i>dimension group</i>:
6750  * "series", "series2", ...
6751  * </li>
6752  * 
6753  * <li>All of the free columns of the "categories" 
6754  * <i>physical group</i>
6755  * generate and load free dimensions of the "category" 
6756  * <i>dimension group</i>:
6757  * "category", "category2", ...
6758  * </li>
6759  * 
6760  * <li>Free columns of the "measures" 
6761  * <i>physical group</i> generate and load,
6762  * in order, skipping the dimension when not-free,
6763  * the following numeric 
6764  * <i>dimensions</i>:
6765  * 
6766  * <ol>
6767  * 
6768  * <li>median</li>
6769  * 
6770  * <li>lowerQuartil</li>
6771  * 
6772  * <li>upperQuartil</li>
6773  * 
6774  * <li>minimum</li>
6775  * 
6776  * <li>maximum</li>
6777  * </ol>
6778  * </li>
6779  * </ol>
6780  * 
6781  * <style>
6782  * .dataformat {
6783  * border-spacing: 0;
6784  * margin: 1em 0;
6785  * }
6786  * .dataformat td {
6787  * border:  solid 1px;
6788  * padding: 3px;
6789  * width:   80px;
6790  * }
6791  * </style>
6792  * <p>
6793  * All the following are possible 
6794  * <i>default layouts</i> and dimension assignments:
6795  * 
6796  * <table class='dataformat'>
6797  * 
6798  * <tr>
6799  * <td>
6800  * <b>Index</b></td>
6801  * <td>0</td>
6802  * <td>1</td>
6803  * <td>2</td>
6804  * <td>3</td>
6805  * <td>4</td>
6806  * <td>5</td></tr>
6807  * 
6808  * <tr>
6809  * <td>
6810  * <b>Dimension</b></td>
6811  * <td>category</td>
6812  * <td>median</td>
6813  * <td>lowerQuartil</td>
6814  * <td>upperQuartil</td>
6815  * <td>minimum</td>
6816  * <td>maximum</td></tr>
6817  * 
6818  * <tr>
6819  * <td>
6820  * <b>DataType</b></td>
6821  * <td>string</td>
6822  * <td>number</td>
6823  * <td>number</td>
6824  * <td>number</td>
6825  * <td>number</td>
6826  * <td>number</td></tr>
6827  * </table>
6828  * 
6829  * <table class='dataformat'>
6830  * 
6831  * <tr>
6832  * <td>
6833  * <b>Index</b></td>
6834  * <td>0</td>
6835  * <td>1</td>
6836  * <td>2</td>
6837  * <td>3</td>
6838  * <td>4</td></tr>
6839  * 
6840  * <tr>
6841  * <td>
6842  * <b>Dimension</b></td>
6843  * <td>series</td>
6844  * <td>category</td>
6845  * <td>median</td>
6846  * <td>lowerQuartil</td>
6847  * <td>upperQuartil</td></tr>
6848  * 
6849  * <tr>
6850  * <td>
6851  * <b>DataType</b></td>
6852  * <td>string</td>
6853  * <td>string</td>
6854  * <td>number</td>
6855  * <td>number</td>
6856  * <td>number</td></tr>
6857  * </table>
6858  * 
6859  * @class
6860  * @extends pvc.options.charts.CategoricalNumericChart
6861  */

7216 /**
7217  * The extension points of the box plot type.
7218  * <p>
7219  * Plot extension points can be specified:
7220  * 
7221  * <ul>
7222  * 
7223  * <li>at the plot level, in the 
7224  * <i>extensionPoints</i> property,
7225  * without need to prefix the extension point with the
7226  * plot id or name.
7227  * </li>
7228  * 
7229  * <li>at the plot options level, directly,
7230  * without need to prefix the extension point with the
7231  * plot id or name.
7232  * </li>
7233  * 
7234  * <li>
7235  * if it is an internal plot (
7236  * <i>main</i>, 
7237  * <i>plot2</i> or 
7238  * <i>trend</i>),
7239  * at the chart options level, directly.
7240  * </li>
7241  * </ul>
7242  * <p>
7243  * To use an extension point you must find its full name, by joining:
7244  * 
7245  * <ol>
7246  * 
7247  * <li>plot property name (ex: 
7248  * <tt>box</tt>)</li>
7249  * 
7250  * <li>extension property (ex: 
7251  * <tt>panel</tt>)</li>
7252  * 
7253  * <li>the "_" character</li>
7254  * 
7255  * <li>extension sub-property (ex: 
7256  * <tt>strokeStyle</tt>)</li>
7257  * </ol>
7258  * and obtaining, for the examples, the camel-cased name: 
7259  * <tt>boxPanel_strokeStyle</tt>
7260  * (see {@link http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CamelCase}).
7261  * <p>
7262  * The extension points of the 
7263  * <i>main plot</i> of a chart
7264  * may be used without the plot property name prefix.
7265  * In the example, when the 
7266  * <tt>box</tt> plot is the main plot,
7267  * the extension point can be written as 
7268  * <tt>panel_strokeStyle</tt>.
7269  * 
7270  * @class
7271  */
7272 pvc.options.ext.BoxplotPlotExtensionPoints = function(){};

7274         
7275         
7276
