7616 /**
7617  * The values mask used to build the text of value labels.
7618  * <p>
7619  * The mask may contain scene variable names and/or scene atom names,
7620  * like in the examples:
7621  * 
7622  * <ul>
7623  * 
7624  * <li>scene variables: 
7625  * <tt>{category}: {value} EUR</tt>, could yield 
7626  * <tt>Drinks: 3.45 EUR</tt></li>
7627  * 
7628  * <li>atom variables:  
7629  * <tt>{#family} - {#product}</tt>, could yield 
7630  * <tt>Plains - Boeing 747</tt></li>
7631  * </ul>
7632  * <p>
7633  * The default of this property varies depending on whether
7634  * the 
7635  * <tt>size</tt> and 
7636  * <tt>color</tt> visual roles are bound.
7637  * 
7638  * <ol>
7639  * 
7640  * <li>if the 
7641  * <tt>color</tt> visual role is bound,
7642  * the default mask is 
7643  * <tt>'{color}'</tt>
7644  * </li>
7645  * 
7646  * <li>else, if the 
7647  * <tt>size</tt> visual role is bound,
7648  * the default mask is 
7649  * <tt>'{size}'</tt></li>
7650  * 
7651  * <li>else, no default value exists; the value label is not shown</li>
7652  * </ol>
7653  * 
7654  * @type string
7655  * @category Layout
7656  */
7657 pvc.options.plots.HeatGridPlot.prototype.valuesMask = undefined;

7734 /**
7735  * The extension points of the 
7736  * <i>Heat grid</i> plot types.
7737  * <p>
7738  * Plot extension points can be specified:
7739  * 
7740  * <ul>
7741  * 
7742  * <li>at the plot level, in the 
7743  * <i>extensionPoints</i> property,
7744  * without need to prefix the extension point with the
7745  * plot id or name.
7746  * </li>
7747  * 
7748  * <li>at the plot options level, directly,
7749  * without need to prefix the extension point with the
7750  * plot id or name.
7751  * </li>
7752  * 
7753  * <li>
7754  * if it is an internal plot (
7755  * <i>main</i>, 
7756  * <i>plot2</i> or 
7757  * <i>trend</i>),
7758  * at the chart options level, directly.
7759  * </li>
7760  * </ul>
7761  * <p>
7762  * To use an extension point you must find its full name, by joining:
7763  * 
7764  * <ol>
7765  * 
7766  * <li>plot property name (ex: 
7767  * <tt>heatGrid</tt>)</li>
7768  * 
7769  * <li>extension property (ex: 
7770  * <tt>panel</tt>)</li>
7771  * 
7772  * <li>the "_" character</li>
7773  * 
7774  * <li>extension sub-property (ex: 
7775  * <tt>strokeStyle</tt>)</li>
7776  * </ol>
7777  * and obtaining, for the examples, the camel-cased name: 
7778  * <tt>heatGridPanel_strokeStyle</tt>
7779  * (see {@link http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CamelCase}).
7780  * <p>
7781  * The extension points of the 
7782  * <i>main plot</i> of a chart
7783  * may be used without the plot property name prefix.
7784  * In the example, when the 
7785  * <tt>heatGrid</tt> plot is the main plot,
7786  * the extension point can be written as 
7787  * <tt>panel_strokeStyle</tt>.
7788  * 
7789  * @class
7790  */
7791 pvc.options.ext.HeatGridPlotExtensionPoints = function(){};

8120 /**
8121  * Indicates if legibility of value labels should be optimized.
8122  * <p>
8123  * The current algorithm varies the text color so that it has enough contrast
8124  * for the fill color of the associated bar.
8125  * <p>
8126  * It is applied only when a value label is considered to be 
8127  * <i>inside</i> its
8128  * associated bar. Presently, it is considered to be inside, if the center point
8129  * of the label is within the bounds of the bar.
8130  * 
8131  * @type boolean
8132  * @default false
8133  * @category Style
8134  */
8135 pvc.options.plots.BarPlotCommon.prototype.valuesOptimizeLegibility = undefined;
8136 /**
8137  * The behavior to apply when the text of a value label does not fit within the bounds of its associated bar.
8138  * <p>
8139  * This option applies only when {@link pvc.options.plots.Plot#valuesVisible} is true.
8140  * <p>
8141  * Moreover, it also applies only for certain configurations of value label placement,
8142  * relative to the associated bar. Presently, the supported placements are:
8143  * 
8144  * <ul>
8145  * 
8146  * <li>
8147  * <b>non-negative text margin</b>,
8148  * {@link pvc.options.marks.LabelExtensionPoint#textMargin}.
8149  * </li>
8150  * 
8151  * <li>
8152  * <b>horizontal text</b> — on horizontal or vertical bars;
8153  * on vertical bars, text is allowed to overflow, without trimming.
8154  * Text is horizontal when
8155  * {@link pvc.options.marks.LabelExtensionPoint#textAngle}
8156  * is such that 
8157  * <tt>sin(textAngle) = 0</tt> (example: 
8158  * <tt>0</tt>).
8159  * </li>
8160  * 
8161  * <li>
8162  * <b>vertical text on vertical bars</b> —
8163  * text is vertical when
8164  * {@link pvc.options.marks.LabelExtensionPoint#textAngle}
8165  * is such that 
8166  * <tt>cos(textAngle) = 0</tt> (example: 
8167  * <tt>Math.PI/2</tt>, 
8168  * <tt>-Math.PI/2</tt>, 
8169  * <tt>3*Math.PI/2</tt>, ...).
8170  * </li>
8171  * 
8172  * <li>
8173  * <b>text that is intensionally inside the bar</b> —
8174  * this would be too painful to enumerate;
8175  * generally, it depends on the values of
8176  * {@link pvc.options.plots.Plot#valuesAnchor},
8177  * {@link pvc.options.marks.LabelExtensionPoint#textAngle},
8178  * {@link pvc.options.marks.LabelExtensionPoint#textAlign} and
8179  * {@link pvc.options.marks.LabelExtensionPoint#textBaseline}.
8180  * </li>
8181  * </ul>
8182  * <p>
8183  * When an unsupported placement occurs, the label is shown.
8184  * <p>
8185  * Note that for the purposes of hiding and trimming,
8186  * the value of {@link pvc.options.marks.LabelExtensionPoint#textMargin}
8187  * is used for more that the distance between the anchor points of the label and the bar.
8188  * <p>
8189  * It is also included as a required margin at the side opposite to the label's anchor.
8190  * For example, if a label is anchored with a 
8191  * <tt>bottom</tt> 
8192  * <i>textBaseline</i>,
8193  * the text margin must also be available on the top side of the label.
8194  * <p>
8195  * Also, the same margin is respected on the horizontal sides of the label (left and right),
8196  * whether or not they are anchor sides.
8197  * 
8198  * @type pvc.options.varia.ValuesOverflow
8199  * @default 'hide'
8200  * @category Style
8201  */
8202 pvc.options.plots.BarPlotCommon.prototype.valuesOverflow = undefined;

8209  * @category Visual Roles

8212 /**
8213  * The extension points of the 
8214  * <i>bar family</i> plot types.
8215  * <p>
8216  * Plot extension points can be specified:
8217  * 
8218  * <ul>
8219  * 
8220  * <li>at the plot level, in the 
8221  * <i>extensionPoints</i> property,
8222  * without need to prefix the extension point with the
8223  * plot id or name.
8224  * </li>
8225  * 
8226  * <li>at the plot options level, directly,
8227  * without need to prefix the extension point with the
8228  * plot id or name.
8229  * </li>
8230  * 
8231  * <li>
8232  * if it is an internal plot (
8233  * <i>main</i>, 
8234  * <i>plot2</i> or 
8235  * <i>trend</i>),
8236  * at the chart options level, directly.
8237  * </li>
8238  * </ul>
8239  * <p>
8240  * To use an extension point you must find its full name, by joining:
8241  * 
8242  * <ol>
8243  * 
8244  * <li>plot property name (ex: 
8245  * <tt>bar</tt>)</li>
8246  * 
8247  * <li>extension property (ex: 
8248  * <tt>panel</tt>)</li>
8249  * 
8250  * <li>the "_" character</li>
8251  * 
8252  * <li>extension sub-property (ex: 
8253  * <tt>strokeStyle</tt>)</li>
8254  * </ol>
8255  * and obtaining, for the examples, the camel-cased name: 
8256  * <tt>barPanel_strokeStyle</tt>
8257  * (see {@link http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CamelCase}).
8258  * <p>
8259  * The extension points of the 
8260  * <i>main plot</i> of a chart
8261  * may be used without the plot property name prefix.
8262  * In the example, when the 
8263  * <tt>bar</tt> plot is the main plot,
8264  * the extension point can be written as 
8265  * <tt>panel_strokeStyle</tt>.
8266  * 
8267  * @class
8268  */

8838 /**
8839  * The extension points of the waterfall plot type.
8840  * <p>
8841  * Plot extension points can be specified:
8842  * 
8843  * <ul>
8844  * 
8845  * <li>at the plot level, in the 
8846  * <i>extensionPoints</i> property,
8847  * without need to prefix the extension point with the
8848  * plot id or name.
8849  * </li>
8850  * 
8851  * <li>at the plot options level, directly,
8852  * without need to prefix the extension point with the
8853  * plot id or name.
8854  * </li>
8855  * 
8856  * <li>
8857  * if it is an internal plot (
8858  * <i>main</i>, 
8859  * <i>plot2</i> or 
8860  * <i>trend</i>),
8861  * at the chart options level, directly.
8862  * </li>
8863  * </ul>
8864  * <p>
8865  * To use an extension point you must find its full name, by joining:
8866  * 
8867  * <ol>
8868  * 
8869  * <li>plot property name (ex: 
8870  * <tt>water</tt>)</li>
8871  * 
8872  * <li>extension property (ex: 
8873  * <tt>line</tt>)</li>
8874  * 
8875  * <li>the "_" character</li>
8876  * 
8877  * <li>extension sub-property (ex: 
8878  * <tt>strokeStyle</tt>)</li>
8879  * </ol>
8880  * and obtaining, for the examples, the camel-cased name: 
8881  * <tt>waterLine_strokeStyle</tt>
8882  * (see {@link http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CamelCase}).
8883  * <p>
8884  * The extension points of the 
8885  * <i>main plot</i> of a chart
8886  * may be used without the plot property name prefix.
8887  * In the example, when the 
8888  * <tt>water</tt> plot is the main plot,
8889  * the extension point can be written as 
8890  * <tt>line_strokeStyle</tt>.
8891  * 
8892  * @class
8893  * @extends pvc.options.ext.BarPlotCommonExtensionPoints
8894  */
8895 pvc.options.ext.WaterfallPlotExtensionPoints = function(){};

9246 /**
9247  * The extension points common to the 
9248  * <b>point</b> plot types.
9249  * <p>
9250  * Plot extension points can be specified:
9251  * 
9252  * <ul>
9253  * 
9254  * <li>at the plot level, in the 
9255  * <i>extensionPoints</i> property,
9256  * without need to prefix the extension point with the
9257  * plot id or name.
9258  * </li>
9259  * 
9260  * <li>at the plot options level, directly,
9261  * without need to prefix the extension point with the
9262  * plot id or name.
9263  * </li>
9264  * 
9265  * <li>
9266  * if it is an internal plot (
9267  * <i>main</i>, 
9268  * <i>plot2</i> or 
9269  * <i>trend</i>),
9270  * at the chart options level, directly.
9271  * </li>
9272  * </ul>
9273  * <p>
9274  * To use an extension point you must find its full name, by joining:
9275  * 
9276  * <ol>
9277  * 
9278  * <li>plot property name (ex: 
9279  * <tt>point</tt>)</li>
9280  * 
9281  * <li>extension property (ex: 
9282  * <tt>area</tt>)</li>
9283  * 
9284  * <li>the "_" character</li>
9285  * 
9286  * <li>extension sub-property (ex: 
9287  * <tt>fillStyle</tt>)</li>
9288  * </ol>
9289  * and obtaining, for the examples, the camel-cased name: 
9290  * <tt>pointArea_fillStyle</tt>
9291  * (see {@link http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CamelCase}).
9292  * <p>
9293  * The extension points of the 
9294  * <i>main plot</i> of a chart
9295  * may be used without the plot property name prefix.
9296  * In the example, when the 
9297  * <tt>point</tt> plot is the main plot,
9298  * the extension point can be written as 
9299  * <tt>area_fillStyle</tt>.
9300  * 
9301  * @class
9302  */

9793 /**
9794  * The common options documentation class for the 
9795  * <b>Metric Line/Dot family</b> charts.
9796  * 
9797  * <h3>Default Data Format</h3>
9798  * For general information on the supported 
9799  * <b>data formats</b>
9800  * see {@link pvc.options.charts.BasicChart}.
9801  * <p>
9802  * The metric-point chart family employs a non-default 
9803  * <i>logical row</i> to dimensions mapping:
9804  * 
9805  * <ol>
9806  * 
9807  * <li>
9808  * All of the free 
9809  * <i>discrete</i> columns of the 
9810  * <i>logical table</i>
9811  * generate and load free dimensions of the "series" 
9812  * <i>dimension group</i>:
9813  * "series", "series2", "series4", ...
9814  * </li>
9815  * 
9816  * <li>Free 
9817  * <i>continuous</i> columns of the 
9818  * <i>logical table</i> generate and load,
9819  * in order, skipping the dimension when not-free,
9820  * the following numeric 
9821  * <i>dimensions</i>:
9822  * 
9823  * <ol>
9824  * 
9825  * <li>x</li>
9826  * 
9827  * <li>y</li>
9828  * 
9829  * <li>color</li>
9830  * 
9831  * <li>size</li>
9832  * </ol>
9833  * </li>
9834  * </ol>
9835  * 
9836  * <style>
9837  * .dataformat {
9838  * border-spacing: 0;
9839  * margin: 1em 0;
9840  * }
9841  * .dataformat td {
9842  * border:  solid 1px;
9843  * padding: 3px;
9844  * width:   80px;
9845  * }
9846  * </style>
9847  * <p>
9848  * All the following are possible 
9849  * <i>default layouts</i> and dimension assignments:
9850  * 
9851  * <table class='dataformat'>
9852  * 
9853  * <tr>
9854  * <td>
9855  * <b>Index</b></td>
9856  * <td>0</td>
9857  * <td>1</td>
9858  * <td>2</td></tr>
9859  * 
9860  * <tr>
9861  * <td>
9862  * <b>Dimension</b></td>
9863  * <td>series</td>
9864  * <td>x</td>
9865  * <td>y</td></tr>
9866  * 
9867  * <tr>
9868  * <td>
9869  * <b>DataType</b></td>
9870  * <td>string</td>
9871  * <td>number</td>
9872  * <td>number</td></tr>
9873  * </table>
9874  * 
9875  * <table class='dataformat'>
9876  * 
9877  * <tr>
9878  * <td>
9879  * <b>Index</b></td>
9880  * <td>0</td>
9881  * <td>1</td>
9882  * <td>2</td>
9883  * <td>3</td>
9884  * <td>4</td></tr>
9885  * 
9886  * <tr>
9887  * <td>
9888  * <b>Dimension</b></td>
9889  * <td>series</td>
9890  * <td>series2</td>
9891  * <td>x</td>
9892  * <td>y</td>
9893  * <td>color</td></tr>
9894  * 
9895  * <tr>
9896  * <td>
9897  * <b>DataType</b></td>
9898  * <td>string</td>
9899  * <td>string</td>
9900  * <td>number</td>
9901  * <td>number</td>
9902  * <td>number</td></tr>
9903  * </table>
9904  * 
9905  * <table class='dataformat'>
9906  * 
9907  * <tr>
9908  * <td>
9909  * <b>Index</b></td>
9910  * <td>0</td>
9911  * <td>1</td>
9912  * <td>2</td>
9913  * <td>3</td>
9914  * <td>4</td></tr>
9915  * 
9916  * <tr>
9917  * <td>
9918  * <b>Dimension</b></td>
9919  * <td>series</td>
9920  * <td>x</td>
9921  * <td>y</td>
9922  * <td>color</td>
9923  * <td>size</td></tr>
9924  * 
9925  * <tr>
9926  * <td>
9927  * <b>DataType</b></td>
9928  * <td>string</td>
9929  * <td>number</td>
9930  * <td>number</td>
9931  * <td>number</td>
9932  * <td>number</td></tr>
9933  * </table>
9934  * 
9935  * <h3>How To Bind The Color Visual Role</h3>
9936  * The Metric Point's 
9937  * <tt>color</tt> visual role can be
9938  * bound to either continuous or discrete dimensions.
9939  * <p>
9940  * In the default table layout,
9941  * when enough free 
9942  * <i>continuous</i> columns exist,
9943  * a dimension named "color" is generated and loaded
9944  * — the name of the 
9945  * <tt>color</tt> role's default dimension —,
9946  * resulting in a 
9947  * <i>continuous</i> color scale.
9948  * <p>
9949  * Otherwise, by default,
9950  * the 
9951  * <tt>color</tt> visual role ends up being bound the
9952  * dimensions of the series role — its default 
9953  * <i>source role</i> —,
9954  * resulting in a 
9955  * <i>discrete</i> color scale.
9956  * <p>
9957  * The 
9958  * <tt>color</tt> role can also be bound to other discrete dimension(s), explicitly.
9959  * 
9960  * <h4>Solution 1</h4>
9961  * One possibility is to 
9962  * <i>switch</i> one of the automatically fed "series" dimensions
9963  * to the 
9964  * <tt>color</tt> visual role.
9965  * For example:
9966  * 
9967  * <pre>
9968  * seriesRole: "series", // steal one here
9969  * colorRole:  "series2" // and assign it here
9970  * 
9971  * </pre>
9972  * 
9973  * <h4>Solution 2</h4>
9974  * A second possibility is to simply match colors to "series":
9975  * 
9976  * <pre>
9977  * seriesRole: {from: "series"} // same dimensions as the series visual role
9978  * 
9979  * </pre>
9980  * 
9981  * <h4>Solution 3</h4>
9982  * Another possibility is to configure the {@link pvc.options.charts.BasicChart#readers}
9983  * with the actual layout, using the default dimension names of
9984  * the desired visual roles.
9985  * For example:
9986  * 
9987  * <pre>
9988  * readers: "color, series, x, y, size"
9989  * 
9990  * </pre>
9991  * 
9992  * <h4>Solution 4</h4>
9993  * Of course, you can (and probably should) use actual business names for the names of dimensions.
9994  * To that end, both the readers and the visual roles' mappings need to be specified:
9995  * 
9996  * <pre>
9997  * readers:      "orderType, productFamily, productType, expectedSales, actualSales, profit"
9998  * colorRole:    "orderType",
9999  * seriesRole:   "orderType", // controls drawing layer only
10000  * xRole:        "expectedSales",
10001  * yRole:        "actualSales",
10002  * sizeRole:     "profit"
10003  * 
10004  * </pre>
10005  * Note that in this plot type, the series visual role only controls the layer
10006  * of the dot cloud.
10007  * Also, the dimensions "productFamily" and "productType"
10008  * were not mapped to any visual role,
10009  * and will only be presented in the tooltip.
10010  * 
10011  * @class
10012  * @extends pvc.options.charts.CartesianChart
10013  * @abstract
10014  */
10015 pvc.options.charts.MetricPointChart = function(){};
10016         
10017         
10018         
10019         
10020 /**
10021  * The trend plot is activated when 
10022  * the 
10023  * <i>other</i> chart plots indicate that their 
10024  * data should be trended.
10025  * <p>
10026  * To activate trending for a plot specify 
10027  * its 
10028  * <tt>trend type</tt> option.
10029  * 
10030  * @type pvc.options.plots.TrendMetricPointPlot

10163 /**
10164  * Fixates the height of each 
10165  * <i>small</i> chart, in pixel units or as a percentage.
10166  * <p>
10167  * A value of type 
10168  * <tt>number</tt>,
10169  * or of type 
10170  * <tt>string</tt>, but with numeric content,
10171  * is interpreted as being in pixel units.
10172  * <p>
10173  * A value of type 
10174  * <tt>string</tt>,
10175  * with numeric content that is suffixed by a "%" character,
10176  * is interpreted as a percentage of the initially available content height.
10177  * <p>
10178  * This property may cause the 
10179  * <i>small multiples</i> chart
10180  * to take up a greater width than the one specified in {@link #height}.
10181  * <p>
10182  * When this property is unspecified,
10183  * its value depends on the evaluation of the
10184  * {@link #smallWidth} property,
10185  * which may impose it a value.
10186  * If after the evaluation of {@link #smallWidth}
10187  * this property remains unspecified,
10188  * it is determined as follows.
10189  * <p>
10190  * If the layout will have a single column
10191  * and the property {@link #multiChartSingleColFillsHeight}
10192  * is 
10193  * <tt>true</tt> (it is by default)
10194  * then the height will be the initially available content height.
10195  * <p>
10196  * If the layout will have a single row
10197  * and the property {@link #multiChartSingleRowFillsHeight}
10198  * is 
10199  * <tt>true</tt> (it is by default)
10200  * then the height will be the initially available content height.
10201  * <p>
10202  * Otherwise, the property {@link #smallAspectRatio} is
10203  * used to determine the height of the small chart from its determined width.
10204  * <p>
10205  * The aspect ratio is defaulted to a value that depends on the chart type,
10206  * but is something around 
10207  * <tt>4/3</tt>.
10208  * 
10209  * @type number|string
10210  * @category Chart - Multi > Layout
10211  */
10212 pvc.options.charts.MetricPointChart.prototype.smallHeight = undefined;
10213 /**
10214  * The margins of a 
10215  * <i>small</i> chart.
10216  * <p>
10217  * See {@link pvc.options.varia.Sides} for information about
10218  * the different supported data types.
10219  * 
10220  * @type number|string|pvc.options.varia.Sides
10221  * @default '2%'
10222  * @category Chart - Multi > Layout
10223  */
10224 pvc.options.charts.MetricPointChart.prototype.smallMargins = undefined;
10225 /**
10226  * The paddings of a 
10227  * <i>small</i> chart.
10228  * <p>
10229  * See {@link pvc.options.varia.Sides} for information about
10230  * the different supported data types.
10231  * 
10232  * @type number|string|pvc.options.varia.Sides
10233  * @default 0
10234  * @category Chart - Multi > Layout
10235  */
10236 pvc.options.charts.MetricPointChart.prototype.smallPaddings = undefined;
10237 /**
10238  * Fixates the width of each 
10239  * <i>small</i> chart, in pixel units or as a percentage.
10240  * <p>
10241  * A value of type 
10242  * <tt>number</tt>,
10243  * or of type 
10244  * <tt>string</tt>, but with numeric content,
10245  * is interpreted as being in pixel units.
10246  * <p>
10247  * A value of type 
10248  * <tt>string</tt>,
10249  * with numeric content that is suffixed by a "%" character,
10250  * is interpreted as a percentage of the initially available content width.
10251  * <p>
10252  * This property may cause the 
10253  * <i>small multiples</i> chart
10254  * to take up a greater width than the one specified in {@link #width}.
10255  * <p>
10256  * When this property is unspecified,
10257  * a specified finite value, or a defaulted value, of the property {@link #multiChartColumnsMax} is
10258  * used to determine it:
10259  * by dividing the initially available content width
10260  * by the maximum number of charts in a row that 
10261  * <i>actually</i> occur
10262  * (so that if there are less small charts than
10263  * the maximum that can be placed in a row,
10264  * these, nevertheless, take up the whole width).
10265  * <p>
10266  * When an infinite value is specified for
10267  * {@link #multiChartColumnsMax},
10268  * the small charts are laid out in a single row,
10269  * and so the width is calculated from the height {@link #smallHeight},
10270  * using the aspect ratio {@link #smallAspectRatio}.
10271  * The height is defaulted to the initially available content height.
10272  * The aspect ratio is defaulted to a value that depends on the chart type,
10273  * but is something around 
10274  * <tt>4/3</tt>.
10275  * The width is then calculated.
10276  * 
10277  * @type number|string
10278  * @category Chart - Multi > Layout
10279  */
10280 pvc.options.charts.MetricPointChart.prototype.smallWidth = undefined;

10297 /**
10298  * The 
10299  * <tt>multiChart</tt> visual role is a chart-level visual role that
10300  * allows turning a chart into a 
10301  * <i>small multiples</i> chart,
10302  * {@link http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Small_multiple}.
10303  * <p>
10304  * Almost all main chart types support being shown
10305  * as a small multiples chart.
10306  * Currently, the exceptions are the charts:
10307  * 
10308  * <i>Heat Grid</i>,
10309  * 
10310  * <i>Bullet</i>,
10311  * 
10312  * <i>Data Tree</i> and
10313  * 
10314  * <i>Parallel Coordinates</i>.
10315  * <p>
10316  * The 
10317  * <tt>multiChart</tt> visual role
10318  * can be bound to any number of dimensions,
10319  * that are, or will be turned into, discrete.
10320  * <p>
10321  * The 
10322  * <tt>multiChart</tt> visual role automatically binds to
10323  * every dimension whose name has the 
10324  * <tt>multiChart</tt> prefix.
10325  * <p>
10326  * One 
10327  * <i>small</i> chart is generated per
10328  * unique combination of the values of the bound dimensions
10329  * that is present in the source data.
10330  * Each small chart then receives as its data
10331  * the partition of the source data that shares its
10332  * unique combination of values.
10333  * <p>
10334  * See {@link pvc.options.VisualRole}
10335  * for more information on supported data types.
10336  * 
10337  * @type string|pvc.options.VisualRole
10338  * @category Chart > Visual Roles
10339  */

10630  * <tt>point</tt> plot is the main plot,

10807 /**
10808  * The 
10809  * <tt>color</tt> visual role is a plot-level visual role that
10810  * is visually encoded by the color of visual elements.
10811  * <p>
10812  * Specifically,
10813  * it is the color of the dots and lines of the visual elements
10814  * that is changed according to the color of the corresponding
10815  * color role value.
10816  * <p>
10817  * The 
10818  * <tt>color</tt> visual role automatically binds to
10819  * every discrete dimension, or a single continuous dimension,
10820  * whose name has the 
10821  * <tt>color</tt> prefix
10822  * or, if none exists,
10823  * the dimensions of the "series" role.
10824  * <p>
10825  * The 
10826  * <tt>color</tt> visual role is discrete or continuous.
10827  * <p>
10828  * The default value type of dimensions bound to it is 
10829  * <tt>Number</tt>.
10830  * <p>
10831  * See {@link pvc.options.VisualRole}
10832  * for more information on supported data types.
10833  * 
10834  * @type string|pvc.options.VisualRole
10835  * @category Visual Roles
10836  */
10837 pvc.options.visualRoles.MetricPointPlotVisualRoles.prototype.color = undefined;

10839  * The 
10840  * <tt>size</tt> visual role is a plot-level visual role that
10841  * is visually encoded by the size of visual elements.
10842  * <p>
10843  * Specifically, when dots are visible,
10844  * controls the size of the dot mark.
10845  * <p>
10846  * The 
10847  * <tt>size</tt> visual role automatically binds to
10848  * every dimension whose name has the 
10849  * <tt>size</tt> prefix.
10850  * <p>
10851  * The 
10852  * <tt>size</tt> visual role is continuous and optional.
10853  * <p>
10854  * The default value type of the dimension bound to it is 
10855  * <tt>Number</tt>.
10856  * <p>
10857  * See {@link pvc.options.VisualRole}
10858  * for more information on supported data types.

10869  * <p>

11067 /**

11069  * a new protovis mark to another mark.
11070  * <p>
11071  * If the extension point refers to a panel mark,
11072  * the parent of the new mark will be that panel.
11073  * Otherwise, its parent will
11074  * be the parent panel of the mark of the extension point.
11075  * 
11076  * <p>
11077  * The following example shows how to add an image to
11078  * an axis tick:
11079  * 
11080  * <pre>
11081  * function yAxisTick(){
11082  *     return new pv.Image()
11083  *             .url('res/images/arrowYy.png')
11084  *             .lineWidth(0)
11085  *             .height(7)
11086  *             .width(5);
11087  * }
11088  *                 
11089  * </pre>
11090  * 
11091  * <p>
11092  * 
11093  * @type function
11094  */
11095 pvc.options.marks.MarkExtensionPoint.prototype.add = undefined;

11132 /**
11133  * Flags that affect the interactivity of the mark.
11134  * <p>
11135  * The default value, 
11136  * <tt>-1</tt> has all bits with the value "1".
11137  * <p>
11138  * Only the bits for which {@link #imask} is "1" are considered.
11139  * <p>
11140  * Bits can be combined by using a "|" character, for example:
11141  * 
11142  * <code>"Selectable|Hoverable"</code>
11143  * <p>
11144  * The following are the supported bit values:
11145  * 
11146  * <style>
11147  * .bitstable {
11148  * border-spacing: 0;
11149  * margin: 1em 0;
11150  * }
11151  * .bitstable th {
11152  * font-weight: bold;
11153  * }
11154  * .bitstable td, .bitstable th {
11155  * border:  solid 1px;
11156  * padding: 5px;
11157  * }
11158  * </style>
11159  * 
11160  * <table class='bitstable'>
11161  * 
11162  * <tr>
11163  * 
11164  * <th>bit</th>
11165  * 
11166  * <th>description</th>
11167  * </tr>
11168  * 
11169  * <tr>
11170  * 
11171  * <td>Interactive</td>
11172  * 
11173  * <td>
11174  * The mark can trigger and display interaction.
11175  * </td>
11176  * </tr>
11177  * 
11178  * <tr>
11179  * 
11180  * <td>ShowsActivity</td>
11181  * 
11182  * <td>The mark's style can change based on the active scene.</td>
11183  * </tr>
11184  * 
11185  * <tr>
11186  * 
11187  * <td>ShowsSelection</td>
11188  * 
11189  * <td>The mark's style can change based on whether the datums in its scene are selected.</td>
11190  * </tr>
11191  * 
11192  * <tr>
11193  * 
11194  * <td>ShowsTooltip</td>
11195  * 
11196  * <td>The mark displays a tooltip when pointed to.</td>
11197  * </tr>
11198  * 
11199  * <tr>
11200  * 
11201  * <td>Selectable</td>
11202  * 
11203  * <td>
11204  * The mark can be selected by one of the possible means.
11205  * Use this to disable this mark from affecting selection,
11206  * by whatever means.
11207  * </td>
11208  * </tr>
11209  * 
11210  * <tr>
11211  * 
11212  * <td>SelectableByClick</td>
11213  * 
11214  * <td>
11215  * The mark can be selected by clicking on it.
11216  * Requires the 
11217  * <i>Selectable</i> bit as well.
11218  * </td>
11219  * </tr>
11220  * 
11221  * <tr>
11222  * 
11223  * <td>SelectableByRubberband</td>
11224  * 
11225  * <td>
11226  * The mark can be selected by using the rubber-band.
11227  * </td>
11228  * </tr>
11229  * 
11230  * <tr>
11231  * 
11232  * <td>SelectableByFocusWindow</td>
11233  * 
11234  * <td>
11235  * The mark can be selected when the focus window reveals it.
11236  * </td>
11237  * </tr>
11238  * 
11239  * <tr>
11240  * 
11241  * <td>Hoverable</td>
11242  * 
11243  * <td>
11244  * The mark can be hovered-over and affect its scene's active state.
11245  * </td>
11246  * </tr>
11247  * 
11248  * <tr>
11249  * 
11250  * <td>Clickable</td>
11251  * 
11252  * <td>
11253  * The mark can be clicked and trigger the 
11254  * <i>clickAction</i> handler.
11255  * </td>
11256  * </tr>
11257  * 
11258  * <tr>
11259  * 
11260  * <td>DoubleClickable</td>
11261  * 
11262  * <td>
11263  * The mark can be double-clicked and trigger the 
11264  * <i>doubleClickAction</i> handler.
11265  * </td>
11266  * </tr>
11267  * </table>
11268  * 
11269  * @type number|string
11270  * @default -1
11271  */
11272 pvc.options.marks.MarkExtensionPoint.prototype.ibits = undefined;
11273 /**
11274  * Bit mask which controls the bits of 
11275  * <i>ibits</i> that should be considered.
11276  * <p>
11277  * The default value, 
11278  * <tt>0</tt> has all bits with the value "0".

12019 pvc.options.axes = {};
12020 
12021 /**
12022  * The options documentation class of the color axis.
12023  * <p>
12024  * A color axis panel and its properties
12025  * can be referred to in several ways,
12026  * using one of the following 
12027  * <b>prefixes</b>,
12028  * in order of precedence:
12029  * 
12030  * <dl>
12031  * 
12032  * <dt>By 
12033  * <b>full id</b></dt>
12034  * 
12035  * <dd>
12036  * the id of the axis is the word 
12037  * <tt>color</tt>,
12038  * followed by it's index (when >= 2),
12039  * and terminated by the word 
12040  * <tt>Axis</tt>.
12041  * </dd>
12042  * 
12043  * <dd>(e.g.: 
12044  * <tt>colorAxis</tt>, 
12045  * <tt>color2Axis</tt>, 
12046  * <tt>color3Axis</tt>, ...)</dd>
12047  * 
12048  * <dt>By 
12049  * <b>scale type</b></dt>
12050  * 
12051  * <dd>
12052  * the scale type can be 
12053  * <tt>discreteColorAxis</tt> or 
12054  * <tt>continuousColorAxis</tt> and,
12055  * in the latter case, with higher precedence,
12056  * 
12057  * <tt>numericColorAxis</tt> and 
12058  * <tt>timeSeriesColorAxis</tt> are also possible
12059  * </dd>
12060  * 
12061  * <dt>By 
12062  * <b>catch all name</b></dt>
12063  * 
12064  * <dd>the name 
12065  * <tt>colorAxes</tt> (note the 
12066  * <i>e</i>) matches any color axis</dd>
12067  * 
12068  * <dt>By the single word 
12069  * <tt>color</tt>, when it is the first axis</dt>
12070  * 
12071  * <dd>
12072  * to make it easier to specify the properties of
12073  * the most used color axis - the first one -
12074  * it can be referred to without the suffix 
12075  * <tt>Axis</tt>,
12076  * resulting in the name 
12077  * <tt>color</tt>.
12078  * </dd>
12079  * 
12080  * <dt>Without id, when it is the first axis,
12081  * for legend properties and the 
12082  * <tt>colors</tt> property</dt>
12083  * 
12084  * <dd>
12085  * Legend related properties of the first axis
12086  * can be referred to directly, without the axis id.
12087  * The same applies to the property 
12088  * <tt>colors</tt>.
12089  * <p>
12090  * As an example,
12091  * the name of the property 
12092  * <tt>legendDrawLine</tt>
12093  * can be used directly, instead of its full name:
12094  * 
12095  * <tt>colorAxisLegendDrawLine</tt>.
12096  * <p>
12097  * For color axes other than the first,
12098  * the legend properties still need to be referred to
12099  * with its full name, like in:
12100  * 
12101  * <tt>color2AxisLegendDrawLine</tt>.
12102  * </dd>
12103  * </dl>
12104  * <p>
12105  * The domain of color axes
12106  * is evaluated at the root chart level.
12107  * When in a 
12108  * <i>small multiples</i> chart,
12109  * colors are shared among 
12110  * <i>small</i> charts.
12111  * <p>
12112  * Color axes map values of the "color" visual role.
12113  * <p>
12114  * For more information on options
12115  * that are specific to only certain color axis types,
12116  * please see one of the following concrete sub-classes:
12117  * 
12118  * <ul>
12119  * 
12120  * <li>
12121  * Numeric or discrete domain color axes: {@link pvc.options.axes.AnyColorAxis}
12122  * </li>
12123  * 
12124  * <li>
12125  * Discrete domain color axes: {@link pvc.options.axes.DiscreteColorAxis}
12126  * </li>
12127  * 
12128  * <li>
12129  * Heat-grid - numeric domain color axis: {@link pvc.options.axes.HeatGridColorAxis}
12130  * </li>
12131  * </ul>
12132  * 
12133  * @class
12134  * @abstract
12135  */
12136 pvc.options.axes.ColorAxis = function(){};
12137         
12138         
12139         
12140         
12141 /**
12142  * The colors of a color axis.
12143  * <p>
12144  * It can be a single color as documented in
12145  * {@link pvc.options.varia.ColorString} or
12146  * a single 
12147  * <i>protovis</i> color object
12148  * (like: 
12149  * <tt>pv.color('red')</tt> or 
12150  * <tt>pv.Color.names.blueviolet</tt>).
12151  * <p>
12152  * Additionally, an array of color strings or
12153  * 
12154  * <i>protovis</i> colors can be specified.
12155  * <p>
12156  * If a function is specified, it can be:
12157  * 
12158  * <ul>
12159  * 
12160  * <li>
12161  * 
12162  * <b>a protovis scale</b>,
12163  * like the one obtained by:
12164  * 
12165  * <tt>pv.colors('red', 'blueviolet')</tt>
12166  * </li>
12167  * 
12168  * <li>
12169  * 
12170  * <b>a scale factory</b> - a function that
12171  * given the domain values as arguments
12172  * return a protovis color scale
12173  * </li>
12174  * </ul>
12175  * <p>
12176  * The default color scheme depends on the
12177  * axis domain being discrete or numeric.
12178  * <p>
12179  * For 
12180  * <b>discrete domains</b>, the default value is the 
12181  * <i>protovis</i>
12182  * 
12183  * <tt>category10</tt> color scheme:
12184  * 
12185  * <ol style='font-weight:bold'>
12186  * 
12187  * <li style='color:#1f77b4'>value</li>
12188  * 
12189  * <li style='color:#ff7f0e'>value</li>
12190  * 
12191  * <li style='color:#2ca02c'>value</li>
12192  * 
12193  * <li style='color:#d62728'>value</li>
12194  * 
12195  * <li style='color:#9467bd'>value</li>
12196  * 
12197  * <li style='color:#8c564b'>value</li>
12198  * 
12199  * <li style='color:#e377c2'>value</li>
12200  * 
12201  * <li style='color:#7f7f7f'>value</li>
12202  * 
12203  * <li style='color:#bcbd22'>value</li>
12204  * 
12205  * <li style='color:#17becf'>value</li>
12206  * </ol>
12207  * <p>
12208  * For 
12209  * <b>numeric domains</b>, the default value is the
12210  * color scheme:
12211  * 
12212  * <ol style='font-weight:bold'>
12213  * 
12214  * <li style='color:red'>value</li>
12215  * 
12216  * <li style='color:yellow'>value</li>
12217  * 
12218  * <li style='color:green'>value</li>
12219  * </ol>
12220  * 
12221  * @type pvc.options.varia.ColorString|pv.Color|list(pvc.options.varia.ColorString|pv.Color)|function
12222  * @category Scale
12223  */
12224 pvc.options.axes.ColorAxis.prototype.colors = undefined;
12225 /**
12226  * The color transform function.
12227  * <p>
12228  * Allows applying an effect to the colors that an axis outputs.
12229  * <p>
12230  * The default value is 
12231  * <tt>null</tt>
12232  * except for color axes that are used only by one of
12233  * the 
12234  * <tt>trend</tt> or 
12235  * <tt>plot2</tt> plots,
12236  * and whose 
12237  * <tt>colors</tt> property was not specified.
12238  * In these cases, the default value is
12239  * 
12240  * <tt>pvc.brighterColorTransform</tt>.
12241  * 
12242  * @returns {pv.Color}
12243  * The transformed color.
12244  * 
12245  * @method
12246  * @this null
12247  * @param {pv.Color} color
12248  * The color to transform.
12249  * 
12250  * @category Scale
12251  */
12252 pvc.options.axes.ColorAxis.prototype.transform = function(){};
12253 /**

12296 /**
12297  * Allows reserving colors to certain color scale keys.
12298  * <p>
12299  * Color scale keys are the values of the color role.
12300  * By default, the color role is bound to the dimensions of the series role.
12301  * Color scale keys that are not mapped,
12302  * receive colors taken from {@link #colors}.
12303  * Colors in {@link #colors} that are also present in the color map are ignored.
12304  * 
12305  * <p>
12306  * Assuming the color role is bound to the grouping 
12307  * <tt>"territory, country"</tt>,
12308  * the following map would reserve the colors 
12309  * <i>red</i> and 
12310  * <i>green</i> to
12311  * Canada and Portugal, respectively:
12312  * 
12313  * <pre>
12314  * chartOptions.colorMap = {
12315  *     "NA~Canada":     "red",
12316  *     "EMEA~Portugal": "green"
12317  * };
12318  *                 
12319  * </pre>
12320  * <p>
12321  * Assumes that the default {@link pvc.options.charts.BasicChart#dataSeparator} is used.
12322  * 
12323  * <p>
12324  * 
12325  * @type map(string : pvc.options.varia.ColorString|pv.Color)
12326  * @category Discrete > Scale
12327  */
12328 pvc.options.axes.AnyColorAxis.prototype.map = undefined;

12748  * <tt>1</tt>.
12749  * 
12750  * @type number
12751  * @default 0.1
12752  * @category Discrete > Scale

12809 /**
12810  * The domain alignment to use when the domain has a fixed or implied length
12811  * (applies to continuous axes).
12812  * <p>
12813  * For more information, see: {@link #fixedLength}.
12814  * 
12815  * @type pvc.options.varia.AxisDomainAlign
12816  * @default 'center'
12817  * @category Numeric > Scale
12818  */
12819 pvc.options.axes.SizeAxis.prototype.domainAlign = undefined;
12820 /**
12821  * The fixed domain length that the axis will show
12822  * (applies to continuous axes).
12823  * <p>
12824  * A string value is converted to a number.
12825  * <p>
12826  * The value may be bigger or smaller than the actual
12827  * length of the data.
12828  * <p>
12829  * This property takes precedence over the property 
12830  * <tt>originIsZero</tt>, if specified either with 
12831  * 
12832  * <tt>fixedMin</tt>, 
12833  * <tt>fixedMax</tt> or 
12834  * <tt>domainAlign</tt>.
12835  * <p>
12836  * This property can be specified with several options to define the initial domain,
12837  * so that its length corresponds to the defined value.
12838  * They take the following precedence order:
12839  * 
12840  * <ol>
12841  * 
12842  * <li>
12843  * If 
12844  * <tt>fixedLength</tt> is not specified:
12845  * 
12846  * <ol>
12847  * 
12848  * <li>
12849  * If neither 
12850  * <tt>fixedMin</tt> and 
12851  * <tt>fixedMax</tt> are specified,
12852  * the axis domain is the data domain;
12853  * option 
12854  * <tt>originIsZero</tt> may augment the axis domain, on one of its sides;
12855  * </li>
12856  * 
12857  * <li>
12858  * If both 
12859  * <tt>fixedMin</tt> and 
12860  * <tt>fixedMax</tt> are specified,
12861  * the axis domain is fully determined; it's length is implied;
12862  * option 
12863  * <tt>originIsZero</tt> is ignored;
12864  * </li>
12865  * 
12866  * <li>
12867  * If 
12868  * <tt>fixedMin</tt> is specified (and 
12869  * <tt>fixedMax</tt> is not)
12870  * the axis domain minimum is 
12871  * <tt>fixedMin</tt> and
12872  * the axis domain maximum is the data domain maximum, possibly corrected by
12873  * option 
12874  * <tt>originIsZero</tt>;
12875  * </li>
12876  * 
12877  * <li>
12878  * Else, (if 
12879  * <tt>fixedMax</tt> is specified and 
12880  * <tt>fixedMin</tt> is not,)
12881  * the axis domain maximum is 
12882  * <tt>fixedMax</tt> and
12883  * the axis domain minimum is the data domain minimum, possibly corrected by
12884  * option 
12885  * <tt>originIsZero</tt>;
12886  * </li>
12887  * </ol>
12888  * </li>
12889  * 
12890  * <li>
12891  * If 
12892  * <tt>fixedLength</tt> is specified, option 
12893  * <tt>originIsZero</tt> is ignored.
12894  * <p>
12895  * The limits of the axis domain are determined as follows:
12896  * 
12897  * <ol>
12898  * 
12899  * <li>
12900  * If 
12901  * <tt>fixedMin</tt> is specified, the axis domain maximum is implied:
12902  * <br></br>
12903  * 
12904  * <tt>max = fixedMin + fixedLength</tt>;
12905  * <br></br>
12906  * options 
12907  * <tt>originIsZero</tt>, 
12908  * <tt>fixedMax</tt> are ignored;
12909  * option 
12910  * <tt>domainAlign</tt> is ignored in this phase;
12911  * </li>
12912  * 
12913  * <li>
12914  * If 
12915  * <tt>fixedMax</tt> is specified, the axis domain minimum is implied:
12916  * <br></br>
12917  * 
12918  * <tt>min = fixedMax - fixedLength</tt>;
12919  * <br></br>
12920  * option 
12921  * <tt>originIsZero</tt> is ignored;
12922  * option 
12923  * <tt>domainAlign</tt> is ignored in this phase;
12924  * </li>
12925  * 
12926  * <li>
12927  * Else, 
12928  * <tt>domainAlign</tt> is either specified or defaults to 
12929  * <tt>center</tt>.
12930  * The axis domain is aligned to either the minimum, maximum or center of the data domain
12931  * and then taken to have the specified fixed length.
12932  * <p>
12933  * It is determined as follows:
12934  * 
12935  * <ul>
12936  * 
12937  * <li>
12938  * If 
12939  * <tt>domainAlign</tt> is 
12940  * <tt>min</tt>, the axis domain minimum is that of
12941  * the actual data and the axis domain maximum is implied:
12942  * <br></br>
12943  * 
12944  * <tt>max = min(data) + fixedLength</tt>;
12945  * </li>
12946  * 
12947  * <li>
12948  * If 
12949  * <tt>domainAlign</tt> is 
12950  * <tt>max</tt>, the axis domain maximum is that of
12951  * the actual data and the axis domain minimum is implied:
12952  * <br></br>
12953  * 
12954  * <tt>min = max(data) - fixedLength</tt>;
12955  * </li>
12956  * 
12957  * <li>
12958  * Else, 
12959  * <tt>domainAlign</tt> is 
12960  * <tt>center</tt>, or defaults to it,
12961  * and both axis domain limits are determined from the actual data domain,
12962  * as follows:
12963  * 
12964  * <ul>
12965  * 
12966  * <li>
12967  * <tt>min = center(data) - fixedLength / 2</tt></li>
12968  * 
12969  * <li>
12970  * <tt>max = center(data) + fixedLength / 2</tt></li>
12971  * </ul>
12972  * where 
12973  * <tt>center(data)</tt> is determined as:
12974  * <br></br>
12975  * 
12976  * <tt>center(data) = (max(data) - min(data)) / 2</tt>.
12977  * </li>
12978  * </ul>
12979  * </li>
12980  * </ol>
12981  * </li>
12982  * </ol>
12983  * <p>
12984  * For more information, see:
12985  * {@link #fixedMin},
12986  * {@link #fixedMax},
12987  * {@link #domainAlign} and
12988  * {@link #originIsZero}.
12989  * 
12990  * @type number|string
12991  * @category Numeric > Scale
12992  */
12993 pvc.options.axes.SizeAxis.prototype.fixedLength = undefined;
12994 /**
12995  * The fixed maximum domain value that the axis will show
12996  * (applies to continuous axes).
12997  * <p>
12998  * A string value is converted to a number.
12999  * <p>
13000  * The value may be bigger or smaller than the actual maximum value of the data.
13001  * <p>
13002  * This property takes precedence over the property 
13003  * <tt>originIsZero</tt>.
13004  * <p>
13005  * This property is ignored if 
13006  * <tt>fixedMin</tt> and 
13007  * <tt>fixedLength</tt> are both specified.
13008  * The behavior is described as follows:
13009  * 
13010  * <ul>
13011  * 
13012  * <li>
13013  * 
13014  * <tt>fixedMin</tt>, 
13015  * <tt>fixedLength</tt> specified:
13016  * a fixed maximum is implied from the min and length values;
13017  * 
13018  * <tt>fixedMin</tt> is ignored
13019  * </li>
13020  * 
13021  * <li>
13022  * 
13023  * <tt>fixedMax</tt>, 
13024  * <tt>fixedLength</tt> specified, without 
13025  * <tt>fixedMin</tt>:
13026  * a fixed minimum is implied from the max and length values
13027  * </li>
13028  * 
13029  * <li>
13030  * 
13031  * <tt>fixedMin</tt>, 
13032  * <tt>fixedMax</tt> specified, without 
13033  * <tt>fixedLength</tt>:
13034  * the fixed maximum and minimum are set directly
13035  * </li>
13036  * </ul>
13037  * <p>
13038  * For more information, see:
13039  * {@link #fixedMin} and
13040  * {@link #fixedLength}.
13041  * 
13042  * @type number|string
13043  * @category Numeric > Scale
13044  */
13045 pvc.options.axes.SizeAxis.prototype.fixedMax = undefined;
13046 /**
13047  * The fixed minimum domain value that the axis will show
13048  * (applies to continuous axes).
13049  * <p>
13050  * A string value is converted to a number.
13051  * <p>
13052  * The value may be bigger or smaller than the actual

13054  * <p>
13055  * This property can be specified with the following options, in order of precedence:

13077  * {@link #fixedLength} and
13078  * {@link #fixedMax}.

13080  * @type number|string

13121 /**
13122  * The options documentation class of
13123  * the cartesian axis
13124  * and cartesian axis panel.
13125  * <p>
13126  * A cartesian axis (and its panel) can be referred to in several ways,
13127  * in order of precedence:
13128  * 
13129  * <dl>
13130  * 
13131  * <dt>By 
13132  * <b>id</b></dt>
13133  * 
13134  * <dd>the id of the axis is its type followed by it's index (when >= 2)</dd>
13135  * 
13136  * <dd>(e.g.: 
13137  * <tt>base</tt>, 
13138  * <tt>ortho</tt>, 
13139  * <tt>base2</tt>, 
13140  * <tt>ortho2</tt>, ...)</dd>
13141  * 
13142  * <dt>By 
13143  * <b>oriented id</b></dt>
13144  * 
13145  * <dd>the oriented id of the axis is its orientation followed by it's index (when >= 2)</dd>
13146  * 
13147  * <dd>(e.g.: 
13148  * <tt>x</tt>, 
13149  * <tt>y</tt>, 
13150  * <tt>x2</tt>, 
13151  * <tt>y2</tt>, ...)</dd>
13152  * 
13153  * <dt>By 
13154  * <b>legacy name</b></dt>
13155  * 
13156  * <dd>
13157  * for the special case of the bar chart,
13158  * the second axes:
13159  * 
13160  * <ul>
13161  * 
13162  * <li>
13163  * 
13164  * <b>normal properties</b> —
13165  * may be referred to by the name 
13166  * <tt>second</tt>
13167  * </li>
13168  * 
13169  * <li>
13170  * 
13171  * <b>extension points</b> —
13172  * may be referred to by the names 
13173  * <tt>secondX</tt> and 
13174  * <tt>secondY</tt>
13175  * </li>
13176  * </ul>
13177  * <p>
13178  * In any case, those names are now deprecated.
13179  * </dd>
13180  * 
13181  * <dt>By 
13182  * <b>scale type</b></dt>
13183  * 
13184  * <dd>
13185  * the scale type can be 
13186  * <tt>discrete</tt> or 
13187  * <tt>continuous</tt> and,
13188  * in the latter case, with higher precedence,
13189  * 
13190  * <tt>numeric</tt> and 
13191  * <tt>timeSeries</tt> are also possible
13192  * </dd>
13193  * 
13194  * <dt>By 
13195  * <b>catch all name</b></dt>
13196  * 
13197  * <dd>the name 
13198  * <tt>axis</tt> matches any cartesian axis</dd>
13199  * </dl>
13200  * <p>
13201  * These names apply equally to the prefixes used to
13202  * build extension point names.
13203  * <p>
13204  * Which of the names is used depends on
13205  * which better selects the axes for the properties being specified.
13206  * If a property should only be applied to vertical axes,
13207  * independently of the chart's orientation, the 
13208  * <i>oriented id</i>
13209  * should be used.
13210  * If, otherwise, a property should only be applied to the base axis,
13211  * whether or not it is horizontally aligned,
13212  * then the normal 
13213  * <i>id</i> should be used.
13214  * If, a property should only apply to continuous axes,
13215  * the 
13216  * <i>scale type</i> should be used.
13217  * <p>
13218  * For more information on options
13219  * that are specific to only certain axis types,
13220  * please see one of the following concrete sub-classes:
13221  * 
13222  * <ul>
13223  * 
13224  * <li>
13225  * Numeric-only axes: {@link pvc.options.axes.NumericCartesianAxis}
13226  * </li>
13227  * 
13228  * <li>
13229  * Normal discrete: {@link pvc.options.axes.FlattenedDiscreteCartesianAxis}
13230  * </li>
13231  * 
13232  * <li>
13233  * Numeric or time-series: {@link pvc.options.axes.AnyContinuousCartesianAxis}
13234  * </li>
13235  * 
13236  * <li>
13237  * Normal or hierarchical discrete:: {@link pvc.options.axes.AnyDiscreteCartesianAxis}
13238  * </li>
13239  * 
13240  * <li>
13241  * Numeric, time-series or normal discrete: {@link pvc.options.axes.AnyNonHierarchicalCartesianAxis}
13242  * </li>
13243  * </ul>
13244  * 
13245  * @class
13246  * @extends pvc.options.panels.Panel
13247  * @abstract
13248  */
13249 pvc.options.axes.CartesianAxis = function(){};

13254 /**
13255  * The percentage padding,
13256  * on each of the sides of the plot panel
13257  * that are orthogonal to the axis orientation.
13258  * <p>
13259  * The percentage is a number
13260  * greater than or equal to 
13261  * <tt>0</tt> and less than

13264  * has the same direction as the axis.
13265  * <p>

13267  * between the plot's visual elements and the axes panels.
13268  * <p>
13269  * If an axis is horizontal,
13270  * the padding affects the left and right sides,
13271  * and if it is vertical,
13272  * affects the top and bottom sides.
13273  * <p>
13274  * If more than one axis of a given orientation specifies an offset,
13275  * the maximum specified offset is used.

13289  * For an vertical axis, it is 
13290  * <tt>left</tt>.
13291  * For axes other than the first,
13292  * the default side is the opposite of that of the first axis:
13293  *

13379 /**
13380  * Indicates if grid rules are drawn

13388 pvc.options.axes.CartesianAxis.prototype.grid = undefined;
13389 /**
13390  * A tick formatter function.
13391  * <p>
13392  * This function has two arguments variants:
13393  * 
13394  * <dl>
13395  * 
13396  * <dt>continuous</dt> 
13397  * <dd>tickFormatter(value, precision, index)</dd>
13398  * 
13399  * <dt>discrete</dt>   
13400  * <dd>tickFormatter(value, label)</dd>
13401  * </dl>
13402  * <p>
13403  * Generally,
13404  * a continuous axis uses the 
13405  * <i>continuous</i> variant and
13406  * a discrete axis uses the 
13407  * <i>discrete</i> variant.
13408  * <p>
13409  * But, there is one exception to this rule:
13410  * a discrete axis having a single date dimension,
13411  * uses the 
13412  * <i>continuous</i> variant.
13413  * This makes it easier to format date categories,
13414  * by automatically choosing an adequate precision,
13415  * that takes the actual data range into account.
13416  * It's also legacy, version 1, behavior.
13417  * Use the compatibility flag
13418  * {@link pvc.options.varia.CompatibilityFlags#discreteTimeSeriesTickFormat}
13419  * to disable this formatting mode.
13420  * <p>
13421  * Summing up:
13422  * 
13423  * <ul>
13424  * 
13425  * <li>a continuous axis uses the 
13426  * <i>continuous</i> arguments variant,</li>
13427  * 
13428  * <li>a discrete axis can use both arguments variant,</li>
13429  * 
13430  * <li>an axis with a single date dimension, uses the 
13431  * <i>continuous</i> arguments variant
13432  * (if {@link pvc.options.varia.CompatibilityFlags#discreteTimeSeriesTickFormat} is
13433  * 
13434  * <tt>true</tt>).</li>
13435  * </ul>
13436  * 
13437  * <p>
13438  * <b>Context object</b></p>
13439  * <p>
13440  * The function is called having as 
13441  * <tt>this</tt> the ticks array,
13442  * whose tick values are being formatted.
13443  * <p>
13444  * Together with the 
13445  * <i>index</i> argument,
13446  * it is possible to use the value of the previous and/or following ticks
13447  * to format the current tick.
13448  * <p>
13449  * The ticks array provides the following useful properties:
13450  * 
13451  * <ul>
13452  * 
13453  * <li>step — the used precision</li>
13454  * 
13455  * <li>base — the base precision from which step is derived</li>
13456  * 
13457  * <li>mult — the multiple of base precision that yields step (step = base * mult)</li>
13458  * 
13459  * <li>format(v) - the default formatting function</li>
13460  * 
13461  * <li>length — the number of ticks</li>
13462  * </ul>
13463  * 
13464  * @returns {string}
13465  * The string that is the formatted value.
13466  * 
13467  * @method
13468  * @this Array
13469  * @param {string|number|Date} value
13470  * The value to format.
13471  * 
13472  * <dl>
13473  * 
13474  * <dt>
13475  * <i>continuous</i> arguments variant</dt>
13476  * 
13477  * <dd>
13478  * The type of argument 
13479  * <i>value</i> can be 
13480  * <i>number</i> or 
13481  * <i>Date</i>.
13482  * </dd>
13483  * 
13484  * <dt>
13485  * <i>discrete</i> arguments variant</dt>
13486  * 
13487  * <dd>
13488  * The type of argument 
13489  * <i>value</i> can be 
13490  * <i>string</i> or 
13491  * <i>number</i>.
13492  * <p>
13493  * When the axis has a single dimension,
13494  * argument 
13495  * <i>value</i> is the 
13496  * <b>value</b> of that dimension.
13497  * <p>
13498  * When the axis has more than one dimension, and is flattened,
13499  * argument 
13500  * <i>value</i> is the junction of the 
13501  * <b>key</b> values of all dimensions,
13502  * separated by {@link pvc.options.charts.BasicChart#dataSeparator}.
13503  * <p>
13504  * When the axis is hierarchical (composite),
13505  * argument 
13506  * <i>value</i> is the 
13507  * <b>key</b> value of the dimension at a certain level.
13508  * </dd>
13509  * </dl>
13510  * 
13511  * @param {number} [precision]
13512  * The precision in which the 
13513  * <i>value</i> argument should be formatted.
13514  * 
13515  * <p>
13516  * <b>ATTENTION:</b> only present in the 
13517  * <i>continuous</i> arguments variant!</p>
13518  * <p>
13519  * When the axis has a 
13520  * <b>date</b> scale type,
13521  * the argument is the chosen 
13522  * 
13523  * <i>number of milliseconds</i> between tick values.
13524  * <p>
13525  * The standard time precisions are defined in:
13526  * {@link pvc.options.varia.TimeInterval}.
13527  * <p>
13528  * In general, the given precision is an integer multiple of one the standard precisions.
13529  * It is many times more useful to use the base standard precision on which the final precision is based on
13530  * (the value of the context property 
13531  * <tt>this.base</tt>).
13532  * <p>
13533  * When the axis has a 
13534  * <b>numeric</b> scale type,
13535  * the argument is the 
13536  * <i>number of decimal places</i> of
13537  * the chosen step value.
13538  * 
13539  * @param {number} [index]
13540  * The index of the tick being formatted.
13541  * 
13542  * <p>
13543  * <b>ATTENTION:</b> only present in the 
13544  * <i>continuous</i> arguments variant!</p>
13545  * <p>
13546  * You may use the index to access neighbouring ticks from the 
13547  * <tt>this</tt> ticks array
13548  * (e..g. 
13549  * <tt>this[index + 1]</tt>).
13550  * 
13551  * @param {string} [label]
13552  * The default label.
13553  * 
13554  * <p>
13555  * <b>ATTENTION:</b> only present in the 
13556  * <i>discrete</i> arguments variant!</p>
13557  * <p>
13558  * The default label is the label that would be displayed
13559  * if the tick formatter had not been specified.
13560  * <p>
13561  * When the axis has a single dimension,
13562  * argument 
13563  * <i>label</i> is the 
13564  * <b>label</b> as formatted by that dimension.
13565  * <p>
13566  * When the axis has more than one dimension, and is flattened,
13567  * argument 
13568  * <i>label</i> is the junction of the 
13569  * <b>label</b> values of all dimensions,
13570  * separated by {@link pvc.options.charts.BasicChart#groupedLabelSep}.
13571  * <p>
13572  * When the axis is hierarchical (composite),
13573  * argument 
13574  * <i>label</i> is the 
13575  * <b>label</b> as formatted by the dimension at a certain level.
13576  * 
13577  * @category Style
13578  */
13579 pvc.options.axes.CartesianAxis.prototype.tickFormatter = function(){};

13582  * 
13583  * @type string|pvc.options.panels.CartesianAxisTitlePanel
13584  * @category Style
13585  */
13586 pvc.options.axes.CartesianAxis.prototype.title = undefined;

13724 /**
13725  * The size, in pixels, of the bands used to represent the discrete domain values (applies to discrete axes).
13726  * <p>
13727  * A non-negative number.
13728  * 
13729  * <p>
13730  * 
13731  * <b>In multi-charts</b>
13732  * <p>
13733  * The current layout algorithm used by multi-charts does not support
13734  * minimum, fixed or maximum sizes in small charts.
13735  * As such, the simples band size ratio model always needs to be used.
13736  * <p>
13737  * The minimum, fixed and maximum sizes and spacings are used to determine an
13738  * equivalent or best-possible band size ratio.
13739  * </p>
13740  * 
13741  * <p>
13742  * 
13743  * <b>Band Size, Spacing, Ratio and Step</b>
13744  * <p>
13745  * The band layout arranges bands and space in the following way.
13746  * Taking 
13747  * <i>B</i> to represent 
13748  * <i>bandSize</i>,
13749  * 
13750  * <i>E</i> to represent {@link #bandSpacing} and
13751  * 
13752  * <i>e</i> to be 
13753  * <tt>E/2</tt>,
13754  * bands and space will follow the pattern:
13755  * 
13756  * <tt>eBe</tt>, 
13757  * <tt>eBEBe</tt>, 
13758  * <tt>eBEBEBe</tt>, ...
13759  * <p>
13760  * For a given pair of 
13761  * <i>B</i> and 
13762  * <i>E</i>, each discrete category will occupy a space given by
13763  * the 
13764  * <i>step</i>, 
13765  * <i>S</i>:
13766  * <br></br>
13767  * 
13768  * <i>S = B + E</i>.
13769  * <p>
13770  * Given the number of discrete categories, a cartesian panel (axis or plot) will have
13771  * corresponding fixed or minimum and maximum sizes.
13772  * <p>
13773  * The option {@link #bandSizeRatio}, R, is used, in under-constrained cases,
13774  * to relate 
13775  * <i>B</i> and 
13776  * <i>E</i>:
13777  * <br></br>
13778  * 
13779  * <i>B = R * S</i>
13780  * </p>
13781  * 
13782  * <p>
13783  * 
13784  * <b>Impact on chart size</b>
13785  * <p>
13786  * If the chart size along the axis' dimension
13787  * is such that the available space is less than the
13788  * determined fixed or minimum size,
13789  * then the chart will grow as much as needed to accommodate the fixed or minimum size,
13790  * along that dimension.
13791  * <p>
13792  * If, on the contrary, the chart size along the axis' dimension
13793  * is greater than the determined fixed or maximum size,
13794  * the plot and axis content will be centered in the available space.
13795  * </p>
13796  * 
13797  * <p>
13798  * 
13799  * <b>Option values harmonization</b>
13800  * <p>
13801  * When both {@link #bandSizeMax} and {@link #bandSizeMin} are specified,
13802  * and {@link #bandSizeMax} is less than or equal to 
13803  * <i>bandSizeMin</i>,
13804  * then {@link #bandSize} is set to the the minimum value.
13805  * <p>
13806  * When both 
13807  * <i>bandSize</i> and {@link #bandSizeMin} are specified,
13808  * and 
13809  * <i>bandSize</i> is less than 
13810  * <i>bandSizeMin</i>,
13811  * then the minimum value is used instead.
13812  * <p>
13813  * When both 
13814  * <i>bandSpacing</i> and {@link #bandSpacingMin} are specified,
13815  * and 
13816  * <i>bandSpacing</i> is less than 
13817  * <i>bandSpacingMin</i>,
13818  * then the minimum value is used instead.
13819  * <p>
13820  * When both {@link #bandSpacingMax} and {@link #bandSpacingMin} are specified,
13821  * and {@link #bandSpacingMax} is less than or equal to 
13822  * <i>bandSpacingMin</i>,
13823  * then {@link #bandSpacing} is set to the the minimum value.
13824  * </p>
13825  * 
13826  * <p>
13827  * 
13828  * <b>The algorithm</b>
13829  * <p>
13830  * The options you specify should just behave as you'd expected them to.
13831  * At least, after thinking about them for a while.
13832  * <p>
13833  * If doubts remain on which options and values should be specified,
13834  * or on why the specified options are behaving in a certain way,
13835  * you can follow this explanation of the band layout algorithm.
13836  * </p>
13837  * 
13838  * <ul>
13839  * 
13840  * <li>
13841  * When both 
13842  * <i>bandSize</i> and {@link #bandSpacing} are specified, the layout is 
13843  * <b>fixed</b>.
13844  * <p>
13845  * When they both have the value 
13846  * <tt>0</tt>, then the layout is reevaluated as if they had not been specified.
13847  * <p>
13848  * The option {@link #bandSizeRatio} is ignored.
13849  * </li>
13850  * 
13851  * <li>
13852  * When one and only one of 
13853  * <i>bandSize</i> or {@link #bandSpacing} is specified,
13854  * the layout is 
13855  * <b>partially fixed</b>.
13856  * <p>
13857  * For the variable option, size or spacing,
13858  * any specified minimum and/or maximum options are still considered.
13859  * <p>
13860  * This configuration does not define a fixed step size,
13861  * but instead constrains the range of step size values.
13862  * <p>
13863  * The option {@link #bandSizeRatio} is ignored.
13864  * </li>
13865  * 
13866  * <li>
13867  * When neither 
13868  * <i>bandSize</i> nor {@link #bandSpacing} are specified,
13869  * the layout is 
13870  * <b>strictly variable</b>.
13871  * <p>
13872  * There are several cases:
13873  * 
13874  * <ul>
13875  * 
13876  * <li>
13877  * When none of the minimum and maximum values, of both size and spacing, are specified,
13878  * the size and spacing are governed solely by the {@link #bandSizeRatio}, 
13879  * <i>R</i>.
13880  * <p>
13881  * This is the way the band layout used to behave,
13882  * before the existence of the fixed, minimum and maximum options.
13883  * <p>
13884  * Small-charts continue to behave this way,
13885  * although with a band size ratio that is determined from the
13886  * the other specified options.
13887  * <p>
13888  * The half-line 
13889  * <i>(E,B)</i> departs from 
13890  * <i>(0,0)</i>
13891  * and goes on indefinitely with a slope given by 
13892  * <i>R</i>: 
13893  * <i>E = (1/R - 1) * B</i>.
13894  * </li>
13895  * 
13896  * <li>
13897  * 
13898  * <p>
13899  * When minimum and maximum values, of both size and spacing, are specified,
13900  * the size and spacing are constrained to belong to the
13901  * line segment 
13902  * <i>(E,B)</i>, that goes from point 
13903  * <i>(Emin,Bmin)</i> to point 
13904  * <i>(Emax,Bmax)</i>.
13905  * </p>
13906  * </li>
13907  * 
13908  * <li>
13909  * 
13910  * <p>
13911  * When only the minimum size and spacing values are specified,
13912  * the size and spacing are constrained to belong to the
13913  * line segment 
13914  * <i>(E,B)</i>, that goes from point 
13915  * <i>(0,0)</i> to point 
13916  * <i>(Emin,Bmin)</i>.
13917  * </p>
13918  * </li>
13919  * 
13920  * <li>
13921  * 
13922  * <p>
13923  * When only the maximum size and spacing values are specified,
13924  * the size and spacing are constrained to belong to the
13925  * line segment 
13926  * <i>(E,B)</i>, that goes from point 
13927  * <i>(0,0)</i> to point 
13928  * <i>(Emax,Bmax)</i>.
13929  * </p>
13930  * </li>
13931  * 
13932  * <li>
13933  * In all the following mixed and under-constrained cases,
13934  * option {@link #bandSizeRatio}, 
13935  * <i>R</i>, is taken into account.
13936  * <p>
13937  * The size and spacing are constrained to belong to the the line 
13938  * <i>(E,B)</i> that
13939  * passes through 
13940  * <i>(0,0)</i> and has a slope
13941  * given by 
13942  * <i>R</i>: 
13943  * <i>E = (1/R - 1) * B</i>.
13944  * <p>
13945  * Again, a few more cases:
13946  * 
13947  * <ul>
13948  * 
13949  * <li>
13950  * 
13951  * <p>
13952  * When only the minimum and maximum size values are specified,
13953  * the corresponding spacing values are implied.
13954  * </p>
13955  * </li>
13956  * 
13957  * <li>
13958  * 
13959  * <p>
13960  * When only the minimum and maximum spacing values are specified,
13961  * the corresponding size values are implied.
13962  * </p>
13963  * </li>
13964  * 
13965  * <li>
13966  * When only the minimum size and the maximum spacing values are specified,
13967  * the specified minimum size implies a minimum spacing and
13968  * the specified maximum spacing implies a maximum size.
13969  * <p>
13970  * If the implied minimum spacing is greater than or equal to the specified
13971  * maximum spacing, the algorithm is reevaluated using a fixed spacing
13972  * equal to the implied minimum spacing.
13973  * </li>
13974  * 
13975  * <li>
13976  * When only the maximum size and the minimum spacing values are specified,
13977  * the specified maximum size implies a maximum spacing and
13978  * the specified minimum spacing implies a minimum size.
13979  * <p>
13980  * If the implied minimum size is greater than or equal to the specified
13981  * maximum size, the algorithm is reevaluated using a fixed size
13982  * equal to the implied minimum size.
13983  * </li>
13984  * </ul>
13985  * </li>
13986  * </ul>
13987  * </li>
13988  * </ul>
13989  * <p>
13990  * See other band-control options:
13991  * {@link #bandSpacing},
13992  * {@link #bandSizeMin},
13993  * {@link #bandSizeMax},
13994  * {@link #bandSpacingMin},
13995  * {@link #bandSpacingMax} and,
13996  * for charts that give it representation,
13997  * {@link #bandSizeRatio}.
13998  * 
13999  * @type number
14000  * @category Discrete > Layout
14001  */
14002 pvc.options.axes.AnyNonHierarchicalCartesianAxis.prototype.bandSize = undefined;
14003 /**
14004  * The maximum size, in pixels, of the bands used to represent the discrete domain values (applies to discrete axes).
14005  * <p>
14006  * A non-negative number.
14007  * <p>
14008  * See {@link #bandSize} for information on the band layout algorithm.
14009  * 
14010  * @type number
14011  * @category Discrete > Layout
14012  */
14013 pvc.options.axes.AnyNonHierarchicalCartesianAxis.prototype.bandSizeMax = undefined;
14014 /**
14015  * The minimum size, in pixels, of the bands used to represent the discrete domain values (applies to discrete axes).
14016  * <p>
14017  * A non-negative number.
14018  * <p>
14019  * See {@link #bandSize} for information on the band layout algorithm.
14020  * 
14021  * @type number
14022  * @category Discrete > Layout
14023  */
14024 pvc.options.axes.AnyNonHierarchicalCartesianAxis.prototype.bandSizeMin = undefined;
14025 /**
14026  * The ratio of the band size over the
14027  * total size (band + spacing),
14028  * in a discrete axis band (applies to discrete axes).
14029  * <p>
14030  * A number between 
14031  * <tt>0</tt> and

14033  * <p>
14034  * The default value of this property is that of the legacy option 
14035  * <i>panelSizeRatio</i>,
14036  * defined for the Bar-family, Box-Plot and the Heat-Grid charts.
14037  * <p>
14038  * This option is only used when
14039  * the band model is under-constrained
14040  * by the fixed, minimum, and maximum size and spacing options.
14041  * <p>
14042  * See {@link #bandSize} for information on the band layout algorithm.
14043  * 
14044  * @type number
14045  * @category Discrete > Layout
14046  */
14047 pvc.options.axes.AnyNonHierarchicalCartesianAxis.prototype.bandSizeRatio = undefined;
14048 /**
14049  * The space, in pixels, separating/surrounding bands (applies to discrete axes).
14050  * <p>
14051  * A non-negative number.
14052  * <p>

14054  * 
14055  * @type number

14058 pvc.options.axes.AnyNonHierarchicalCartesianAxis.prototype.bandSpacing = undefined;
14059 /**
14060  * The maximum space, in pixels, separating/surrounding bands (applies to discrete axes).
14061  * <p>
14062  * A non-negative number.
14063  * <p>
14064  * See {@link #bandSize} for information on the band layout algorithm.
14065  * 
14066  * @type number
14067  * @category Discrete > Layout
14068  */
14069 pvc.options.axes.AnyNonHierarchicalCartesianAxis.prototype.bandSpacingMax = undefined;
14070 /**
14071  * The minimum space, in pixels, separating/surrounding bands (applies to discrete axes).
14072  * <p>
14073  * A non-negative number.
14074  * <p>
14075  * See {@link #bandSize} for information on the band layout algorithm.
14076  * 
14077  * @type number
14078  * @category Discrete > Layout
14079  */
14080 pvc.options.axes.AnyNonHierarchicalCartesianAxis.prototype.bandSpacingMin = undefined;
14081 /**
14082  * The domain alignment to use when the domain has a fixed or implied length (applies to continuous axes).
14083  * <p>
14084  * For more information, see {@link #fixedLength}.
14085  * 
14086  * @type pvc.options.varia.AxisDomainAlign
14087  * @default 'center'
14088  * @category Continuous > Scale
14089  */
14090 pvc.options.axes.AnyNonHierarchicalCartesianAxis.prototype.domainAlign = undefined;
14091 /**
14092  * Controls the type of scale domain coordination that should be performed
14093  * amongst the axes of the same id of each 
14094  * <i>small chart</i> (applies to continuous axes).
14095  * <p>
14096  * The value {@link pvc.options.varia.AxisDomainScope#Row}
14097  * can only be specified if the axis has vertical orientation.
14098  * Conversely,
14099  * the value {@link pvc.options.varia.AxisDomainScope#Column}
14100  * can only be specified if the axis has horizontal orientation.
14101  * 
14102  * @type pvc.options.varia.AxisDomainScope
14103  * @default 'global'
14104  * @category Continuous > Scale
14105  */
14106 pvc.options.axes.AnyNonHierarchicalCartesianAxis.prototype.domainScope = undefined;
14107 /**
14108  * The fixed length of the axis domain (applies to continuous axes).
14109  * <p>
14110  * A string value is converted to a number.
14111  * <p>
14112  * The value may be bigger or smaller than the actual length of the data.
14113  * <p>
14114  * By default, the domain of the axis is determined from the actual domain of the data.
14115  * This and other options allow modifying the axis domain.
14116  * <p>
14117  * When the axis domain gets smaller than the data domain,
14118  * and {@link pvc.options.charts.CartesianChart#leafContentOverflow} is set to 
14119  * <tt>auto</tt>,
14120  * the default value,
14121  * clipping is activated in the related plot panels and any overflown content is hidden.
14122  * 
14123  * <h3>Phase I</h3>
14124  * <p>
14125  * The phase I axis domain is determined by the following procedure:
14126  * 
14127  * <ol>
14128  * 
14129  * <li>
14130  * If 
14131  * <tt>fixedLength</tt> is not specified:
14132  * 
14133  * <ol>
14134  * 
14135  * <li>
14136  * If neither 
14137  * <tt>fixedMin</tt> and 
14138  * <tt>fixedMax</tt> are specified,
14139  * the axis domain is the data domain;
14140  * option 
14141  * <tt>originIsZero</tt> may augment the axis domain, on one of its sides;
14142  * </li>
14143  * 
14144  * <li>
14145  * If both 
14146  * <tt>fixedMin</tt> and 
14147  * <tt>fixedMax</tt> are specified,
14148  * the axis domain is fully determined; it's length is implied;
14149  * option 
14150  * <tt>originIsZero</tt> is ignored;
14151  * </li>
14152  * 
14153  * <li>
14154  * If 
14155  * <tt>fixedMin</tt> is specified (and 
14156  * <tt>fixedMax</tt> is not)
14157  * the axis domain minimum is 
14158  * <tt>fixedMin</tt> and
14159  * the axis domain maximum is the data domain maximum, possibly corrected by
14160  * option 
14161  * <tt>originIsZero</tt>;
14162  * </li>
14163  * 
14164  * <li>
14165  * Else, (if 
14166  * <tt>fixedMax</tt> is specified and 
14167  * <tt>fixedMin</tt> is not,)
14168  * the axis domain maximum is 
14169  * <tt>fixedMax</tt> and
14170  * the axis domain minimum is the data domain minimum, possibly corrected by
14171  * option 
14172  * <tt>originIsZero</tt>;
14173  * </li>
14174  * </ol>
14175  * </li>
14176  * 
14177  * <li>
14178  * If 
14179  * <tt>fixedLength</tt> is specified, option 
14180  * <tt>originIsZero</tt> is ignored.
14181  * <p>
14182  * The limits of the axis domain are determined as follows:
14183  * 
14184  * <ol>
14185  * 
14186  * <li>
14187  * If 
14188  * <tt>fixedMin</tt> is specified, the axis domain maximum is implied:
14189  * <br></br>
14190  * 
14191  * <tt>max = fixedMin + fixedLength</tt>;
14192  * <br></br>
14193  * options 
14194  * <tt>originIsZero</tt>, 
14195  * <tt>fixedMax</tt> are ignored;
14196  * option 
14197  * <tt>domainAlign</tt> is ignored in this phase;
14198  * </li>
14199  * 
14200  * <li>
14201  * If 
14202  * <tt>fixedMax</tt> is specified, the axis domain minimum is implied:
14203  * <br></br>
14204  * 
14205  * <tt>min = fixedMax - fixedLength</tt>;
14206  * <br></br>
14207  * option 
14208  * <tt>originIsZero</tt> is ignored;
14209  * option 
14210  * <tt>domainAlign</tt> is ignored in this phase;
14211  * </li>
14212  * 
14213  * <li>
14214  * Else, 
14215  * <tt>domainAlign</tt> is either specified or defaults to 
14216  * <tt>center</tt>.
14217  * The axis domain is aligned to either the minimum, maximum or center of the data domain
14218  * and then taken to have the specified fixed length.
14219  * <p>
14220  * It is determined as follows:
14221  * 
14222  * <ul>
14223  * 
14224  * <li>
14225  * If 
14226  * <tt>domainAlign</tt> is 
14227  * <tt>min</tt>, the axis domain minimum is that of
14228  * the actual data and the axis domain maximum is implied:
14229  * <br></br>
14230  * 
14231  * <tt>max = min(data) + fixedLength</tt>;
14232  * </li>
14233  * 
14234  * <li>
14235  * If 
14236  * <tt>domainAlign</tt> is 
14237  * <tt>max</tt>, the axis domain maximum is that of
14238  * the actual data and the axis domain minimum is implied:
14239  * <br></br>
14240  * 
14241  * <tt>min = max(data) - fixedLength</tt>;
14242  * </li>
14243  * 
14244  * <li>
14245  * Else, 
14246  * <tt>domainAlign</tt> is 
14247  * <tt>center</tt>, or defaults to it,
14248  * and both axis domain limits are determined from the actual data domain,
14249  * as follows:
14250  * 
14251  * <ul>
14252  * 
14253  * <li>
14254  * <tt>min = center(data) - fixedLength / 2</tt></li>
14255  * 
14256  * <li>
14257  * <tt>max = center(data) + fixedLength / 2</tt></li>
14258  * </ul>
14259  * where 
14260  * <tt>center(data)</tt> is determined as:
14261  * <br></br>
14262  * 
14263  * <tt>center(data) = (max(data) - min(data)) / 2</tt>.
14264  * </li>
14265  * </ul>
14266  * </li>
14267  * </ol>
14268  * </li>
14269  * </ol>
14270  * 
14271  * <h3>Phase II</h3>
14272  * <p>
14273  * In phase II, additional options may modify the phase I axis domain.
14274  * <p>
14275  * If {@link #domainRoundMode} is 
14276  * <tt>nice</tt>, the axis domain is made "nice",
14277  * by making sure that its ends are "nice" numbers.
14278  * <p>
14279  * If {@link #ratio} is specified (or a ratio is imposed due to {@link preserveRatio}),
14280  * the length of the axis domain is imposed by the length of the axis' range (a number of pixels).
14281  * The axis domain is aligned relative to the phase I axis domain, according to the value
14282  * of {@link #domainAlign}.
14283  * <p>
14284  * If {@link #domainRoundMode} is 
14285  * <tt>tick</tt>,
14286  * the phase I axis domain is extended to include the calculated ticks and only then are
14287  * the 
14288  * <tt>ratio</tt> and 
14289  * <tt>domainAlign</tt> options processed, so that the domain aligns to
14290  * the calculated ticks.
14291  * 
14292  * <h3>Default</h3>
14293  * <p>
14294  * If a sliding window exists, it is its length {@link pvc.options.SlidingWindow#length},
14295  * otherwise, 
14296  * <tt>null</tt>.
14297  * <p>
14298  * For more information, see:
14299  * {@link #fixedMin},
14300  * {@link #fixedMax},
14301  * {@link #domainAlign},
14302  * {@link #ratio} and
14303  * {@link #originIsZero}.
14304  * 
14305  * @type number|pvc.options.varia.TimeInterval
14306  * @category Continuous > Scale
14307  */
14308 pvc.options.axes.AnyNonHierarchicalCartesianAxis.prototype.fixedLength = undefined;
14309 /**
14310  * The fixed maximum value of the axis domain (applies to continuous axes).
14311  * <p>
14312  * The value is converted using the {@link pvc.options.DimensionType#converter} of
14313  * the first dimension of the first role bound to the axis.
14314  * <p>
14315  * For example, if the base axis shows the 
14316  * <i>category</i> dimension,
14317  * and the dimension is configured as type 
14318  * <tt>Date</tt>,
14319  * and it uses the default converter, then it accepts:
14320  * 
14321  * <ul>
14322  * 
14323  * <li>
14324  * values of type 
14325  * <tt>number</tt>,
14326  * representing milliseconds as returned by
14327  * the JavaScript's 
14328  * <tt>Date.getTime()</tt> method;
14329  * </li>
14330  * 
14331  * <li>
14332  * values of type 
14333  * <tt>Date</tt>, which are accepted as is;
14334  * </li>
14335  * 
14336  * <li>
14337  * values of type 
14338  * <tt>string</tt>,
14339  * in a format defined by the dimension's
14340  * {@link pvc.options.DimensionType#rawFormat}.
14341  * </li>
14342  * </ul>
14343  * <p>
14344  * The value may be bigger or smaller than the maximum value of the data domain.
14345  * <p>
14346  * For more information, see {@link #fixedLength}.
14347  * 
14348  * @type number|string|Date
14349  * @category Continuous > Scale
14350  */
14351 pvc.options.axes.AnyNonHierarchicalCartesianAxis.prototype.fixedMax = undefined;
14352 /**
14353  * The fixed minimum value of the axis domain (applies to continuous axes).
14354  * <p>
14355  * The value is converted using the
14356  * {@link pvc.options.DimensionType#converter} of
14357  * the first dimension of the first role bound to the axis.
14358  * <p>
14359  * For example, if the base axis shows the 
14360  * <i>category</i> dimension,
14361  * and the dimension is configured as type Date,
14362  * and it uses the default converter, then it accepts:
14363  * 
14364  * <ul>
14365  * 
14366  * <li>values of type 
14367  * <tt>number</tt>,
14368  * representing milliseconds as returned by
14369  * the JavaScript's 
14370  * <tt>Date.getTime()</tt> method
14371  * </li>
14372  * 
14373  * <li>values of type 
14374  * <tt>Date</tt>, which are accepted as is</li>
14375  * 
14376  * <li>values of type 
14377  * <tt>string</tt>,
14378  * in a format defined by the dimension's
14379  * {@link pvc.options.DimensionType#rawFormat}.
14380  * </li>
14381  * </ul>
14382  * <p>
14383  * The value may be bigger or smaller than the minimum value of the data domain.
14384  * <p>
14385  * For more information, see {@link #fixedLength}.
14386  * 
14387  * @type number|string|Date
14388  * @category Continuous > Scale
14389  */
14390 pvc.options.axes.AnyNonHierarchicalCartesianAxis.prototype.fixedMin = undefined;
14391 /**
14392  * Indicates if it should be ensured that the 0 domain value is shown (applies to numeric axes).
14393  * <p>
14394  * The properties
14395  * 
14396  * <tt>fixedMin</tt> and
14397  * 
14398  * <tt>fixedMax</tt> have precedence over this one.
14399  * <p>
14400  * If this property is 
14401  * <tt>true</tt>
14402  * and respecting it would require changing
14403  * the minimum value,
14404  * but the option

14407  * The same would apply if
14408  * it were required to change
14409  * the maximum value,
14410  * but the property 
14411  * <tt>fixedMax</tt> was also specified.
14412  * <p>
14413  * For more information, see: {@link #fixedLength}.
14414  * 
14415  * @type boolean
14416  * @category Continuous > Scale
14417  */
14418 pvc.options.axes.AnyNonHierarchicalCartesianAxis.prototype.originIsZero = undefined;
14419 /**
14420  * Indicates if the initial proportion between the axis' domain and range lengths should be
14421  * preserved between renders (applies to continuous axes).
14422  * <p>
14423  * When using a sliding window for real time applications,
