14425  * regardless of the data values provided.
14426  * <p>
14427  * When 
14428  * <tt>preserveRatio</tt> is specified,
14429  * following renders will use the 
14430  * <i>effective ratio</i> of the first render,
14431  * whether the ratio was initially fixed using 
14432  * <tt>ratio</tt> or not.
14433  * <p>
14434  * See {@link pvc.options.SlidingWindow}.
14435  * 
14436  * <h3>Default</h3>
14437  * If a sliding window exists: 
14438  * <tt>true</tt>, otherwise, 
14439  * <tt>false</tt>.
14440  * <p>
14441  * See {@link #ratio}.
14442  * 
14443  * @type boolean
14444  * @category Continuous > Scale
14445  */

14447 /**
14448  * The fixed ratio value which is the proportion between the axis' range and domain lengths (applies to continuous axes).
14449  * <p>
14450  * This property can be defined as a number or a string.
14451  * <p>
14452  * For example, if the desired correspondence is that 100 pixels (range) represent 25 days (domain),
14453  * the option can be specified with any of the following equivalent forms:
14454  * 
14455  * <ul>
14456  * 
14457  * <li>
14458  * <tt>ratio = "100/25d"</tt>; or</li>
14459  * 
14460  * <li>
14461  * <tt>ratio = "100/216e7"</tt> (
14462  * <tt>"25d" = 216e7</tt> milliseconds); or</li>
14463  * 
14464  * <li>
14465  * <tt>ratio = 4.63e-8</tt>.</li>
14466  * </ul>
14467  * <p>
14468  * For more information,
14469  * see {@link #fixedLength} and {@link #preserveRatio}.
14470  * 
14471  * @type number|pvc.options.varia.TimeRatio
14472  * @category Continuous > Scale
14473  */
14474 pvc.options.axes.AnyNonHierarchicalCartesianAxis.prototype.ratio = undefined;
14475 /**
14476  * The 
14477  * <i>desired</i> number of major ticks.
14478  * <p>
14479  * A positive integer, possibly infinite.
14480  * <p>
14481  * Attention: This option is ignored when {@link #tickUnit} is specified!
14482  * <p>
14483  * Depending on
14484  * the domain values extent,
14485  * the labels' font size,
14486  * the available space,
14487  * the axis' orientation,
14488  * and the minimum label spacing
14489  * (given by {@link pvc.options.axes.AnyNonHierarchicalCartesianAxis#labelSpacingMin}),
14490  * a maximum number of ticks is implied.
14491  * <p>
14492  * The value of 
14493  * <i>desiredTickCount</i> is clamped to this layout imposed maximum.
14494  * <p>
14495  * When specified and finite,
14496  * the tick calculation algorithm chooses,
14497  * amongst possible tick units,
14498  * the one that results in a number of ticks
14499  * that is 
14500  * <b>closest</b> to the specified 
14501  * <b>desired</b> value.
14502  * <p>
14503  * When specified and infinite (
14504  * <tt>Infinity</tt>),
14505  * the layout imposed maximum is used instead.
14506  * 
14507  * <p>
14508  * 
14509  * <b>The minimum tick count</b>
14510  * </p>
14511  * <p>
14512  * This actually depends on the value of {@link #domainRoundMode}.
14513  * 
14514  * <ul>
14515  * 
14516  * <li>
14517  * 
14518  * <p>
14519  * <b>
14520  * <i>domainRoundMode</i> is {@link pvc.options.varia.AxisDomainRoundingMode#Tick}</b></p>
14521  * <p>
14522  * For tick counts greater than two or three, the algorithm strives to satisfy the user's desire!
14523  * <p>
14524  * However,
14525  * the algorithm always generates at least two or three ticks,
14526  * ignoring both 
14527  * <i>desiredTickCount</i> and 
14528  * <i>labelSpacingMin</i>,
14529  * if needed.
14530  * <p>
14531  * At least three ticks are generated for numeric domains having both negative and positive data.
14532  * There are also temporal domain cases where a minimum of three ticks are generated.
14533  * <p>
14534  * When the labels of these ticks really overlap,
14535  * one of the labels is kept visible and the other(s) is hidden.
14536  * <p>
14537  * This behavior ensures that, unless it is really impossible to do so,
14538  * the axis serves one of its main purposes - allowing to translate visual lengths.
14539  * <p>
14540  * When three tick labels overlap,
14541  * the middle label is kept visible and the end labels are hidden.
14542  * <p>
14543  * When two tick labels overlap,
14544  * one of the labels
14545  * — the one with tick value 
14546  * <tt>0</tt>, if any, or the first one, if none —
14547  * is kept visible and the other is hidden.
14548  * </li>
14549  * 
14550  * <li>
14551  * 
14552  * <p>
14553  * <b>
14554  * <i>domainRoundMode</i> is
14555  * {@link pvc.options.varia.AxisDomainRoundingMode#None} or
14556  * {@link pvc.options.varia.AxisDomainRoundingMode#Nice}</b></p>
14557  * <p>
14558  * The algorithm always generates at least one tick.
14559  * </li>
14560  * </ul>
14561  * <p>
14562  * Specifying a value of 
14563  * <tt>1</tt> results in the minimum possible tick count.
14564  * 
14565  * <p>
14566  * 
14567  * <b>Domain type specifics</b>
14568  * </p>
14569  * 
14570  * <ul>
14571  * 
14572  * <li>
14573  * 
14574  * <b>Numeric</b>
14575  * <p>
14576  * When unspecified, the default value is 
14577  * <tt>Infinity</tt>.
14578  * </li>
14579  * 
14580  * <li>
14581  * 
14582  * <b>Temporal</b>
14583  * <p>
14584  * The value must be less than or equal to 
14585  * <tt>10</tt>.
14586  * <p>
14587  * When unspecified, the default value is 
14588  * <tt>5</tt>.
14589  * </li>
14590  * </ul>
14591  * <p>
14592  * See {@link #tickUnit} for more information.
14593  * 
14594  * @type number
14595  * @category Continuous > Style
14596  */
14597 pvc.options.axes.AnyNonHierarchicalCartesianAxis.prototype.desiredTickCount = undefined;
14598 /**
14599  * Indicates if minor ticks are shown between major ticks (applies to continuous axes).
14600  * 
14601  * @type boolean
14602  * @default true
14603  * @category Continuous > Style
14604  */
14605 pvc.options.axes.AnyNonHierarchicalCartesianAxis.prototype.minorTicks = undefined;
14606 /**
14607  * The ticks' major unit (difference in domain value between consecutive ticks).
14608  * <p>
14609  * When a number, it must be a non-negative, finite, integer.
14610  * 
14611  * <ul>
14612  * 
14613  * <li>
14614  * 
14615  * <b>Numeric axis</b>
14616  * <p>
14617  * Specified values are rounded down to one of the standard precisions:
14618  * a number that is an integer power of 10,
14619  * multiplied by 1, 2 or 5 (e.g. 0.1, 0.2, 0.5, 1, 2, 5, 10, 20, 50, ...).
14620  * </li>
14621  * 
14622  * <li>
14623  * 
14624  * <b>Temporal axis</b>
14625  * <p>
14626  * When a number or numeric string is specified,
14627  * it is a the number of milliseconds of a duration.
14628  * <p>
14629  * It is rounded down to an integer and used directly.
14630  * By default, the corresponding tick format will be the one of the
14631  * greatest standard unit that is below the specified value.
14632  * <p>
14633  * When a (non-numeric) string is specified,
14634  * it should be the code of a standard precision,
14635  * optionally immediately preceded by an integer multiple
14636  * (e.g. 
14637  * <tt>'25d'</tt> means twenty five days).
14638  * <p>
14639  * The standard time precision codes are defined in {@link pvc.options.varia.TimeInterval}
14640  * <p>
14641  * This option should be used instead of the now deprecated
14642  * {@link pvc.options.marks.QuantitativeScaleExtensionPoint#dateTickPrecision}
14643  * extension point, via {@link #extensionPoints} and then 
14644  * <i>scale</i>.
14645  * </li>
14646  * </ul>
14647  * 
14648  * <b>Relations with other options</b>
14649  * <p>
14650  * When both {@link #tickUnitMin} and {@link #tickUnitMax} are specified,
14651  * and the former is greater than or equal to the later,
14652  * then it is as if 
14653  * <i>tickUnit</i> had been specified with the value of 
14654  * <i>tickUnitMin</i>.
14655  * <p>
14656  * When both 
14657  * <i>tickUnit</i> and {@link #tickUnitMin} are specified,
14658  * and 
14659  * <i>tickUnit</i> is less than 
14660  * <i>tickUnitMin</i>,
14661  * then the value of 
14662  * <i>tickUnitMin</i> is used instead.
14663  * <p>
14664  * When both 
14665  * <i>tickUnit</i> and {@link #tickUnitMax} are specified,
14666  * and 
14667  * <i>tickUnit</i> is greater than 
14668  * <i>tickUnitMax</i>,
14669  * then the value of 
14670  * <i>tickUnitMax</i> is used instead.
14671  * <p>
14672  * When specified or implied,
14673  * both {@link #desiredTickCount} and 
14674  * <i>labelSpacingMin</i>
14675  * are ignored.
14676  * <p>
14677  * See related axis options:
14678  * {@link #tickUnitMin},
14679  * {@link #tickUnitMax},
14680  * {@link #domainRoundMode},
14681  * {@link #desiredTickCount} and
14682  * {@link pvc.options.axes.AnyNonHierarchicalCartesianAxis#labelSpacingMin}.
14683  * <p>
14684  * For numeric axes, see also
14685  * {@link pvc.options.axes.NumericCartesianAxis#tickExponentMin} and
14686  * {@link pvc.options.axes.NumericCartesianAxis#tickExponentMax}.
14687  * 
14688  * @type number|string|pvc.options.varia.TimeInterval
14689  * @category Continuous > Style
14690  */
14691 pvc.options.axes.AnyNonHierarchicalCartesianAxis.prototype.tickUnit = undefined;
14692 /**
14693  * The maximum ticks' major unit (difference in domain value between consecutive ticks).
14694  * <p>
14695  * Use this option to ensure that ticks are separated by at most a certain value.
14696  * For example,
14697  * a value of 
14698  * <tt>100</tt> ensures that the unit 
14699  * <tt>200</tt> will not be used,
14700  * and of 
14701  * <tt>'3m'</tt> that a year or semester unit will not be used.
14702  * <p>
14703  * As another example,
14704  * to ensure that the tick unit is less than 
14705  * <tt>1000</tt>,
14706  * either
14707  * specify a 
14708  * <i>tickUnitMax</i> of 
14709  * <tt>900</tt>, or, maybe better,
14710  * specify a {@link pvc.options.axes.NumericCartesianAxis#tickExponentMax} of 
14711  * <tt>2</tt>.
14712  * <p>
14713  * When a number, it must be a positive integer.
14714  * <p>
14715  * The same value parsing rules of {@link #tickUnit} apply to this option.
14716  * <p>
14717  * For numeric axes,
14718  * the value of this option is combined with that of
14719  * {@link pvc.options.axes.NumericCartesianAxis#tickExponentMax},
14720  * resulting in the most restrictive one being used.
14721  * <p>
14722  * See {@link #tickUnit} for more information.
14723  * 
14724  * @type number|string
14725  * @default Infinity
14726  * @category Continuous > Style
14727  */
14728 pvc.options.axes.AnyNonHierarchicalCartesianAxis.prototype.tickUnitMax = undefined;
14729 /**
14730  * The minimum ticks' major unit (difference in domain value between consecutive ticks).
14731  * <p>
14732  * Use this option to ensure that ticks are separated by a minimum value.
14733  * For example, a value of 
14734  * <tt>1</tt> ensures ticks are integers,
14735  * and of 
14736  * <tt>'d'</tt>, that hour ticks are not used.
14737  * <p>
14738  * When a number, it must be a non-negative finite integer.
14739  * <p>
14740  * The same value parsing rules of {@link #tickUnit} apply to this option,
14741  * with the exception that rounding to a standard precision is performed 
14742  * <i>up</i>.
14743  * <p>
14744  * For numeric axes,
14745  * the value of this option is combined with that of
14746  * {@link pvc.options.axes.NumericCartesianAxis#tickExponentMin},
14747  * resulting in the most restrictive one being used.
14748  * <p>
14749  * See {@link #tickUnit} for more information.
14750  * 
14751  * @type number|string
14752  * @default 0
14753  * @category Continuous > Style
14754  */
14755 pvc.options.axes.AnyNonHierarchicalCartesianAxis.prototype.tickUnitMin = undefined;
14756 /**
14757  * The axis' domain rounding mode (applies to continuous axes).
14758  * 
14759  * @type pvc.options.varia.AxisDomainRoundingMode
14760  * @default 'tick'
14761  * @category Continuous-Numeric > Style
14762  */
14763 pvc.options.axes.AnyNonHierarchicalCartesianAxis.prototype.domainRoundMode = undefined;
14764 /**
14765  * The maximum exponent of 
14766  * <tt>10</tt> that is used to generate ticks (applies to continuous-numeric axes).
14767  * <p>
14768  * The value of this option is combined with that of {@link #tickUnitMax},
14769  * resulting in the most restrictive one being used.
14770  * <p>
14771  * The generated ticks are separated by a 
14772  * <i>step</i> value.
14773  * A step value is a certain power of 
14774  * <tt>10</tt>,
14775  * possibly multiplied by 
14776  * <tt>2</tt> or 
14777  * <tt>5</tt>.
14778  * <p>
14779  * For example, 
14780  * for a chosen exponent of 
14781  * <tt>4</tt>,
14782  * the corresponding power of 
14783  * <tt>10</tt> is 
14784  * <tt>10^4=10000</tt> and
14785  * the generated ticks could be:
14786  * 
14787  * <tt>0</tt>, 
14788  * <tt>10000</tt>, 
14789  * <tt>20000</tt>, ...
14790  * <p>
14791  * If the multiplier 
14792  * <tt>5</tt> was chosen, 
14793  * those ticks would instead be:
14794  * 
14795  * <tt>0</tt>, 
14796  * <tt>50000</tt>, 
14797  * <tt>100000</tt>, ...
14798  * <p>
14799  * Setting this property allows imposing a limit on 
14800  * the size of numbers chosen to separate ticks,
14801  * which may be seen as imposing a minimum granularity 
14802  * on the generated tick values.
14803  * <p>
14804  * See {@link #tickUnit} for more information.
14805  * 
14806  * @type number
14807  * @category Continuous-Numeric > Style
14808  */
14809 pvc.options.axes.AnyNonHierarchicalCartesianAxis.prototype.tickExponentMax = undefined;
14810 /**
14811  * The minimum exponent of 
14812  * <tt>10</tt> that is used to generate ticks (applies to continuous-numeric axes).
14813  * <p>
14814  * The value of this option is combined with that of {@link #tickUnitMax},
14815  * resulting in the most restrictive one being used.
14816  * <p>
14817  * The generated ticks are separated by a 
14818  * <i>step</i> value.
14819  * A step value is a certain power of 
14820  * <tt>10</tt>,
14821  * possibly multiplied by 
14822  * <tt>2</tt> or 
14823  * <tt>5</tt>.
14824  * <p>
14825  * For example, 
14826  * for a chosen exponent of 
14827  * <tt>2</tt>,
14828  * the corresponding power of 
14829  * <tt>10</tt> is 
14830  * <tt>10^2=100</tt> and
14831  * the generated ticks could be:
14832  * 
14833  * <tt>0</tt>, 
14834  * <tt>100</tt>, 
14835  * <tt>200</tt>, ...
14836  * <p>
14837  * If the multiplier 
14838  * <tt>2</tt> was chosen, 
14839  * those ticks would instead be:
14840  * 
14841  * <tt>0</tt>, 
14842  * <tt>200</tt>, 
14843  * <tt>400</tt>, ...
14844  * <p>
14845  * Setting this property to 
14846  * <tt>2</tt> would ensure 
14847  * that generated ticks would be separated by the step values
14848  * 
14849  * <tt>100</tt>, 
14850  * <tt>200</tt> or 
14851  * <tt>500</tt>,
14852  * or by steps whose corresponding exponent is 
14853  * bigger than 
14854  * <tt>2</tt>, 
14855  * like: 
14856  * <tt>1000</tt>, 
14857  * <tt>2000</tt> or 
14858  * <tt>5000</tt>.
14859  * <p>
14860  * A more typical use case is ensuring that generated ticks are integers.
14861  * A value of 
14862  * <tt>tickExponentMin</tt> of 
14863  * <tt>0</tt> would accomplish that.
14864  * <p>
14865  * Generally, 
14866  * to impose a maximum number of decimal places on the generated ticks, 
14867  * a negative number can be specified.
14868  * For example, the value 
14869  * <tt>-1</tt> could generate the ticks:
14870  * 
14871  * <tt>0.1</tt>, 
14872  * <tt>0.2</tt>, 
14873  * <tt>0.3</tt>, ...
14874  * If the multiplier 
14875  * <tt>5</tt> was chosen, 
14876  * those ticks would instead be:
14877  * 
14878  * <tt>0.5</tt>, 
14879  * <tt>1.0</tt>, 
14880  * <tt>1.5</tt>, ...
14881  * It could not generate ticks 
14882  * with more that one decimal place.
14883  * <p>
14884  * See {@link #tickUnit} for more information.
14885  * 
14886  * @type number
14887  * @category Continuous-Numeric > Style
14888  */
14889 pvc.options.axes.AnyNonHierarchicalCartesianAxis.prototype.tickExponentMin = undefined;

15126 /**
15127  * The size, in pixels, of the bands used to represent the discrete domain values (applies to discrete axes).
15128  * <p>
15129  * A non-negative number.
15130  * 
15131  * <p>
15132  * 
15133  * <b>In multi-charts</b>
15134  * <p>
15135  * The current layout algorithm used by multi-charts does not support
15136  * minimum, fixed or maximum sizes in small charts.
15137  * As such, the simples band size ratio model always needs to be used.
15138  * <p>
15139  * The minimum, fixed and maximum sizes and spacings are used to determine an
15140  * equivalent or best-possible band size ratio.
15141  * </p>
15142  * 
15143  * <p>
15144  * 
15145  * <b>Band Size, Spacing, Ratio and Step</b>
15146  * <p>
15147  * The band layout arranges bands and space in the following way.
15148  * Taking 
15149  * <i>B</i> to represent 
15150  * <i>bandSize</i>,
15151  * 
15152  * <i>E</i> to represent {@link #bandSpacing} and
15153  * 
15154  * <i>e</i> to be 
15155  * <tt>E/2</tt>,
15156  * bands and space will follow the pattern:
15157  * 
15158  * <tt>eBe</tt>, 
15159  * <tt>eBEBe</tt>, 
15160  * <tt>eBEBEBe</tt>, ...
15161  * <p>
15162  * For a given pair of 
15163  * <i>B</i> and 
15164  * <i>E</i>, each discrete category will occupy a space given by
15165  * the 
15166  * <i>step</i>, 
15167  * <i>S</i>:
15168  * <br></br>
15169  * 
15170  * <i>S = B + E</i>.
15171  * <p>
15172  * Given the number of discrete categories, a cartesian panel (axis or plot) will have
15173  * corresponding fixed or minimum and maximum sizes.
15174  * <p>
15175  * The option {@link #bandSizeRatio}, R, is used, in under-constrained cases,
15176  * to relate 
15177  * <i>B</i> and 
15178  * <i>E</i>:
15179  * <br></br>
15180  * 
15181  * <i>B = R * S</i>
15182  * </p>
15183  * 
15184  * <p>
15185  * 
15186  * <b>Impact on chart size</b>
15187  * <p>
15188  * If the chart size along the axis' dimension
15189  * is such that the available space is less than the
15190  * determined fixed or minimum size,
15191  * then the chart will grow as much as needed to accommodate the fixed or minimum size,
15192  * along that dimension.
15193  * <p>
15194  * If, on the contrary, the chart size along the axis' dimension
15195  * is greater than the determined fixed or maximum size,
15196  * the plot and axis content will be centered in the available space.
15197  * </p>
15198  * 
15199  * <p>
15200  * 
15201  * <b>Option values harmonization</b>
15202  * <p>
15203  * When both {@link #bandSizeMax} and {@link #bandSizeMin} are specified,
15204  * and {@link #bandSizeMax} is less than or equal to 
15205  * <i>bandSizeMin</i>,
15206  * then {@link #bandSize} is set to the the minimum value.
15207  * <p>
15208  * When both 
15209  * <i>bandSize</i> and {@link #bandSizeMin} are specified,
15210  * and 
15211  * <i>bandSize</i> is less than 
15212  * <i>bandSizeMin</i>,
15213  * then the minimum value is used instead.
15214  * <p>
15215  * When both 
15216  * <i>bandSpacing</i> and {@link #bandSpacingMin} are specified,
15217  * and 
15218  * <i>bandSpacing</i> is less than 
15219  * <i>bandSpacingMin</i>,
15220  * then the minimum value is used instead.
15221  * <p>
15222  * When both {@link #bandSpacingMax} and {@link #bandSpacingMin} are specified,
15223  * and {@link #bandSpacingMax} is less than or equal to 
15224  * <i>bandSpacingMin</i>,
15225  * then {@link #bandSpacing} is set to the the minimum value.
15226  * </p>
15227  * 
15228  * <p>
15229  * 
15230  * <b>The algorithm</b>
15231  * <p>
15232  * The options you specify should just behave as you'd expected them to.
15233  * At least, after thinking about them for a while.
15234  * <p>
15235  * If doubts remain on which options and values should be specified,
15236  * or on why the specified options are behaving in a certain way,
15237  * you can follow this explanation of the band layout algorithm.
15238  * </p>
15239  * 
15240  * <ul>
15241  * 
15242  * <li>
15243  * When both 
15244  * <i>bandSize</i> and {@link #bandSpacing} are specified, the layout is 
15245  * <b>fixed</b>.
15246  * <p>
15247  * When they both have the value 
15248  * <tt>0</tt>, then the layout is reevaluated as if they had not been specified.
15249  * <p>
15250  * The option {@link #bandSizeRatio} is ignored.
15251  * </li>
15252  * 
15253  * <li>
15254  * When one and only one of 
15255  * <i>bandSize</i> or {@link #bandSpacing} is specified,
15256  * the layout is 
15257  * <b>partially fixed</b>.
15258  * <p>
15259  * For the variable option, size or spacing,
15260  * any specified minimum and/or maximum options are still considered.
15261  * <p>
15262  * This configuration does not define a fixed step size,
15263  * but instead constrains the range of step size values.
15264  * <p>
15265  * The option {@link #bandSizeRatio} is ignored.
15266  * </li>
15267  * 
15268  * <li>
15269  * When neither 
15270  * <i>bandSize</i> nor {@link #bandSpacing} are specified,
15271  * the layout is 
15272  * <b>strictly variable</b>.
15273  * <p>
15274  * There are several cases:
15275  * 
15276  * <ul>
15277  * 
15278  * <li>
15279  * When none of the minimum and maximum values, of both size and spacing, are specified,
15280  * the size and spacing are governed solely by the {@link #bandSizeRatio}, 
15281  * <i>R</i>.
15282  * <p>
15283  * This is the way the band layout used to behave,
15284  * before the existence of the fixed, minimum and maximum options.
15285  * <p>
15286  * Small-charts continue to behave this way,
15287  * although with a band size ratio that is determined from the
15288  * the other specified options.
15289  * <p>
15290  * The half-line 
15291  * <i>(E,B)</i> departs from 
15292  * <i>(0,0)</i>
15293  * and goes on indefinitely with a slope given by 
15294  * <i>R</i>: 
15295  * <i>E = (1/R - 1) * B</i>.
15296  * </li>
15297  * 
15298  * <li>
15299  * 
15300  * <p>
15301  * When minimum and maximum values, of both size and spacing, are specified,
15302  * the size and spacing are constrained to belong to the
15303  * line segment 
15304  * <i>(E,B)</i>, that goes from point 
15305  * <i>(Emin,Bmin)</i> to point 
15306  * <i>(Emax,Bmax)</i>.
15307  * </p>
15308  * </li>
15309  * 
15310  * <li>
15311  * 
15312  * <p>
15313  * When only the minimum size and spacing values are specified,
15314  * the size and spacing are constrained to belong to the
15315  * line segment 
15316  * <i>(E,B)</i>, that goes from point 
15317  * <i>(0,0)</i> to point 
15318  * <i>(Emin,Bmin)</i>.
15319  * </p>
15320  * </li>
15321  * 
15322  * <li>
15323  * 
15324  * <p>
15325  * When only the maximum size and spacing values are specified,
15326  * the size and spacing are constrained to belong to the
15327  * line segment 
15328  * <i>(E,B)</i>, that goes from point 
15329  * <i>(0,0)</i> to point 
15330  * <i>(Emax,Bmax)</i>.
15331  * </p>
15332  * </li>
15333  * 
15334  * <li>
15335  * In all the following mixed and under-constrained cases,
15336  * option {@link #bandSizeRatio}, 
15337  * <i>R</i>, is taken into account.
15338  * <p>
15339  * The size and spacing are constrained to belong to the the line 
15340  * <i>(E,B)</i> that
15341  * passes through 
15342  * <i>(0,0)</i> and has a slope
15343  * given by 
15344  * <i>R</i>: 
15345  * <i>E = (1/R - 1) * B</i>.
15346  * <p>
15347  * Again, a few more cases:
15348  * 
15349  * <ul>
15350  * 
15351  * <li>
15352  * 
15353  * <p>
15354  * When only the minimum and maximum size values are specified,
15355  * the corresponding spacing values are implied.
15356  * </p>
15357  * </li>
15358  * 
15359  * <li>
15360  * 
15361  * <p>
15362  * When only the minimum and maximum spacing values are specified,
15363  * the corresponding size values are implied.
15364  * </p>
15365  * </li>
15366  * 
15367  * <li>
15368  * When only the minimum size and the maximum spacing values are specified,
15369  * the specified minimum size implies a minimum spacing and
15370  * the specified maximum spacing implies a maximum size.
15371  * <p>
15372  * If the implied minimum spacing is greater than or equal to the specified
15373  * maximum spacing, the algorithm is reevaluated using a fixed spacing
15374  * equal to the implied minimum spacing.
15375  * </li>
15376  * 
15377  * <li>
15378  * When only the maximum size and the minimum spacing values are specified,
15379  * the specified maximum size implies a maximum spacing and
15380  * the specified minimum spacing implies a minimum size.
15381  * <p>
15382  * If the implied minimum size is greater than or equal to the specified
15383  * maximum size, the algorithm is reevaluated using a fixed size
15384  * equal to the implied minimum size.
15385  * </li>
15386  * </ul>
15387  * </li>
15388  * </ul>
15389  * </li>
15390  * </ul>
15391  * <p>
15392  * See other band-control options:
15393  * {@link #bandSpacing},
15394  * {@link #bandSizeMin},
15395  * {@link #bandSizeMax},
15396  * {@link #bandSpacingMin},
15397  * {@link #bandSpacingMax} and,
15398  * for charts that give it representation,
15399  * {@link #bandSizeRatio}.
15400  * 
15401  * @type number
15402  * @category Discrete > Layout
15403  */
15404 pvc.options.axes.DiscreteCartesianAxis.prototype.bandSize = undefined;

15407  * <p>

15409  * <p>
15410  * See {@link #bandSize} for information on the band layout algorithm.

15774 /**

15784 /**
15785  * Controls the type of scale domain coordination that should be performed
15786  * amongst the axes of the same id of each 
15787  * <i>small chart</i> (applies to continuous axes).
15788  * <p>
15789  * The value {@link pvc.options.varia.AxisDomainScope#Row}
15790  * can only be specified if the axis has vertical orientation.
15791  * Conversely,
15792  * the value {@link pvc.options.varia.AxisDomainScope#Column}
15793  * can only be specified if the axis has horizontal orientation.
15794  * 
15795  * @type pvc.options.varia.AxisDomainScope
15796  * @default 'global'
15797  * @category Continuous > Scale
15798  */
15799 pvc.options.axes.AnyContinuousCartesianAxis.prototype.domainScope = undefined;
15800 /**
15801  * The fixed length of the axis domain (applies to continuous axes).
15802  * <p>
15803  * A string value is converted to a number.
15804  * <p>
15805  * The value may be bigger or smaller than the actual length of the data.
15806  * <p>
15807  * By default, the domain of the axis is determined from the actual domain of the data.
15808  * This and other options allow modifying the axis domain.
15809  * <p>
15810  * When the axis domain gets smaller than the data domain,
15811  * and {@link pvc.options.charts.CartesianChart#leafContentOverflow} is set to 
15812  * <tt>auto</tt>,
15813  * the default value,
15814  * clipping is activated in the related plot panels and any overflown content is hidden.
15815  * 
15816  * <h3>Phase I</h3>
15817  * <p>
15818  * The phase I axis domain is determined by the following procedure:
15819  * 
15820  * <ol>
15821  * 
15822  * <li>
15823  * If 
15824  * <tt>fixedLength</tt> is not specified:
15825  * 
15826  * <ol>
15827  * 
15828  * <li>
15829  * If neither 
15830  * <tt>fixedMin</tt> and 
15831  * <tt>fixedMax</tt> are specified,
15832  * the axis domain is the data domain;
15833  * option 
15834  * <tt>originIsZero</tt> may augment the axis domain, on one of its sides;
15835  * </li>
15836  * 
15837  * <li>
15838  * If both 
15839  * <tt>fixedMin</tt> and 
15840  * <tt>fixedMax</tt> are specified,
15841  * the axis domain is fully determined; it's length is implied;
15842  * option 
15843  * <tt>originIsZero</tt> is ignored;
15844  * </li>
15845  * 
15846  * <li>
15847  * If 
15848  * <tt>fixedMin</tt> is specified (and 
15849  * <tt>fixedMax</tt> is not)
15850  * the axis domain minimum is 
15851  * <tt>fixedMin</tt> and
15852  * the axis domain maximum is the data domain maximum, possibly corrected by
15853  * option 
15854  * <tt>originIsZero</tt>;
15855  * </li>
15856  * 
15857  * <li>
15858  * Else, (if 
15859  * <tt>fixedMax</tt> is specified and 
15860  * <tt>fixedMin</tt> is not,)
15861  * the axis domain maximum is 
15862  * <tt>fixedMax</tt> and
15863  * the axis domain minimum is the data domain minimum, possibly corrected by
15864  * option 
15865  * <tt>originIsZero</tt>;
15866  * </li>
15867  * </ol>
15868  * </li>
15869  * 
15870  * <li>
15871  * If 
15872  * <tt>fixedLength</tt> is specified, option 
15873  * <tt>originIsZero</tt> is ignored.
15874  * <p>
15875  * The limits of the axis domain are determined as follows:
15876  * 
15877  * <ol>
15878  * 
15879  * <li>
15880  * If 
15881  * <tt>fixedMin</tt> is specified, the axis domain maximum is implied:
15882  * <br></br>
15883  * 
15884  * <tt>max = fixedMin + fixedLength</tt>;
15885  * <br></br>
15886  * options 
15887  * <tt>originIsZero</tt>, 
15888  * <tt>fixedMax</tt> are ignored;
15889  * option 
15890  * <tt>domainAlign</tt> is ignored in this phase;
15891  * </li>
15892  * 
15893  * <li>
15894  * If 
15895  * <tt>fixedMax</tt> is specified, the axis domain minimum is implied:
15896  * <br></br>
15897  * 
15898  * <tt>min = fixedMax - fixedLength</tt>;
15899  * <br></br>
15900  * option 
15901  * <tt>originIsZero</tt> is ignored;
15902  * option 
15903  * <tt>domainAlign</tt> is ignored in this phase;
15904  * </li>
15905  * 
15906  * <li>
15907  * Else, 
15908  * <tt>domainAlign</tt> is either specified or defaults to 
15909  * <tt>center</tt>.
15910  * The axis domain is aligned to either the minimum, maximum or center of the data domain
15911  * and then taken to have the specified fixed length.
15912  * <p>
15913  * It is determined as follows:
15914  * 
15915  * <ul>
15916  * 
15917  * <li>
15918  * If 
15919  * <tt>domainAlign</tt> is 
15920  * <tt>min</tt>, the axis domain minimum is that of
15921  * the actual data and the axis domain maximum is implied:
15922  * <br></br>
15923  * 
15924  * <tt>max = min(data) + fixedLength</tt>;
15925  * </li>
15926  * 
15927  * <li>
15928  * If 
15929  * <tt>domainAlign</tt> is 
15930  * <tt>max</tt>, the axis domain maximum is that of
15931  * the actual data and the axis domain minimum is implied:
15932  * <br></br>
15933  * 
15934  * <tt>min = max(data) - fixedLength</tt>;
15935  * </li>
15936  * 
15937  * <li>
15938  * Else, 
15939  * <tt>domainAlign</tt> is 
15940  * <tt>center</tt>, or defaults to it,
15941  * and both axis domain limits are determined from the actual data domain,
15942  * as follows:
15943  * 
15944  * <ul>
15945  * 
15946  * <li>
15947  * <tt>min = center(data) - fixedLength / 2</tt></li>
15948  * 
15949  * <li>
15950  * <tt>max = center(data) + fixedLength / 2</tt></li>
15951  * </ul>
15952  * where 
15953  * <tt>center(data)</tt> is determined as:
15954  * <br></br>
15955  * 
15956  * <tt>center(data) = (max(data) - min(data)) / 2</tt>.
15957  * </li>
15958  * </ul>
15959  * </li>
15960  * </ol>
15961  * </li>
15962  * </ol>
15963  * 
15964  * <h3>Phase II</h3>
15965  * <p>
15966  * In phase II, additional options may modify the phase I axis domain.
15967  * <p>
15968  * If {@link #domainRoundMode} is 
15969  * <tt>nice</tt>, the axis domain is made "nice",
15970  * by making sure that its ends are "nice" numbers.
15971  * <p>
15972  * If {@link #ratio} is specified (or a ratio is imposed due to {@link preserveRatio}),
15973  * the length of the axis domain is imposed by the length of the axis' range (a number of pixels).
15974  * The axis domain is aligned relative to the phase I axis domain, according to the value
15975  * of {@link #domainAlign}.
15976  * <p>
15977  * If {@link #domainRoundMode} is 
15978  * <tt>tick</tt>,
15979  * the phase I axis domain is extended to include the calculated ticks and only then are
15980  * the 
15981  * <tt>ratio</tt> and 
15982  * <tt>domainAlign</tt> options processed, so that the domain aligns to
15983  * the calculated ticks.
15984  * 
15985  * <h3>Default</h3>
15986  * <p>
15987  * If a sliding window exists, it is its length {@link pvc.options.SlidingWindow#length},
15988  * otherwise, 
15989  * <tt>null</tt>.
15990  * <p>
15991  * For more information, see:
15992  * {@link #fixedMin},
15993  * {@link #fixedMax},
15994  * {@link #domainAlign},
15995  * {@link #ratio} and
15996  * {@link #originIsZero}.
15997  * 
15998  * @type number|pvc.options.varia.TimeInterval
15999  * @category Continuous > Scale
16000  */
16001 pvc.options.axes.AnyContinuousCartesianAxis.prototype.fixedLength = undefined;
16002 /**
16003  * The fixed maximum value of the axis domain (applies to continuous axes).
16004  * <p>
16005  * The value is converted using the {@link pvc.options.DimensionType#converter} of
16006  * the first dimension of the first role bound to the axis.
16007  * <p>
16008  * For example, if the base axis shows the 
16009  * <i>category</i> dimension,
16010  * and the dimension is configured as type 
16011  * <tt>Date</tt>,
16012  * and it uses the default converter, then it accepts:
16013  * 
16014  * <ul>
16015  *

16017  * values of type 
16018  * <tt>number</tt>,
16019  * representing milliseconds as returned by
16020  * the JavaScript's 
16021  * <tt>Date.getTime()</tt> method;
16022  * </li>
16023  * 
16024  * <li>
16025  * values of type 
16026  * <tt>Date</tt>, which are accepted as is;
16027  * </li>
16028  * 
16029  * <li>
16030  * values of type 
16031  * <tt>string</tt>,
16032  * in a format defined by the dimension's
16033  * {@link pvc.options.DimensionType#rawFormat}.
16034  * </li>
16035  * </ul>
16036  * <p>
16037  * The value may be bigger or smaller than the maximum value of the data domain.
16038  * <p>
16039  * For more information, see {@link #fixedLength}.
16040  * 
16041  * @type number|string|Date
16042  * @category Continuous > Scale
16043  */
16044 pvc.options.axes.AnyContinuousCartesianAxis.prototype.fixedMax = undefined;

16050  * the first dimension of the first role bound to the axis.
16051  * <p>
16052  * For example, if the base axis shows the

16056  * 
16057  * <ul>

16069  * <li>values of type

16084 /**

16112 /**
16113  * Indicates if the initial proportion between the axis' domain and range lengths should be
16114  * preserved between renders (applies to continuous axes).
16115  * <p>
16116  * When using a sliding window for real time applications,
16117  * the ratio preservation allows for a stable visualization,
16118  * regardless of the data values provided.
16119  * <p>
16120  * When 
16121  * <tt>preserveRatio</tt> is specified,
16122  * following renders will use the 
16123  * <i>effective ratio</i> of the first render,
16124  * whether the ratio was initially fixed using 
16125  * <tt>ratio</tt> or not.
16126  * <p>
16127  * See {@link pvc.options.SlidingWindow}.
16128  * 
16129  * <h3>Default</h3>
16130  * If a sliding window exists: 
16131  * <tt>true</tt>, otherwise, 
16132  * <tt>false</tt>.
16133  * <p>
16134  * See {@link #ratio}.
16135  * 
16136  * @type boolean
16137  * @category Continuous > Scale
16138  */
16139 pvc.options.axes.AnyContinuousCartesianAxis.prototype.preserveRatio = undefined;
16140 /**
16141  * The fixed ratio value which is the proportion between the axis' range and domain lengths (applies to continuous axes).
16142  * <p>
16143  * This property can be defined as a number or a string.
16144  * <p>
16145  * For example, if the desired correspondence is that 100 pixels (range) represent 25 days (domain),
16146  * the option can be specified with any of the following equivalent forms:
16147  * 
16148  * <ul>
16149  * 
16150  * <li>
16151  * <tt>ratio = "100/25d"</tt>; or</li>
16152  * 
16153  * <li>
16154  * <tt>ratio = "100/216e7"</tt> (
16155  * <tt>"25d" = 216e7</tt> milliseconds); or</li>
16156  * 
16157  * <li>
16158  * <tt>ratio = 4.63e-8</tt>.</li>
16159  * </ul>
16160  * <p>
16161  * For more information,
16162  * see {@link #fixedLength} and {@link #preserveRatio}.
16163  * 
16164  * @type number|pvc.options.varia.TimeRatio
16165  * @category Continuous > Scale
16166  */
16167 pvc.options.axes.AnyContinuousCartesianAxis.prototype.ratio = undefined;
16168 /**
16169  * The 
16170  * <i>desired</i> number of major ticks.
16171  * <p>
16172  * A positive integer, possibly infinite.
16173  * <p>
16174  * Attention: This option is ignored when {@link #tickUnit} is specified!
16175  * <p>
16176  * Depending on
16177  * the domain values extent,
16178  * the labels' font size,
16179  * the available space,
16180  * the axis' orientation,
16181  * and the minimum label spacing
16182  * (given by {@link pvc.options.axes.AnyNonHierarchicalCartesianAxis#labelSpacingMin}),
16183  * a maximum number of ticks is implied.
16184  * <p>
16185  * The value of 
16186  * <i>desiredTickCount</i> is clamped to this layout imposed maximum.
16187  * <p>
16188  * When specified and finite,
16189  * the tick calculation algorithm chooses,
16190  * amongst possible tick units,
16191  * the one that results in a number of ticks
16192  * that is 
16193  * <b>closest</b> to the specified 
16194  * <b>desired</b> value.
16195  * <p>
16196  * When specified and infinite (
16197  * <tt>Infinity</tt>),
16198  * the layout imposed maximum is used instead.
16199  * 
16200  * <p>
16201  * 
16202  * <b>The minimum tick count</b>
16203  * </p>
16204  * <p>
16205  * This actually depends on the value of {@link #domainRoundMode}.
16206  * 
16207  * <ul>
16208  * 
16209  * <li>
16210  * 
16211  * <p>
16212  * <b>
16213  * <i>domainRoundMode</i> is {@link pvc.options.varia.AxisDomainRoundingMode#Tick}</b></p>
16214  * <p>
16215  * For tick counts greater than two or three, the algorithm strives to satisfy the user's desire!
16216  * <p>
16217  * However,
16218  * the algorithm always generates at least two or three ticks,
16219  * ignoring both 
16220  * <i>desiredTickCount</i> and 
16221  * <i>labelSpacingMin</i>,
16222  * if needed.
16223  * <p>
16224  * At least three ticks are generated for numeric domains having both negative and positive data.
16225  * There are also temporal domain cases where a minimum of three ticks are generated.
16226  * <p>
16227  * When the labels of these ticks really overlap,
16228  * one of the labels is kept visible and the other(s) is hidden.
16229  * <p>
16230  * This behavior ensures that, unless it is really impossible to do so,
16231  * the axis serves one of its main purposes - allowing to translate visual lengths.
16232  * <p>
16233  * When three tick labels overlap,
16234  * the middle label is kept visible and the end labels are hidden.
16235  * <p>
16236  * When two tick labels overlap,
16237  * one of the labels
16238  * — the one with tick value 
16239  * <tt>0</tt>, if any, or the first one, if none —
16240  * is kept visible and the other is hidden.
16241  * </li>
16242  * 
16243  * <li>
16244  * 
16245  * <p>
16246  * <b>
16247  * <i>domainRoundMode</i> is
16248  * {@link pvc.options.varia.AxisDomainRoundingMode#None} or
16249  * {@link pvc.options.varia.AxisDomainRoundingMode#Nice}</b></p>
16250  * <p>
16251  * The algorithm always generates at least one tick.
16252  * </li>
16253  * </ul>
16254  * <p>
16255  * Specifying a value of 
16256  * <tt>1</tt> results in the minimum possible tick count.
16257  * 
16258  * <p>
16259  * 
16260  * <b>Domain type specifics</b>
16261  * </p>
16262  * 
16263  * <ul>
16264  * 
16265  * <li>
16266  * 
16267  * <b>Numeric</b>
16268  * <p>
16269  * When unspecified, the default value is 
16270  * <tt>Infinity</tt>.
16271  * </li>
16272  * 
16273  * <li>
16274  * 
16275  * <b>Temporal</b>
16276  * <p>
16277  * The value must be less than or equal to 
16278  * <tt>10</tt>.
16279  * <p>
16280  * When unspecified, the default value is 
16281  * <tt>5</tt>.
16282  * </li>
16283  * </ul>
16284  * <p>
16285  * See {@link #tickUnit} for more information.
16286  * 
16287  * @type number
16288  * @category Continuous > Style
16289  */
16290 pvc.options.axes.AnyContinuousCartesianAxis.prototype.desiredTickCount = undefined;
16291 /**
16292  * Indicates if minor ticks are shown between major ticks (applies to continuous axes).
16293  * 
16294  * @type boolean
16295  * @default true
16296  * @category Continuous > Style
16297  */
16298 pvc.options.axes.AnyContinuousCartesianAxis.prototype.minorTicks = undefined;
16299 /**
16300  * The ticks' major unit (difference in domain value between consecutive ticks).
16301  * <p>
16302  * When a number, it must be a non-negative, finite, integer.
16303  * 
16304  * <ul>
16305  * 
16306  * <li>
16307  * 
16308  * <b>Numeric axis</b>
16309  * <p>
16310  * Specified values are rounded down to one of the standard precisions:
16311  * a number that is an integer power of 10,
16312  * multiplied by 1, 2 or 5 (e.g. 0.1, 0.2, 0.5, 1, 2, 5, 10, 20, 50, ...).
16313  * </li>
16314  * 
16315  * <li>
16316  * 
16317  * <b>Temporal axis</b>
16318  * <p>
16319  * When a number or numeric string is specified,
16320  * it is a the number of milliseconds of a duration.
16321  * <p>
16322  * It is rounded down to an integer and used directly.
16323  * By default, the corresponding tick format will be the one of the
16324  * greatest standard unit that is below the specified value.
16325  * <p>
16326  * When a (non-numeric) string is specified,
16327  * it should be the code of a standard precision,
16328  * optionally immediately preceded by an integer multiple
16329  * (e.g. 
16330  * <tt>'25d'</tt> means twenty five days).
16331  * <p>
16332  * The standard time precision codes are defined in {@link pvc.options.varia.TimeInterval}
16333  * <p>
16334  * This option should be used instead of the now deprecated
16335  * {@link pvc.options.marks.QuantitativeScaleExtensionPoint#dateTickPrecision}
16336  * extension point, via {@link #extensionPoints} and then 
16337  * <i>scale</i>.
16338  * </li>
16339  * </ul>
16340  * 
16341  * <b>Relations with other options</b>
16342  * <p>
16343  * When both {@link #tickUnitMin} and {@link #tickUnitMax} are specified,
16344  * and the former is greater than or equal to the later,
16345  * then it is as if 
16346  * <i>tickUnit</i> had been specified with the value of 
16347  * <i>tickUnitMin</i>.
16348  * <p>
16349  * When both 
16350  * <i>tickUnit</i> and {@link #tickUnitMin} are specified,
16351  * and 
16352  * <i>tickUnit</i> is less than 
16353  * <i>tickUnitMin</i>,
16354  * then the value of 
16355  * <i>tickUnitMin</i> is used instead.
16356  * <p>
16357  * When both 
16358  * <i>tickUnit</i> and {@link #tickUnitMax} are specified,
16359  * and 
16360  * <i>tickUnit</i> is greater than 
16361  * <i>tickUnitMax</i>,
16362  * then the value of 
16363  * <i>tickUnitMax</i> is used instead.
16364  * <p>
16365  * When specified or implied,
16366  * both {@link #desiredTickCount} and 
16367  * <i>labelSpacingMin</i>
16368  * are ignored.
16369  * <p>
16370  * See related axis options:
16371  * {@link #tickUnitMin},
16372  * {@link #tickUnitMax},
16373  * {@link #domainRoundMode},
16374  * {@link #desiredTickCount} and
16375  * {@link pvc.options.axes.AnyNonHierarchicalCartesianAxis#labelSpacingMin}.
16376  * <p>
16377  * For numeric axes, see also
16378  * {@link pvc.options.axes.NumericCartesianAxis#tickExponentMin} and
16379  * {@link pvc.options.axes.NumericCartesianAxis#tickExponentMax}.
16380  * 
16381  * @type number|string|pvc.options.varia.TimeInterval
16382  * @category Continuous > Style
16383  */
16384 pvc.options.axes.AnyContinuousCartesianAxis.prototype.tickUnit = undefined;
16385 /**
16386  * The maximum ticks' major unit (difference in domain value between consecutive ticks).
16387  * <p>
16388  * Use this option to ensure that ticks are separated by at most a certain value.
16389  * For example,
16390  * a value of 
16391  * <tt>100</tt> ensures that the unit 
16392  * <tt>200</tt> will not be used,
16393  * and of 
16394  * <tt>'3m'</tt> that a year or semester unit will not be used.
16395  * <p>
16396  * As another example,
16397  * to ensure that the tick unit is less than 
16398  * <tt>1000</tt>,
16399  * either
16400  * specify a 
16401  * <i>tickUnitMax</i> of 
16402  * <tt>900</tt>, or, maybe better,
16403  * specify a {@link pvc.options.axes.NumericCartesianAxis#tickExponentMax} of 
16404  * <tt>2</tt>.
16405  * <p>
16406  * When a number, it must be a positive integer.
16407  * <p>
16408  * The same value parsing rules of {@link #tickUnit} apply to this option.
16409  * <p>
16410  * For numeric axes,
16411  * the value of this option is combined with that of
16412  * {@link pvc.options.axes.NumericCartesianAxis#tickExponentMax},
16413  * resulting in the most restrictive one being used.
16414  * <p>
16415  * See {@link #tickUnit} for more information.
16416  * 
16417  * @type number|string
16418  * @default Infinity
16419  * @category Continuous > Style
16420  */
16421 pvc.options.axes.AnyContinuousCartesianAxis.prototype.tickUnitMax = undefined;
16422 /**
16423  * The minimum ticks' major unit (difference in domain value between consecutive ticks).
16424  * <p>
16425  * Use this option to ensure that ticks are separated by a minimum value.
16426  * For example, a value of 
16427  * <tt>1</tt> ensures ticks are integers,
16428  * and of 
16429  * <tt>'d'</tt>, that hour ticks are not used.
16430  * <p>
16431  * When a number, it must be a non-negative finite integer.
16432  * <p>
16433  * The same value parsing rules of {@link #tickUnit} apply to this option,
16434  * with the exception that rounding to a standard precision is performed 
16435  * <i>up</i>.
16436  * <p>
16437  * For numeric axes,
16438  * the value of this option is combined with that of
16439  * {@link pvc.options.axes.NumericCartesianAxis#tickExponentMin},
16440  * resulting in the most restrictive one being used.
16441  * <p>
16442  * See {@link #tickUnit} for more information.
16443  * 
16444  * @type number|string
16445  * @default 0
16446  * @category Continuous > Style
16447  */
16448 pvc.options.axes.AnyContinuousCartesianAxis.prototype.tickUnitMin = undefined;
16449 /**
16450  * The axis' domain rounding mode (applies to continuous axes).
16451  * 
16452  * @type pvc.options.varia.AxisDomainRoundingMode
16453  * @default 'tick'
16454  * @category Continuous-Numeric > Style
16455  */
16456 pvc.options.axes.AnyContinuousCartesianAxis.prototype.domainRoundMode = undefined;
16457 /**
16458  * The maximum exponent of 
16459  * <tt>10</tt> that is used to generate ticks (applies to continuous-numeric axes).
16460  * <p>
16461  * The value of this option is combined with that of {@link #tickUnitMax},
16462  * resulting in the most restrictive one being used.
16463  * <p>
16464  * The generated ticks are separated by a 
16465  * <i>step</i> value.
16466  * A step value is a certain power of 
16467  * <tt>10</tt>,
16468  * possibly multiplied by 
16469  * <tt>2</tt> or 
16470  * <tt>5</tt>.
16471  * <p>
16472  * For example, 
16473  * for a chosen exponent of 
16474  * <tt>4</tt>,
16475  * the corresponding power of 
16476  * <tt>10</tt> is 
16477  * <tt>10^4=10000</tt> and
16478  * the generated ticks could be:
16479  * 
16480  * <tt>0</tt>, 
16481  * <tt>10000</tt>, 
16482  * <tt>20000</tt>, ...
16483  * <p>
16484  * If the multiplier 
16485  * <tt>5</tt> was chosen, 
16486  * those ticks would instead be:
16487  * 
16488  * <tt>0</tt>, 
16489  * <tt>50000</tt>, 
16490  * <tt>100000</tt>, ...
16491  * <p>
16492  * Setting this property allows imposing a limit on 
16493  * the size of numbers chosen to separate ticks,
16494  * which may be seen as imposing a minimum granularity 
16495  * on the generated tick values.
16496  * <p>
16497  * See {@link #tickUnit} for more information.
16498  * 
16499  * @type number
16500  * @category Continuous-Numeric > Style
16501  */
16502 pvc.options.axes.AnyContinuousCartesianAxis.prototype.tickExponentMax = undefined;
16503 /**
16504  * The minimum exponent of 
16505  * <tt>10</tt> that is used to generate ticks (applies to continuous-numeric axes).
16506  * <p>
16507  * The value of this option is combined with that of {@link #tickUnitMax},
16508  * resulting in the most restrictive one being used.
16509  * <p>
16510  * The generated ticks are separated by a 
16511  * <i>step</i> value.
16512  * A step value is a certain power of 
16513  * <tt>10</tt>,
16514  * possibly multiplied by 
16515  * <tt>2</tt> or 
16516  * <tt>5</tt>.
16517  * <p>
16518  * For example, 
16519  * for a chosen exponent of 
16520  * <tt>2</tt>,
16521  * the corresponding power of 
16522  * <tt>10</tt> is 
16523  * <tt>10^2=100</tt> and
16524  * the generated ticks could be:
16525  * 
16526  * <tt>0</tt>, 
16527  * <tt>100</tt>, 
16528  * <tt>200</tt>, ...
16529  * <p>
16530  * If the multiplier 
16531  * <tt>2</tt> was chosen, 
16532  * those ticks would instead be:
16533  * 
16534  * <tt>0</tt>, 
16535  * <tt>200</tt>, 
16536  * <tt>400</tt>, ...
16537  * <p>
16538  * Setting this property to 
16539  * <tt>2</tt> would ensure 
16540  * that generated ticks would be separated by the step values
16541  * 
16542  * <tt>100</tt>, 
16543  * <tt>200</tt> or 
16544  * <tt>500</tt>,
16545  * or by steps whose corresponding exponent is 
16546  * bigger than 
16547  * <tt>2</tt>, 
16548  * like: 
16549  * <tt>1000</tt>, 
16550  * <tt>2000</tt> or 
16551  * <tt>5000</tt>.
16552  * <p>
16553  * A more typical use case is ensuring that generated ticks are integers.
16554  * A value of 
16555  * <tt>tickExponentMin</tt> of 
16556  * <tt>0</tt> would accomplish that.
16557  * <p>
16558  * Generally, 
16559  * to impose a maximum number of decimal places on the generated ticks, 
16560  * a negative number can be specified.
16561  * For example, the value 
16562  * <tt>-1</tt> could generate the ticks:
16563  * 
16564  * <tt>0.1</tt>, 
16565  * <tt>0.2</tt>, 
16566  * <tt>0.3</tt>, ...
16567  * If the multiplier 
16568  * <tt>5</tt> was chosen, 
16569  * those ticks would instead be:
16570  * 
16571  * <tt>0.5</tt>, 
16572  * <tt>1.0</tt>, 
16573  * <tt>1.5</tt>, ...
16574  * It could not generate ticks 
16575  * with more that one decimal place.
16576  * <p>
16577  * See {@link #tickUnit} for more information.
16578  * 
16579  * @type number
16580  * @category Continuous-Numeric > Style
16581  */
16582 pvc.options.axes.AnyContinuousCartesianAxis.prototype.tickExponentMin = undefined;

16584  * Indicates if the zero line rule is drawn,

16587  * <p>

16620  */
16621 pvc.options.axes.AnyContinuousCartesianAxis.prototype.ticks = undefined;

16720 /**
16721  * The domain alignment to use when the domain has a fixed or implied length (applies to continuous axes).

16730 /**
16731  * Controls the type of scale domain coordination that should be performed
16732  * amongst the axes of the same id of each 
16733  * <i>small chart</i> (applies to continuous axes).
16734  * <p>
16735  * The value {@link pvc.options.varia.AxisDomainScope#Row}
16736  * can only be specified if the axis has vertical orientation.
16737  * Conversely,
16738  * the value {@link pvc.options.varia.AxisDomainScope#Column}
16739  * can only be specified if the axis has horizontal orientation.
16740  * 
16741  * @type pvc.options.varia.AxisDomainScope
16742  * @default 'global'
16743  * @category Continuous > Scale
16744  */
16745 pvc.options.axes.NumericCartesianAxis.prototype.domainScope = undefined;
16746 /**
16747  * The fixed length of the axis domain (applies to continuous axes).
16748  * <p>
16749  * A string value is converted to a number.
16750  * <p>
16751  * The value may be bigger or smaller than the actual length of the data.
16752  * <p>
16753  * By default, the domain of the axis is determined from the actual domain of the data.
16754  * This and other options allow modifying the axis domain.
16755  * <p>
16756  * When the axis domain gets smaller than the data domain,
16757  * and {@link pvc.options.charts.CartesianChart#leafContentOverflow} is set to 
16758  * <tt>auto</tt>,
16759  * the default value,
16760  * clipping is activated in the related plot panels and any overflown content is hidden.
16761  * 
16762  * <h3>Phase I</h3>
16763  * <p>
16764  * The phase I axis domain is determined by the following procedure:
16765  * 
16766  * <ol>
16767  * 
16768  * <li>
16769  * If 
16770  * <tt>fixedLength</tt> is not specified:
16771  * 
16772  * <ol>
16773  * 
16774  * <li>
16775  * If neither 
16776  * <tt>fixedMin</tt> and 
16777  * <tt>fixedMax</tt> are specified,
16778  * the axis domain is the data domain;
16779  * option 
16780  * <tt>originIsZero</tt> may augment the axis domain, on one of its sides;
16781  * </li>
16782  * 
16783  * <li>
16784  * If both 
16785  * <tt>fixedMin</tt> and 
16786  * <tt>fixedMax</tt> are specified,
16787  * the axis domain is fully determined; it's length is implied;
16788  * option 
16789  * <tt>originIsZero</tt> is ignored;
16790  * </li>
16791  * 
16792  * <li>
16793  * If 
16794  * <tt>fixedMin</tt> is specified (and 
16795  * <tt>fixedMax</tt> is not)
16796  * the axis domain minimum is 
16797  * <tt>fixedMin</tt> and
16798  * the axis domain maximum is the data domain maximum, possibly corrected by
16799  * option 
16800  * <tt>originIsZero</tt>;
16801  * </li>
16802  * 
16803  * <li>
16804  * Else, (if 
16805  * <tt>fixedMax</tt> is specified and 
16806  * <tt>fixedMin</tt> is not,)
16807  * the axis domain maximum is 
16808  * <tt>fixedMax</tt> and
16809  * the axis domain minimum is the data domain minimum, possibly corrected by
16810  * option 
16811  * <tt>originIsZero</tt>;
16812  * </li>
16813  * </ol>
16814  * </li>
16815  * 
16816  * <li>
16817  * If 
16818  * <tt>fixedLength</tt> is specified, option 
16819  * <tt>originIsZero</tt> is ignored.
16820  * <p>
16821  * The limits of the axis domain are determined as follows:
16822  * 
16823  * <ol>
16824  * 
16825  * <li>
16826  * If 
16827  * <tt>fixedMin</tt> is specified, the axis domain maximum is implied:
16828  * <br></br>
16829  * 
16830  * <tt>max = fixedMin + fixedLength</tt>;
16831  * <br></br>
16832  * options 
16833  * <tt>originIsZero</tt>, 
16834  * <tt>fixedMax</tt> are ignored;
16835  * option 
16836  * <tt>domainAlign</tt> is ignored in this phase;
16837  * </li>
16838  * 
16839  * <li>
16840  * If 
16841  * <tt>fixedMax</tt> is specified, the axis domain minimum is implied:
16842  * <br></br>
16843  * 
16844  * <tt>min = fixedMax - fixedLength</tt>;
16845  * <br></br>
16846  * option 
16847  * <tt>originIsZero</tt> is ignored;
16848  * option 
16849  * <tt>domainAlign</tt> is ignored in this phase;
16850  * </li>
16851  * 
16852  * <li>
16853  * Else, 
16854  * <tt>domainAlign</tt> is either specified or defaults to 
16855  * <tt>center</tt>.
16856  * The axis domain is aligned to either the minimum, maximum or center of the data domain
16857  * and then taken to have the specified fixed length.
16858  * <p>
16859  * It is determined as follows:
16860  * 
16861  * <ul>
16862  * 
16863  * <li>
16864  * If 
16865  * <tt>domainAlign</tt> is 
16866  * <tt>min</tt>, the axis domain minimum is that of
16867  * the actual data and the axis domain maximum is implied:
16868  * <br></br>
16869  * 
16870  * <tt>max = min(data) + fixedLength</tt>;
16871  * </li>
16872  * 
16873  * <li>
16874  * If 
16875  * <tt>domainAlign</tt> is 
16876  * <tt>max</tt>, the axis domain maximum is that of
16877  * the actual data and the axis domain minimum is implied:
16878  * <br></br>
16879  * 
16880  * <tt>min = max(data) - fixedLength</tt>;
16881  * </li>
16882  * 
16883  * <li>
16884  * Else, 
16885  * <tt>domainAlign</tt> is 
16886  * <tt>center</tt>, or defaults to it,
16887  * and both axis domain limits are determined from the actual data domain,
16888  * as follows:
16889  * 
16890  * <ul>
16891  * 
16892  * <li>
16893  * <tt>min = center(data) - fixedLength / 2</tt></li>
16894  * 
16895  * <li>
16896  * <tt>max = center(data) + fixedLength / 2</tt></li>
16897  * </ul>
16898  * where 
16899  * <tt>center(data)</tt> is determined as:
16900  * <br></br>
16901  * 
16902  * <tt>center(data) = (max(data) - min(data)) / 2</tt>.
16903  * </li>
16904  * </ul>
16905  * </li>
16906  * </ol>
16907  * </li>
16908  * </ol>
16909  * 
16910  * <h3>Phase II</h3>
16911  * <p>
16912  * In phase II, additional options may modify the phase I axis domain.
16913  * <p>
16914  * If {@link #domainRoundMode} is 
16915  * <tt>nice</tt>, the axis domain is made "nice",
16916  * by making sure that its ends are "nice" numbers.
16917  * <p>
16918  * If {@link #ratio} is specified (or a ratio is imposed due to {@link preserveRatio}),
16919  * the length of the axis domain is imposed by the length of the axis' range (a number of pixels).
16920  * The axis domain is aligned relative to the phase I axis domain, according to the value
16921  * of {@link #domainAlign}.
16922  * <p>
16923  * If {@link #domainRoundMode} is 
16924  * <tt>tick</tt>,
16925  * the phase I axis domain is extended to include the calculated ticks and only then are
16926  * the 
16927  * <tt>ratio</tt> and 
16928  * <tt>domainAlign</tt> options processed, so that the domain aligns to
16929  * the calculated ticks.
16930  * 
16931  * <h3>Default</h3>
16932  * <p>
16933  * If a sliding window exists, it is its length {@link pvc.options.SlidingWindow#length},
16934  * otherwise, 
16935  * <tt>null</tt>.
16936  * <p>
16937  * For more information, see:
16938  * {@link #fixedMin},
16939  * {@link #fixedMax},
16940  * {@link #domainAlign},
16941  * {@link #ratio} and
16942  * {@link #originIsZero}.
16943  * 
16944  * @type number|pvc.options.varia.TimeInterval
16945  * @category Continuous > Scale
16946  */
16947 pvc.options.axes.NumericCartesianAxis.prototype.fixedLength = undefined;
16948 /**
16949  * The fixed maximum value of the axis domain (applies to continuous axes).
16950  * <p>
16951  * The value is converted using the {@link pvc.options.DimensionType#converter} of
16952  * the first dimension of the first role bound to the axis.
16953  * <p>
16954  * For example, if the base axis shows the 
16955  * <i>category</i> dimension,
16956  * and the dimension is configured as type 
16957  * <tt>Date</tt>,
16958  * and it uses the default converter, then it accepts:
16959  * 
16960  * <ul>
16961  * 
16962  * <li>
16963  * values of type 
16964  * <tt>number</tt>,
16965  * representing milliseconds as returned by
16966  * the JavaScript's 
16967  * <tt>Date.getTime()</tt> method;
16968  * </li>
16969  * 
16970  * <li>
16971  * values of type 
16972  * <tt>Date</tt>, which are accepted as is;
16973  * </li>
16974  * 
16975  * <li>
16976  * values of type 
16977  * <tt>string</tt>,
16978  * in a format defined by the dimension's
16979  * {@link pvc.options.DimensionType#rawFormat}.
16980  * </li>
16981  * </ul>
16982  * <p>
16983  * The value may be bigger or smaller than the maximum value of the data domain.
16984  * <p>
16985  * For more information, see {@link #fixedLength}.
16986  * 
16987  * @type number|string|Date
16988  * @category Continuous > Scale
16989  */
16990 pvc.options.axes.NumericCartesianAxis.prototype.fixedMax = undefined;
16991 /**
16992  * The fixed minimum value of the axis domain (applies to continuous axes).
16993  * <p>
16994  * The value is converted using the
16995  * {@link pvc.options.DimensionType#converter} of
16996  * the first dimension of the first role bound to the axis.
16997  * <p>
16998  * For example, if the base axis shows the 
16999  * <i>category</i> dimension,
17000  * and the dimension is configured as type Date,
17001  * and it uses the default converter, then it accepts:
17002  * 
17003  * <ul>
17004  * 
17005  * <li>values of type 
17006  * <tt>number</tt>,
17007  * representing milliseconds as returned by
17008  * the JavaScript's 
17009  * <tt>Date.getTime()</tt> method
17010  * </li>
17011  * 
17012  * <li>values of type 
17013  * <tt>Date</tt>, which are accepted as is</li>
17014  * 
17015  * <li>values of type 
17016  * <tt>string</tt>,
17017  * in a format defined by the dimension's
17018  * {@link pvc.options.DimensionType#rawFormat}.
17019  * </li>
17020  * </ul>
17021  * <p>
17022  * The value may be bigger or smaller than the minimum value of the data domain.
17023  * <p>
17024  * For more information, see {@link #fixedLength}.
17025  * 
17026  * @type number|string|Date
17027  * @category Continuous > Scale
17028  */
17029 pvc.options.axes.NumericCartesianAxis.prototype.fixedMin = undefined;
17030 /**
17031  * Indicates if it should be ensured that the 0 domain value is shown (applies to numeric axes).
17032  * <p>
17033  * The properties
17034  * 
17035  * <tt>fixedMin</tt> and
17036  * 
17037  * <tt>fixedMax</tt> have precedence over this one.
17038  * <p>
17039  * If this property is 
17040  * <tt>true</tt>
17041  * and respecting it would require changing
17042  * the minimum value,
17043  * but the option 
17044  * <tt>fixedMin</tt> is also specified,

17046  * The same would apply if
17047  * it were required to change
17048  * the maximum value,
17049  * but the property 
17050  * <tt>fixedMax</tt> was also specified.
17051  * <p>
17052  * For more information, see: {@link #fixedLength}.
17053  * 
17054  * @type boolean
17055  * @category Continuous > Scale
17056  */
17057 pvc.options.axes.NumericCartesianAxis.prototype.originIsZero = undefined;
17058 /**
17059  * Indicates if the initial proportion between the axis' domain and range lengths should be
17060  * preserved between renders (applies to continuous axes).
17061  * <p>
17062  * When using a sliding window for real time applications,
17063  * the ratio preservation allows for a stable visualization,
17064  * regardless of the data values provided.
17065  * <p>
17066  * When 
17067  * <tt>preserveRatio</tt> is specified,
17068  * following renders will use the 
17069  * <i>effective ratio</i> of the first render,
17070  * whether the ratio was initially fixed using 
17071  * <tt>ratio</tt> or not.
17072  * <p>
17073  * See {@link pvc.options.SlidingWindow}.
17074  * 
17075  * <h3>Default</h3>
17076  * If a sliding window exists: 
17077  * <tt>true</tt>, otherwise, 
17078  * <tt>false</tt>.
17079  * <p>
17080  * See {@link #ratio}.
17081  * 
17082  * @type boolean
17083  * @category Continuous > Scale
17084  */
17085 pvc.options.axes.NumericCartesianAxis.prototype.preserveRatio = undefined;
17086 /**
17087  * The fixed ratio value which is the proportion between the axis' range and domain lengths (applies to continuous axes).
17088  * <p>
17089  * This property can be defined as a number or a string.
17090  * <p>
17091  * For example, if the desired correspondence is that 100 pixels (range) represent 25 days (domain),
17092  * the option can be specified with any of the following equivalent forms:
17093  * 
17094  * <ul>
17095  * 
17096  * <li>
17097  * <tt>ratio = "100/25d"</tt>; or</li>
17098  * 
17099  * <li>
17100  * <tt>ratio = "100/216e7"</tt> (
17101  * <tt>"25d" = 216e7</tt> milliseconds); or</li>
17102  * 
17103  * <li>
17104  * <tt>ratio = 4.63e-8</tt>.</li>
17105  * </ul>
17106  * <p>
17107  * For more information,
17108  * see {@link #fixedLength} and {@link #preserveRatio}.
17109  * 
17110  * @type number|pvc.options.varia.TimeRatio
17111  * @category Continuous > Scale
17112  */
17113 pvc.options.axes.NumericCartesianAxis.prototype.ratio = undefined;
17114 /**
17115  * The 
17116  * <i>desired</i> number of major ticks.
17117  * <p>
17118  * A positive integer, possibly infinite.
17119  * <p>
17120  * Attention: This option is ignored when {@link #tickUnit} is specified!
17121  * <p>
17122  * Depending on
17123  * the domain values extent,
17124  * the labels' font size,
17125  * the available space,
17126  * the axis' orientation,
17127  * and the minimum label spacing
17128  * (given by {@link pvc.options.axes.AnyNonHierarchicalCartesianAxis#labelSpacingMin}),
17129  * a maximum number of ticks is implied.
17130  * <p>
17131  * The value of 
17132  * <i>desiredTickCount</i> is clamped to this layout imposed maximum.
17133  * <p>
17134  * When specified and finite,
17135  * the tick calculation algorithm chooses,
17136  * amongst possible tick units,
17137  * the one that results in a number of ticks
17138  * that is 
17139  * <b>closest</b> to the specified 
17140  * <b>desired</b> value.
17141  * <p>
17142  * When specified and infinite (
17143  * <tt>Infinity</tt>),
17144  * the layout imposed maximum is used instead.
17145  * 
17146  * <p>
17147  * 
17148  * <b>The minimum tick count</b>
17149  * </p>
17150  * <p>
17151  * This actually depends on the value of {@link #domainRoundMode}.
17152  * 
17153  * <ul>
17154  * 
17155  * <li>
17156  * 
17157  * <p>
17158  * <b>
17159  * <i>domainRoundMode</i> is {@link pvc.options.varia.AxisDomainRoundingMode#Tick}</b></p>
17160  * <p>
17161  * For tick counts greater than two or three, the algorithm strives to satisfy the user's desire!
17162  * <p>
17163  * However,
17164  * the algorithm always generates at least two or three ticks,
17165  * ignoring both 
17166  * <i>desiredTickCount</i> and 
17167  * <i>labelSpacingMin</i>,
17168  * if needed.
17169  * <p>
17170  * At least three ticks are generated for numeric domains having both negative and positive data.
17171  * There are also temporal domain cases where a minimum of three ticks are generated.
17172  * <p>
17173  * When the labels of these ticks really overlap,
17174  * one of the labels is kept visible and the other(s) is hidden.
17175  * <p>
17176  * This behavior ensures that, unless it is really impossible to do so,
17177  * the axis serves one of its main purposes - allowing to translate visual lengths.
17178  * <p>
17179  * When three tick labels overlap,
17180  * the middle label is kept visible and the end labels are hidden.
17181  * <p>
17182  * When two tick labels overlap,
17183  * one of the labels
17184  * — the one with tick value 
17185  * <tt>0</tt>, if any, or the first one, if none —
17186  * is kept visible and the other is hidden.
17187  * </li>
17188  * 
17189  * <li>
17190  * 
17191  * <p>
17192  * <b>
17193  * <i>domainRoundMode</i> is
17194  * {@link pvc.options.varia.AxisDomainRoundingMode#None} or
17195  * {@link pvc.options.varia.AxisDomainRoundingMode#Nice}</b></p>
17196  * <p>
17197  * The algorithm always generates at least one tick.
17198  * </li>
17199  * </ul>
17200  * <p>
17201  * Specifying a value of 
17202  * <tt>1</tt> results in the minimum possible tick count.
17203  * 
17204  * <p>
17205  * 
17206  * <b>Domain type specifics</b>
17207  * </p>
17208  * 
17209  * <ul>
17210  * 
17211  * <li>
17212  * 
17213  * <b>Numeric</b>
17214  * <p>
17215  * When unspecified, the default value is 
17216  * <tt>Infinity</tt>.
17217  * </li>
17218  * 
17219  * <li>
17220  * 
17221  * <b>Temporal</b>
17222  * <p>
17223  * The value must be less than or equal to 
17224  * <tt>10</tt>.
17225  * <p>
17226  * When unspecified, the default value is 
17227  * <tt>5</tt>.
17228  * </li>
17229  * </ul>
17230  * <p>
17231  * See {@link #tickUnit} for more information.
17232  * 
17233  * @type number
17234  * @category Continuous > Style
17235  */
17236 pvc.options.axes.NumericCartesianAxis.prototype.desiredTickCount = undefined;
17237 /**
17238  * Indicates if minor ticks are shown between major ticks (applies to continuous axes).
17239  * 
17240  * @type boolean
17241  * @default true
17242  * @category Continuous > Style
17243  */
17244 pvc.options.axes.NumericCartesianAxis.prototype.minorTicks = undefined;
17245 /**
17246  * The ticks' major unit (difference in domain value between consecutive ticks).
17247  * <p>
17248  * When a number, it must be a non-negative, finite, integer.
17249  * 
17250  * <ul>
17251  * 
17252  * <li>
17253  * 
17254  * <b>Numeric axis</b>
17255  * <p>
17256  * Specified values are rounded down to one of the standard precisions:
17257  * a number that is an integer power of 10,
17258  * multiplied by 1, 2 or 5 (e.g. 0.1, 0.2, 0.5, 1, 2, 5, 10, 20, 50, ...).
17259  * </li>
17260  * 
17261  * <li>
17262  * 
17263  * <b>Temporal axis</b>
17264  * <p>
17265  * When a number or numeric string is specified,
17266  * it is a the number of milliseconds of a duration.
17267  * <p>
17268  * It is rounded down to an integer and used directly.
17269  * By default, the corresponding tick format will be the one of the
17270  * greatest standard unit that is below the specified value.
17271  * <p>
17272  * When a (non-numeric) string is specified,
17273  * it should be the code of a standard precision,
17274  * optionally immediately preceded by an integer multiple
17275  * (e.g. 
17276  * <tt>'25d'</tt> means twenty five days).
17277  * <p>
17278  * The standard time precision codes are defined in {@link pvc.options.varia.TimeInterval}
17279  * <p>
17280  * This option should be used instead of the now deprecated
17281  * {@link pvc.options.marks.QuantitativeScaleExtensionPoint#dateTickPrecision}
17282  * extension point, via {@link #extensionPoints} and then 
17283  * <i>scale</i>.
17284  * </li>
17285  * </ul>
17286  * 
17287  * <b>Relations with other options</b>
17288  * <p>
17289  * When both {@link #tickUnitMin} and {@link #tickUnitMax} are specified,
17290  * and the former is greater than or equal to the later,
17291  * then it is as if 
17292  * <i>tickUnit</i> had been specified with the value of 
17293  * <i>tickUnitMin</i>.
17294  * <p>
17295  * When both 
17296  * <i>tickUnit</i> and {@link #tickUnitMin} are specified,
17297  * and 
17298  * <i>tickUnit</i> is less than 
17299  * <i>tickUnitMin</i>,
17300  * then the value of 
17301  * <i>tickUnitMin</i> is used instead.
17302  * <p>
17303  * When both 
17304  * <i>tickUnit</i> and {@link #tickUnitMax} are specified,
17305  * and 
17306  * <i>tickUnit</i> is greater than 
17307  * <i>tickUnitMax</i>,
17308  * then the value of 
17309  * <i>tickUnitMax</i> is used instead.
17310  * <p>
17311  * When specified or implied,
17312  * both {@link #desiredTickCount} and 
17313  * <i>labelSpacingMin</i>
17314  * are ignored.
17315  * <p>
17316  * See related axis options:
17317  * {@link #tickUnitMin},
17318  * {@link #tickUnitMax},
17319  * {@link #domainRoundMode},
17320  * {@link #desiredTickCount} and
17321  * {@link pvc.options.axes.AnyNonHierarchicalCartesianAxis#labelSpacingMin}.
17322  * <p>
17323  * For numeric axes, see also
17324  * {@link pvc.options.axes.NumericCartesianAxis#tickExponentMin} and
17325  * {@link pvc.options.axes.NumericCartesianAxis#tickExponentMax}.
17326  * 
17327  * @type number|string|pvc.options.varia.TimeInterval
17328  * @category Continuous > Style
17329  */
17330 pvc.options.axes.NumericCartesianAxis.prototype.tickUnit = undefined;
17331 /**
17332  * The maximum ticks' major unit (difference in domain value between consecutive ticks).
17333  * <p>
17334  * Use this option to ensure that ticks are separated by at most a certain value.
17335  * For example,
17336  * a value of 
17337  * <tt>100</tt> ensures that the unit 
17338  * <tt>200</tt> will not be used,
17339  * and of 
17340  * <tt>'3m'</tt> that a year or semester unit will not be used.
17341  * <p>
17342  * As another example,
17343  * to ensure that the tick unit is less than 
17344  * <tt>1000</tt>,
17345  * either
17346  * specify a 
17347  * <i>tickUnitMax</i> of 
17348  * <tt>900</tt>, or, maybe better,
17349  * specify a {@link pvc.options.axes.NumericCartesianAxis#tickExponentMax} of 
17350  * <tt>2</tt>.
17351  * <p>
17352  * When a number, it must be a positive integer.
17353  * <p>
17354  * The same value parsing rules of {@link #tickUnit} apply to this option.
17355  * <p>
17356  * For numeric axes,
17357  * the value of this option is combined with that of
17358  * {@link pvc.options.axes.NumericCartesianAxis#tickExponentMax},
17359  * resulting in the most restrictive one being used.
17360  * <p>
17361  * See {@link #tickUnit} for more information.
17362  * 
17363  * @type number|string
17364  * @default Infinity
17365  * @category Continuous > Style
17366  */
17367 pvc.options.axes.NumericCartesianAxis.prototype.tickUnitMax = undefined;
17368 /**
17369  * The minimum ticks' major unit (difference in domain value between consecutive ticks).
17370  * <p>
17371  * Use this option to ensure that ticks are separated by a minimum value.
17372  * For example, a value of 
17373  * <tt>1</tt> ensures ticks are integers,
17374  * and of 
17375  * <tt>'d'</tt>, that hour ticks are not used.
17376  * <p>
17377  * When a number, it must be a non-negative finite integer.
17378  * <p>
17379  * The same value parsing rules of {@link #tickUnit} apply to this option,
17380  * with the exception that rounding to a standard precision is performed 
17381  * <i>up</i>.
17382  * <p>
17383  * For numeric axes,
17384  * the value of this option is combined with that of
17385  * {@link pvc.options.axes.NumericCartesianAxis#tickExponentMin},
17386  * resulting in the most restrictive one being used.
17387  * <p>
17388  * See {@link #tickUnit} for more information.
17389  * 
17390  * @type number|string
17391  * @default 0
17392  * @category Continuous > Style
17393  */
17394 pvc.options.axes.NumericCartesianAxis.prototype.tickUnitMin = undefined;
17395 /**
17396  * The axis' domain rounding mode (applies to continuous axes).
17397  * 
17398  * @type pvc.options.varia.AxisDomainRoundingMode
17399  * @default 'tick'
17400  * @category Continuous-Numeric > Style
17401  */
17402 pvc.options.axes.NumericCartesianAxis.prototype.domainRoundMode = undefined;
17403 /**
17404  * The maximum exponent of 
17405  * <tt>10</tt> that is used to generate ticks (applies to continuous-numeric axes).
17406  * <p>
17407  * The value of this option is combined with that of {@link #tickUnitMax},
17408  * resulting in the most restrictive one being used.
17409  * <p>
17410  * The generated ticks are separated by a 
17411  * <i>step</i> value.
17412  * A step value is a certain power of 
17413  * <tt>10</tt>,
17414  * possibly multiplied by 
17415  * <tt>2</tt> or 
17416  * <tt>5</tt>.
17417  * <p>
17418  * For example, 
17419  * for a chosen exponent of 
17420  * <tt>4</tt>,
17421  * the corresponding power of 
17422  * <tt>10</tt> is 
17423  * <tt>10^4=10000</tt> and
17424  * the generated ticks could be:
17425  * 
17426  * <tt>0</tt>, 
17427  * <tt>10000</tt>, 
17428  * <tt>20000</tt>, ...
17429  * <p>
17430  * If the multiplier 
17431  * <tt>5</tt> was chosen, 
17432  * those ticks would instead be:
17433  * 
17434  * <tt>0</tt>, 
17435  * <tt>50000</tt>, 
17436  * <tt>100000</tt>, ...
17437  * <p>
17438  * Setting this property allows imposing a limit on 
17439  * the size of numbers chosen to separate ticks,
17440  * which may be seen as imposing a minimum granularity 
17441  * on the generated tick values.
17442  * <p>
17443  * See {@link #tickUnit} for more information.
17444  * 
17445  * @type number
17446  * @category Continuous-Numeric > Style
17447  */
17448 pvc.options.axes.NumericCartesianAxis.prototype.tickExponentMax = undefined;
17449 /**
17450  * The minimum exponent of 
17451  * <tt>10</tt> that is used to generate ticks (applies to continuous-numeric axes).
17452  * <p>
17453  * The value of this option is combined with that of {@link #tickUnitMax},
17454  * resulting in the most restrictive one being used.
17455  * <p>
17456  * The generated ticks are separated by a 
17457  * <i>step</i> value.
17458  * A step value is a certain power of 
17459  * <tt>10</tt>,
17460  * possibly multiplied by 
17461  * <tt>2</tt> or 
17462  * <tt>5</tt>.
17463  * <p>
17464  * For example, 
17465  * for a chosen exponent of 
17466  * <tt>2</tt>,
17467  * the corresponding power of 
17468  * <tt>10</tt> is 
17469  * <tt>10^2=100</tt> and
17470  * the generated ticks could be:
17471  * 
17472  * <tt>0</tt>, 
17473  * <tt>100</tt>, 
17474  * <tt>200</tt>, ...
17475  * <p>
17476  * If the multiplier 
17477  * <tt>2</tt> was chosen, 
17478  * those ticks would instead be:
17479  * 
17480  * <tt>0</tt>, 
17481  * <tt>200</tt>, 
17482  * <tt>400</tt>, ...
17483  * <p>
17484  * Setting this property to 
17485  * <tt>2</tt> would ensure 
17486  * that generated ticks would be separated by the step values
17487  * 
17488  * <tt>100</tt>, 
17489  * <tt>200</tt> or 
17490  * <tt>500</tt>,
17491  * or by steps whose corresponding exponent is 
17492  * bigger than 
17493  * <tt>2</tt>, 
17494  * like: 
17495  * <tt>1000</tt>, 
17496  * <tt>2000</tt> or 
17497  * <tt>5000</tt>.
17498  * <p>
17499  * A more typical use case is ensuring that generated ticks are integers.
17500  * A value of 
17501  * <tt>tickExponentMin</tt> of 
17502  * <tt>0</tt> would accomplish that.
17503  * <p>
17504  * Generally, 
17505  * to impose a maximum number of decimal places on the generated ticks, 
17506  * a negative number can be specified.
17507  * For example, the value 
17508  * <tt>-1</tt> could generate the ticks:
17509  * 
17510  * <tt>0.1</tt>, 
17511  * <tt>0.2</tt>, 
17512  * <tt>0.3</tt>, ...
17513  * If the multiplier 
17514  * <tt>5</tt> was chosen, 
17515  * those ticks would instead be:
17516  * 
17517  * <tt>0.5</tt>, 
17518  * <tt>1.0</tt>, 
17519  * <tt>1.5</tt>, ...
17520  * It could not generate ticks 
17521  * with more that one decimal place.
17522  * <p>
17523  * See {@link #tickUnit} for more information.
17524  * 
17525  * @type number
17526  * @category Continuous-Numeric > Style
17527  */
17528 pvc.options.axes.NumericCartesianAxis.prototype.tickExponentMin = undefined;
17529 /**
17530  * Indicates if the zero line rule is drawn, 
17531  * on the position of the 0-valued tick, 
17532  * when there is one (applies to continuous-numeric axes).
17533  * <p>
17534  * An horizontal axis has a vertical zero line rule,
17535  * while a a vertical axis has an horizontal zero line rule.
17536  * 
17537  * @type boolean
17538  * @default true
17539  * @category Continuous-Numeric > Style
17540  */
17541 pvc.options.axes.NumericCartesianAxis.prototype.zeroLine = undefined;

17543  * The minimum spacing between tick labels, in

17547  * Attention:
17548  * In continuous axes,
17549  * this option is ignored when {@link pvc.options.axes.AnyContinuousCartesianAxis#tickUnit}
17550  * is specified,
17551  * or when only two or three ticks are used!
17552  * <p>
17553  * See {@link pvc.options.axes.AnyContinuousCartesianAxis#tickUnit} for more information.

17555  * @type number
17556  * @category Non-Hierarchical > Layout
17557  */
17558 pvc.options.axes.NumericCartesianAxis.prototype.labelSpacingMin = undefined;

17562  * 
17563  * @type boolean
17564  * @default true
17565  * @category Non-Hierarchical > Style
17566  */
17567 pvc.options.axes.NumericCartesianAxis.prototype.ticks = undefined;

17916  * <ol>
17917  * 
17918  * <li>panel property name (ex: 
17919  * <tt>legend</tt>)</li>
17920  * 
17921  * <li>extension property (ex: 
17922  * <tt>label</tt>)</li>
17923  * 
17924  * <li>the "_" character</li>
17925  * 
17926  * <li>extension sub-property (ex: 
17927  * <tt>textStyle</tt>)</li>
17928  * </ol>
17929  * and obtaining, for the examples, the camel-cased name: 
17930  * <tt>legendLabel_textStyle</tt>
17931  * (see {@link http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CamelCase}).
17932  * 
17933  * @class
17934  */
