18182 /**
18183  * The options documentation class for 
18184  * specifying trending options for a plot.
18185  * <p>
18186  * Each trend type may define additional options.
18187  * Specifying additional options requires using object notation
18188  * for the trend option, like in the following example:
18189  * 
18190  * <pre>
18191  *             var chartOptions = {
18192  *                 trend: {
18193  *                     type:    'moving-average',
18194  *                     label:   'My Trend',
18195  *                     periods: 4 // additional option of the 'moving-average' trend type
18196  *                 }
18197  *             };
18198  *             
18199  * </pre>
18200  * Trending is performed after null-interpolation,
18201  * so that it takes the null-interpolated datums into account. 
18202  * 
18203  * @class
18204  */
18205 pvc.options.varia.PlotTrending = function(){};
18206         
18207         
18208         
18209         
18210 /**
18211  * A description to show next to the trended data.
18212  * <p>
18213  * The description shows next to legend items and 
18214  * in auto-generated tooltips.
18215  * <p>
18216  * The default value is the description of the associated trend type.  
18217  * 
18218  * @type string
18219  */
18220 pvc.options.varia.PlotTrending.prototype.label = undefined;
18221 /**
18222  * The type of trend to perform on the data of the associated plot.
18223  * <p>
18224  * The specified trend type must have been 
18225  * previously defined in the CCC library, 
18226  * through the 
18227  * <tt>pvc.trends.define</tt> method.
18228  * <p>
18229  * Some trend types come with the CCC library. 
18230  * Currently these are:
18231  * 
18232  * <dl>
18233  * 
18234  * <dt>'linear'</dt>
18235  * 
18236  * <dd>
18237  * performs a 
18238  * <bb>simple linear regression</bb>
18239  * (see {@link http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simple_linear_regression})
18240  * </dd>
18241  * 
18242  * <dt>'moving-average'</dt>
18243  * 
18244  * <dd>
18245  * performs a simple moving average
18246  * (see {@link http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moving_average});
18247  * the additional option 
18248  * <tt>periods</tt>, which defaults to 
18249  * <tt>3</tt>, and must not be less than 
18250  * <tt>2</tt>, 
18251  * may be specified to control the number of data points of the average window.
18252  * </dd>
18253  * 
18254  * <dt>'weighted-moving-average'</dt>
18255  * 
18256  * <dd>
18257  * performs a weighted moving average
18258  * (see {@link http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moving_average});
18259  * the additional option 
18260  * <tt>periods</tt>, which defaults to 
18261  * <tt>3</tt>, and must not be less than 
18262  * <tt>2</tt>, 
18263  * may be specified to control the number of data points of the average window.
18264  * </dd>
18265  * </dl> 
18266  * 
18267  * @type string
18268  */
18269 pvc.options.varia.PlotTrending.prototype.type = undefined;

18431 pvc.options.format = {};
18432 
18433 /**
18434  * The options documentation of the format provider class.
18435  * <p>
18436  * A format provider contains formats for main value types and main modes in which these are formatted.
18437  * Currently, it contains the following formats:
18438  * {@link pvc.options.format.FormatProvider#number} ,
18439  * {@link pvc.options.format.FormatProvider#percent},
18440  * {@link pvc.options.format.FormatProvider#date} and
18441  * {@link pvc.options.format.FormatProvider#any}.
18442  * 
18443  * <p>
18444  * Format providers exist in, and can be configured at,
18445  * three levels, from most specific to least specific:
18446  * </p>
18447  * 
18448  * <dl>
18449  * 
18450  * <dt>
18451  * <b>Dimension Type</b></dt>
18452  * 
18453  * <dd>
18454  * Most formatting operations use a dimension type's format provider to obtain a format.
18455  * <p>
18456  * By default, the unconfigured properties of a dimension type's format provider
18457  * inherit the corresponding value obtained from the chart's format provider.
18458  * <p>
18459  * A dimension type's format provider is configured through
18460  * the option {@link pvc.options.DimensionType#format}.
18461  * </dd>
18462  * 
18463  * <dt>
18464  * <b>Chart</b></dt>
18465  * 
18466  * <dd>
18467  * The chart's format provides defaults for all formatting operations done in the chart.
18468  * <p>
18469  * The unconfigured properties of a chart's format provider
18470  * inherit the corresponding value obtained from the global format provider
18471  * (any format provider directly or indirectly inherits from the global format provider).
18472  * <p>
18473  * A chart's format provider is configured
18474  * through the option {@link pvc.options.charts.BasicChart#format}.
18475  * </dd>
18476  * 
18477  * <dt>
18478  * <b>Global</b></dt>
18479  * 
18480  * <dd>
18481  * Allows changing the default formats used by all charts.
18482  * <p>
18483  * The global format provider exists in 
18484  * <tt>pvc.data.format.defaults</tt>.
18485  * And can also be accessed by its alias 
18486  * <tt>cdo.format.defaults</tt>.
18487  * 
18488  * <p>
18489  * Using the auxiliary method 
18490  * <tt>def.configure</tt>,
18491  * global defaults can be configured the following way:
18492  * 
18493  * <pre>
18494  * def.configure(pvc.data.format.defaults, {
18495  *     number: {
18496  *         mask: "#,0.00",
18497  *         style: {
18498  *             decimal: ",",
18499  *             group: "."
18500  *         }
18501  *     },
18502  *     date: "%m %Y"
18503  * });
18504  *                         
18505  * </pre>
18506  * 
18507  * <p>
18508  * 
18509  * <p>
18510  * Configuring global defaults can also be done
18511  * by using the format provider and contained objects' accessor methods
18512  * (which follow a similar structure to that of the here documented options):
18513  * 
18514  * <pre>
18515  * pvc.data.format.defaults
18516  *     .number().mask("#,0.00");
18517  * 
18518  * pvc.data.format.defaults
18519  *     .style()
18520  *         .decimal(",")
18521  *         .group(".");
18522  * 
18523  * pvc.data.format.defaults
18524  *     .date("%m %Y");
18525  *                         
18526  * </pre>
18527  * 
18528  * <p>
18529  * </dd>
18530  * </dl>
18531  * 
18532  * <h2>
18533  * Internationalization
18534  * </h2>
18535  * 
18536  * <p>
18537  * Get, set, create and configure different format providers arranged by language.
18538  * <p>
18539  * The default language is 
18540  * <i>en-us</i> but can also be accessed with an empty string.
18541  * It's configuration is the same as the global defaults in cdo.
18542  * </p>
18543  * 
18544  * <p>
18545  * 
18546  * <b>Warning:</b> If you change cdo global defaults, the configuration for the default
18547  * language 
18548  * <i>en-us</i> will also change, so changing them is not recommended.
18549  * </p>
18550  * 
18551  * <dl>
18552  * 
18553  * <dt>Create or configure a format provider by specifying a language and the configuration object</dt>
18554  * 
18555  * <dd>
18556  * 
18557  * <p>
18558  * 
18559  * <pre>
18560  * cdo.format.language('fr-fr', {
18561  *     number: {
18562  *         mask:              '#,0.##',
18563  *         style: {
18564  *             integerPad:    '0',
18565  *             fractionPad:   '0',
18566  *             decimal:       ',',
18567  *             group:         ' ',
18568  *             groupSizes:    [3],
18569  *             abbreviations: ['k','m', 'b', 't'],
18570  *             negativeSign:  '-',
18571  *             currency:      '€'
18572  *         }
18573  *     },
18574  *     date: {
18575  *         mask:              '%d/%m/%Y'
18576  *     }
18577  * });
18578  *                         
18579  * </pre>
18580  * 
18581  * <p>
18582  * </dd>
18583  * 
18584  * <dt>Create or configure multiple format providers</dt>
18585  * 
18586  * <dd>
18587  * 
18588  * <p>
18589  * 
18590  * <pre>
18591  * cdo.format.language({
18592  *     'en-us': {
18593  *         number: {
18594  *             mask:              '0,0 Currency',
18595  *         },
18596  *         date: '%Y/%m/%d'
18597  *     },
18598  *     'en-gb': {
18599  *         number: {
18600  *             mask:              '0.00 Abbreviation',
18601  *             style: {
18602  *                 abbreviations: ['k','m', 'b', 't']
18603  *             }
18604  *     }
18605  * });
18606  *                         
18607  * </pre>
18608  * 
18609  * <p>
18610  * </dd>
18611  * 
18612  * <dt>Get the format provider of a specific language</dt>
18613  * 
18614  * <dd>
18615  * 
18616  * <p>
18617  * 
18618  * <pre>
18619  * cdo.format.language('pt-pt');
18620  *                         
18621  * </pre>
18622  * 
18623  * <p>
18624  * </dd>
18625  * </dl>
18626  * 
18627  * @class
18628  */
18629 pvc.options.format.FormatProvider = function(){};
18630         
18631         
18632         
18633         
18634 /**
18635  * The format function/object used to format values of other data types,
18636  * like 
18637  * <i>string</i>, 
18638  * <i>boolean</i> and 
18639  * <i>object</i>.
18640  * <p>
18641  * When a function is specified,
18642  * it is the {@link pvc.options.format.CustomFormat#formatter} property
18643  * of a new custom format that replaces the current format.
18644  * <p>
18645  * When an object is specified, it configures the 
18646  * <i>current</i> format object.
18647  * <p>
18648  * Alternatively, a direct instance of {@link pvc.options.format.CustomFormat}
18649  * can be specified, replacing the existing format.
18650  * <p>
18651  * The global default custom formatter formats 
18652  * <i>nully</i>
18653  * values as an empty string and
18654  * other values by calling their 
18655  * <i>#toString()</i> method.
18656  * 
18657  * @type function|object|pvc.options.format.CustomFormat
18658  */
18659 pvc.options.format.FormatProvider.prototype.any = undefined;
18660 /**
18661  * The format function/object used to format date/time objects.
18662  * <p>
18663  * When a string is specified,
18664  * it is the {@link pvc.options.format.DateFormat#mask} property of
18665  * a new date format that replaces the current format.
18666  * <p>
18667  * When a function is specified,
18668  * it is the {@link pvc.options.format.CustomFormat#formatter} property
18669  * of a new custom format that replaces the current format.
18670  * <p>
18671  * When an object is specified, it configures the 
18672  * <i>current</i> format object.
18673  * <p>
18674  * Alternatively, direct instances of
18675  * {@link pvc.options.format.DateFormat} and {@link pvc.options.format.CustomFormat}
18676  * can be specified, replacing the existing format.
18677  * <p>
18678  * The global default date mask id 
18679  * <tt>"%Y/%m/%d"</tt>.
18680  * 
18681  * @type string|function|object|pvc.options.format.DateFormat|pvc.options.format.CustomFormat
18682  */
18683 pvc.options.format.FormatProvider.prototype.date = undefined;
18684 /**
18685  * The format function/object used to format numbers in a general way.
18686  * <p>
18687  * When a string is specified,
18688  * it is the {@link pvc.options.format.NumberFormat#mask} property of
18689  * a new number format that replaces the current format.
18690  * <p>
18691  * When a function is specified,
18692  * it is the {@link pvc.options.format.CustomFormat#formatter} property
18693  * of a new custom format that replaces the current format.
18694  * <p>
18695  * When an object is specified, it configures the 
18696  * <i>current</i> format object.
18697  * <p>
18698  * Alternatively, direct instances of
18699  * {@link pvc.options.format.NumberFormat} and {@link pvc.options.format.CustomFormat}
18700  * can be specified, replacing the existing format.
18701  * <p>
18702  * The global default of the number format mask is 
18703  * <tt>"#,0.##"</tt> —
18704  * numbers are first rounded to decimal places.
18705  * Then, they are formatted with a thousands group separator and only significant decimal places.
18706  * <p>
18707  * See the {@link pvc.options.format.NumberFormatStyle}
18708  * for information on the global default number styles.
18709  * <p>
18710  * See also related information in {@link pvc.options.charts.BasicChart#valueFormat}.
18711  * 
18712  * @type string|function|object|pvc.options.format.NumberFormat|pvc.options.format.CustomFormat
18713  */
18714 pvc.options.format.FormatProvider.prototype.number = undefined;
18715 /**
18716  * The format function/object used to format percentage numbers.
18717  * <p>
18718  * The formatting function should multiply the numeric value by 100.
18719  * <p>
18720  * This function is used whenever a chart needs to show percentages,
18721  * like in the tooltips of a stacked chart or the percentages shown in a Pie chart.
18722  * <p>
18723  * When a string is specified,
18724  * it is the {@link pvc.options.format.NumberFormat#mask} property of
18725  * a new number format that replaces the current format.
18726  * <p>
18727  * When a function is specified,
18728  * it is the {@link pvc.options.format.CustomFormat#formatter} property
18729  * of a new custom format that replaces the current format.
18730  * <p>
18731  * When an object is specified, it configures the 
18732  * <i>current</i> format object.
18733  * <p>
18734  * Alternatively, direct instances of
18735  * {@link pvc.options.format.NumberFormat} and {@link pvc.options.format.CustomFormat}
18736  * can be specified, replacing the existing format.
18737  * <p>
18738  * The global default percent mask is 
18739  * <tt>"#,0.#%"</tt> —
18740  * numbers are first multiplied by 100 and then
18741  * rounded to one decimal place.
18742  * Then, they are formatted
18743  * with a thousands group separator,
18744  * with only significant decimal places,
18745  * and by appending a "%" character.
18746  * <p>
18747  * See the {@link pvc.options.format.NumberFormatStyle}
18748  * for information on the global default number styles.
18749  * <p>
18750  * See also related information in {@link pvc.options.charts.Chart#percentValueFormat}.
18751  * 
18752  * @type string|function|object|pvc.options.format.NumberFormat|pvc.options.format.CustomFormat
18753  */
18754 pvc.options.format.FormatProvider.prototype.percent = undefined;

18964 pvc.options.format.CustomFormat.prototype.formatter = function(){};
18965 /**
18966  * The options documentation class of a data dimensions reader.
18967  * <p>
18968  * A dimensions reader is executed for each row of a
18969  * data source to convert values of one or more columns
18970  * into one or more atoms of certain dimensions.
18971  * <p>
18972  * Together, a set of dimensions readers,
18973  * are executed to fully convert
18974  * each data source row into atoms of the defined dimension types.
18975  * The atoms of each row are used to construct a datum.
18976  * <p>
18977  * The mentioned data source row is called the 
18978  * <i>logical row</i>.
18979  * Depending on the data source format (crosstab or relational),
18980  * the actual rows carry different informaton.
18981  * The 
18982  * <i>logical row</i> is a normalized view of each row of the data source,
18983  * independent of its format.
18984  * <p>
18985  * A dimensions reader can be configured in the following ways:
18986  * 
18987  * <dl>
18988  * 
18989  * <dt>specify 
18990  * <tt>names</tt> but not 
18991  * <tt>reader</tt></dt>
18992  * 
18993  * <dd>
18994  * names are paired with any specified indexes, from left to right;
18995  * excess indexes feed dimensions whose name starts with the last specified name (a dimension group);
18996  * excess names are fed with the 
18997  * <i>non reserved</i>indexes
18998  * that follow the last specified index (or 0, if none);
18999  * indexes explicitly specified in dimensions readers are all
19000  * reserved beforehand
19001  * </dd>
19002  * 
19003  * <dt>specify 
19004  * <tt>indexes</tt> but not 
19005  * <tt>names</tt> and 
19006  * <tt>reader</tt></dt>
19007  * 
19008  * <dd>
19009  * the specified indexes become reserved but are not read,
19010  * and so are effectively ignored
19011  * </dd>
19012  * 
19013  * <dt>specify both 
19014  * <tt>reader</tt> and 
19015  * <tt>names</tt></dt>
19016  * 
19017  * <dd>
19018  * any specified indexes are reserved,
19019  * and no pairing is performed between these and the specified names;
19020  * the reader function may
19021  * read any column from the 
19022  * <i>logical row</i> and
19023  * return atoms from any of the dimensions specified in 
19024  * <tt>names</tt>;
19025  * atoms of stated dimensions, that are not returned,
19026  * result in a 
19027  * <i>null</i> value;
19028  * this form allows, for example,
19029  * splitting a value in the 
19030  * <i>logical row</i> into two dimensions.
19031  * </dd>
19032  * </dl>
19033  * 
19034  * @class
19035  */
19036 pvc.options.DimensionsReader = function(){};
19037         
19038         
19039         
19040         
19041 /**
19042  * The index or indexes of the columns that the reader reads
19043  * from each 
19044  * <i>logical row</i>.
19045  * <p>
19046  * Only one dimensions reader can state that it reads a given index
19047  * (although a dimensions reader function may sneek into any columns it likes).
19048  * 
19049  * @type number|string|list(number|string)
19050  * @category General
19051  */
19052 pvc.options.DimensionsReader.prototype.indexes = undefined;
19053 /**
19054  * The name or names of the dimensions that the reader reads
19055  * from each 
19056  * <i>logical row</i>.
19057  * <p>
19058  * When the argument is a string, it can be a list of names,
19059  * separated by the character ",".
19060  * <p>
19061  * Only one dimensions reader or dimensions calculation can
19062  * read or calculate a given dimension.
19063  * 
19064  * @type string|list(string)
19065  * @category General
19066  */
19067 pvc.options.DimensionsReader.prototype.names = undefined;
19068 /**
19069  * A dimensions reader function,
19070  * reads the values of dimensions,
19071  * for each 
19072  * <i>logical row</i>.
19073  * <p>
19074  * When unspecified,
19075  * one is created that performs a simple
19076  * mapping between the specified names and indexes.
19077  * <p>
19078  * A dimensions reader function can be specified
19079  * to perform non-simple operations over the read columns,
19080  * like the following:
19081  * 
19082  * <ul>
19083  * 
19084  * <li>
19085  * combine values from two or more columns into a single dimension,
19086  * </li>
19087  * 
19088  * <li>
19089  * split the value of one column into more than one dimension,
19090  * </li>
19091  * 
19092  * <li>
19093  * feed a dimension with correlated data read from an external data source.
19094  * </li>
19095  * </ul>
19096  * <p>
19097  * Dimensions reader functions need not be specifed to perform
19098  * conversion or formatting operations of a single column.
19099  * For those cases, the dimension type's
19100  * {@link pvc.options.DimensionType#converter}
19101  * and
19102  * {@link pvc.options.DimensionType#formatter}
19103  * are more appropriate.
19104  * <p>
19105  * Also, when the value of a dimension
19106  * is calculated from the value of other dimensions,
19107  * a dimensions calculation may be more appropriate:
19108  * see {@link pvc.options.DimensionsCalculation}.
19109  * <p>
19110  * The function may read columns whose indexes were not
19111  * "reserved" in 
19112  * <tt>indexes</tt>.
19113  * Those columns might be read by other readers,
19114  * possibly default ones created by the translator.
19115  * 
19116  * @returns {undefined}
19117  * @method
19118  * @this pvc.data.Data
19119  * @param {list(any)} logicalRow
19120  * The 
19121  * <i>logical row</i> array.
19122  * 
19123  * @param {object} outAtoms
19124  * An object that should be filled with read raw values,
19125  * each placed in a property with the name
19126  * of the corresponding dimension.
19127  * <p>
19128  * It is also possible that the values be the atoms themselves,
19129  * a technique that can be used to achieve greater performance,
19130  * when a dimension only has two or three possible values.
19131  * 
19132  * @category General
19133  */
19134 pvc.options.DimensionsReader.prototype.reader = function(){};
19135 /**
19136  * A dimensions calculation allows the values of a dimension
19137  * to be calculated from the typed values of
19138  * the other non-calculated dimensions.
19139  * <p>
19140  * While a dimensions reader could achieve the same result,
19141  * it works by reading values from the 
19142  * <i>logical table</i>,
19143  * accessing it by index.
19144  * That would require the knowledge of the indexes
19145  * in which the desired dimensions were,
19146  * which is many times not true,
19147  * specially when the mapping between
19148  * dimensions and 
19149  * <i>logical table</i> indexes is determined automatically
19150  * by the data translator.
19151  * 
19152  * @class
19153  */
19154 pvc.options.DimensionsCalculation = function(){};

19167  * whose dimensions are being calculated.
19168  * 
19169  * @param {object} outAtoms
19170  * An object that should be filled with read raw or typed values, 
19171  * each placed in a property with the name
19172  * of the corresponding dimension.
19173  * <p>
19174  * It is also possible that the values be the atoms themselves, 
19175  * a technique that can be used to achieve greater performance,
19176  * when a dimension only has two or three possible values. 
19177  * 
19178  * @category General
19179  */
19180 pvc.options.DimensionsCalculation.prototype.calculation = function(){};

19187  * <p>
19188  * Only one dimensions calculation or dimensions reader

19190  * 
19191  * @type string|list(string)
19192  * @category General

19194 pvc.options.DimensionsCalculation.prototype.names = undefined;

19205 /**
19206  * A function that compares two different and non-null values of the dimension's
19207  * {@link pvc.options.DimensionType#valueType}.
19208  * <p>
19209  * When unspecified,
19210  * a default natural order comparer function
19211  * is applied to the continuous value types:
19212  * {@link pvc.options.varia.DimensionValueType#Number} and
19213  * {@link pvc.options.varia.DimensionValueType#Date}.
19214  * <p>
19215  * Dimension types that do not have a comparer
19216  * function "compare" their values by "input order"
19217  * - order of first appearance, in the data source.
19218  * 
19219  * @returns {number}
19220  * The number 0 if the two values have the same order, 
19221  * a negative number if 
19222  * <tt>a</tt> is before 
19223  * <tt>b</tt>, and
19224  * a positive number if 
19225  * <tt>a</tt> is after 
19226  * <tt>b</tt>.
19227  * 
19228  * @method
19229  * @this null
19230  * @param {any} a
19231  * The first value to compare.
19232  * 
19233  * @param {any} b
19234  * The second value to compare.
19235  * 
19236  * @category Data
19237  */
19238 pvc.options.DimensionType.prototype.comparer = function(){};
19239 /**
19240  * Converts a non-null raw value,
19241  * as read from the data source,
19242  * into a value of the dimension's {@link #valueType}.
19243  * <p>
19244  * The returned value
19245  * need not have the type of the dimension's value type.
19246  * Yet,
19247  * it must be such that
19248  * the associated value type's cast function can
19249  * convert it to the dimension's value type.
19250  * In this way,
19251  * only "non-standard" conversions
19252  * need to be handled with a converter function.
19253  * <p>
19254  * Values that are not convertible by the dimension's value type
19255  * cast function become null.
19256  * <p>
19257  * Also, note that the only value type that
19258  * does not have a cast function is the
19259  * {@link pvc.options.varia.DimensionValueType#Any}.
19260  * <p>
19261  * When unspecified and
19262  * the value type is {@link pvc.options.varia.DimensionValueType#Date},
19263  * and the option {@link #rawFormat} is specified
19264  * a default converter is created for it.
19265  * 
19266  * @returns {any}
19267  * The converted value.
19268  * 
19269  * @method
19270  * @this null
19271  * @param {any} sourceValue
19272  * The non-null source value to convert.
19273  * <p>
19274  * In the case where the raw value to convert is 
19275  * a Google-table-like cell, 
19276  * it is the value of its 
19277  * <tt>v</tt>
19278  * property that is passed to this argument.
19279  * 
19280  * @category Data
19281  */
19282 pvc.options.DimensionType.prototype.converter = function(){};
19283 /**
19284  * Indicates if a dimension type should be considered discrete
19285  * or continuous.
19286  * <p>
19287  * Only dimension types whose {@link #valueType}
19288  * is one of
19289  * {@link pvc.options.varia.DimensionValueType#Number} or
19290  * {@link pvc.options.varia.DimensionValueType#Date}
19291  * can be continuous.
19292  * <p>
19293  * Some chart types support binding
19294  * a continuous or a discrete dimension to a visual role,
19295  * yielding different visual results.
19296  * An example is the "color" visual role of the Metric Line/Dot charts.
19297  * Another example is the Line/Dot/Area chart that supports
19298  * both a continuous or a discrete dimension in its "category" visual role.
19299  * <p>

19301  * If it can be continuous, then the default value is 
19302  * <tt>false</tt>.

19304  * <tt>true</tt>.
19305  * 
19306  * @type boolean

19318 pvc.options.DimensionType.prototype.isKey = undefined;
19319 /**
19320  * A function that converts a non-null value of the dimension's

19336  * <p>

19382 /**
19383  * The dimension type's format provider.
19384  * <p>
19385  * When the option {@link #formatter} is specified, this one is ignored.
19386  * <p>
19387  * When a string, it is the mask of the
19388  * {@link pvc.options.format.FormatProvider#number} or
19389  * {@link pvc.options.format.FormatProvider#date} formats,
19390  * depending on the dimension's the dimension's
19391  * {@link pvc.options.DimensionType#valueType},
19392  * of a new format provider that replaces the current one.
19393  * <p>
19394  * When a function, it is the formatter of the
19395  * {@link pvc.options.format.FormatProvider#number} or
19396  * {@link pvc.options.format.FormatProvider#date} custom formats,
19397  * depending on the dimension's the dimension's
19398  * {@link pvc.options.DimensionType#valueType},
19399  * of a new format provider that replaces the current one.
19400  * Note that specifying a function to this property is equivalent to specifying
19401  * {@link pvc.options.DimensionType#formatter}.
19402  * <p>
19403  * When an object is specified,
19404  * it configures the 
19405  * <i>current</i> format object.
19406  * <p>
19407  * Alternatively,
19408  * a direct instance of
19409  * {@link pvc.options.format.FormatProvider},
19410  * can be specified, replacing the existing format provider.
19411  * Instead, specifying
19412  * {@link pvc.options.format.NumberFormat},
19413  * {@link pvc.options.format.DateFormat},
19414  * or {@link pvc.options.format.CustomFormat}
19415  * configures the existing format provider.
19416  * <p>
19417  * A protovis format string that is to format a value of
19418  * the dimension's
19419  * {@link pvc.options.DimensionType#valueType}.
19420  * <p>
19421  * When unspecified,
19422  * and the dimension type's value type is {@link pvc.options.varia.DimensionValueType#Date},
19423  * and the property {@link #rawFormat} is specified,
19424  * a format string is derived from the later by replacing the "-" character with a "/" character.
19425  * <p>
19426  * Otherwise, the dimension type's format provider inherits its
19427  * property values from the chart's format provider.
19428  * 
19429  * @type string|function|object|pvc.options.format.FormatProvider
19430  * @category Presentation
19431  */
19432 pvc.options.DimensionType.prototype.format = undefined;
19433 /**
19434  * A function that formats a value,
19435  * possibly null,
19436  * of the dimension's
19437  * {@link pvc.options.DimensionType#valueType}.
19438  * <p>
19439  * Note that, the chart option
19440  * {@link pvc.options.charts.BasicChart#valueFormat},
19441  * is used to build a default formatter function
19442  * for numeric dimensions of the "value" dimension group.
19443  * <p>
19444  * When unspecified and
19445  * the value type is {@link pvc.options.varia.DimensionValueType#Number},
19446  * a default formatter is created that formats numbers with two decimal places.
19447  * <p>
19448  * When unspecified and
19449  * the value type is {@link pvc.options.varia.DimensionValueType#Date},
19450  * and the option {@link #format} is specified (or implied)
19451  * a default formatter is created for it.
19452  * <p>
19453  * Otherwise a value is formatted by calling
19454  * the standard JavaScript 
19455  * <tt>String</tt> function on it.
19456  * 
19457  * @returns {string}
19458  * The string that is the formatted value.
19459  * Only the 
19460  * <tt>null</tt> value 
19461  * <i>should</i> have the empty string
19462  * as the formatted value.
19463  * 
19464  * @method
19465  * @this null
19466  * @param {any} value
19467  * The value to format.
19468  * 
19469  * @param {any} [sourceValue]
19470  * The source (or raw) value,
19471  * when the value was read from a data source,
19472  * or 
19473  * <tt>undefined</tt>, otherwise.
19474  * <p>
19475  * In the case where the raw value is 
19476  * a Google-table-like cell, 
19477  * it is the value of its 
19478  * <i>v</i>
19479  * property that is passed to this argument.
19480  * 
19481  * @category Presentation
19482  */
19483 pvc.options.DimensionType.prototype.formatter = function(){};
19484 /**

19487  * <p>

19490  * <ul>
19491  *

19494  * <li>
19495  * complete the minimal working information a chart needs to work,
19496  * like, for example,
19497  * a "series" dimension created automatically by a chart if
19498  * its required "series" visual role was not unbound
19499  * </li>
19500  * </ul>

19528 /**
19529  * The options documentation class of a sliding window for real time use.
19530  * <p>
19531  * A sliding window defines the range of data to be kept, this is,
19532  * all data outside the window is removed and therefore lost.
19533  * <p>
19534  * The intended use is the real time case where data is being delivered at some rate and
19535  * the window is "sliding", allowing the visualization of the most recent set of data in
19536  * a given domain span.
19537  * <p>
19538  * When slidingWindow is set to 
19539  * <tt>true</tt>, the following properties have the
19540  * indicated default values:
19541  * 
19542  * <ul>
19543  * 
19544  * <li>
19545  * 
19546  * <tt>preserveMap</tt>: 
19547  * <tt>true</tt>,
19548  * see {@link pvc.options.axes.DiscreteColorAxis#preserveMap};
19549  * </li>
19550  * 
19551  * <li>
19552  * 
19553  * <tt>preserveRatio</tt>: 
19554  * <tt>true</tt>,
19555  * see {@link pvc.options.axes.AnyContinuousCartesianAxis#preserveRatio};
19556  * </li>
19557  * 
19558  * <li>
19559  * 
19560  * <tt>fixedLength</tt> -
19561  * if the sliding window length ({@link #length}) is defined,
19562  * fixed length is set to this value;
19563  * see
19564  * {@link pvc.options.axes.AnyContinuousCartesianAxis#fixedLength} and
19565  * {@link pvc.options.axes.SizeAxis#fixedLength};
19566  * </li>
19567  * 
19568  * <li>
19569  * 
19570  * <tt>comparer</tt>: 
19571  * <tt>def.ascending</tt>,
19572  * see {@link pvc.options.DimensionType#comparer}.
19573  * </li>
19574  * </ul>
19575  * 
19576  * @class
19577  */

20198 /**
20199  * The domain alignment is used to determine the domain of an axis
20200  * when it is specified as a 
20201  * <i>floating</i> domain.
20202  * <p>
20203  * For options like  
20204  * <tt>fixedLength</tt> and 
20205  * <tt>ratio</tt>,
20206  * when specified with 
20207  * <tt>domainAlign</tt>,
20208  * the domain is altered so that a given domain length is kept
20209  * (domain length is either 
20210  * <tt>fixedLength</tt> or derived from 
20211  * <tt>ratio</tt>).
20212  * When altering the domain,
20213  * some values will be kept and others may be lost.
20214  * The domain alignment specifies which values are kept.
20215  * <p>
20216  * This only applies when the domain has some order among its elements,
20217  * and, consequently, some minimum and maximum values.
20218  * <p>
20219  * For more information, see the following axis options:
20220  * {@link pvc.options.axes.AnyContinuousCartesianAxis#fixedLength},
20221  * {@link pvc.options.axes.SizeAxis#fixedLength} and
20222  * {@link pvc.options.axes.AnyContinuousCartesianAxis#ratio}.
20223  * 
20224  * @class
20225  * @enum
20226  * @extends string
20227  */
20228 pvc.options.varia.AxisDomainAlign = function(){};
20229         
20230         
20231         
20232 /**
20233  * Both minimum and maximum may be lost. However, the center is kept: 
20234  * 
20235  * <ul>
20236  * 
20237  * <li>center = (maximum - minimum) / 2.</li>
20238  * </ul>
20239  * 
20240  * @value 'center'
20241  */
20242 pvc.options.varia.AxisDomainAlign.prototype.Center = 'center';
20243 /**
20244  * The maximum value is kept in the domain and the minimum may be lost.
20245  * 
20246  * @value 'max'
20247  */
20248 pvc.options.varia.AxisDomainAlign.prototype.Max = 'max';
20249 /**
20250  * The minimum value is kept in the domain and the maximum may be lost.
20251  * 
20252  * @value 'min'
20253  */
20254 pvc.options.varia.AxisDomainAlign.prototype.Min = 'min';

20524 /**
20525  * The gravity of the tooltip controls 
20526  * where the tooltip is place relative to the
20527  * visual element's anchor point.
20528  * <p>
20529  * The gravity is the 
20530  * tooltip's corner or side
20531  * that is placed at the visual element's anchor point.
20532  * <p>
20533  * Said in yet another way: 
20534  * «Gravity is the direction of the tooltip arrow.
20535  * The arrow points to the target element.»
20536  * 
20537  * <p>
20538  * The following diagram illustrates the
20539  * tooltip arrow anchor points.
20540  * <p>
20541  * When {@link pvc.options.Tooltip#useCorners}
20542  * is 
20543  * <tt>true</tt>,
20544  * the "crossed" gravities are really at
20545  * the tooltip box corners.
20546  * 
20547  * <pre>
20548  *                nw    n    ne
20549  *               +-o----o----o-+
20550  *               |             |
20551  *             w o   Tooltip   o e
20552  *               |             |
20553  *               +-o----o----o-+
20554  *                sw    s    se
20555  *                 
20556  * </pre>
20557  * 
20558  * <p>
20559  * 
20560  * @class
20561  * @enum
20562  * @extends string
20563  */
20564 pvc.options.varia.TooltipGravity = function(){};
20565         
20566         
20567         
20568 /**
20569  * Right tooltip side is placed at the 
20570  * visual element's anchor point,
20571  * resulting in the tooltip being at its left.
20572  * 
20573  * @value 'e'
20574  */
20575 pvc.options.varia.TooltipGravity.prototype.East = 'e';
20576 /**
20577  * Top tooltip side is placed at the 
20578  * visual element's anchor point,
20579  * resulting in the tooltip being below it. 
20580  * 
20581  * @value 'n'
20582  */
20583 pvc.options.varia.TooltipGravity.prototype.North = 'n';
20584 /**
20585  * Upper-right tooltip corner is placed at the 
20586  * visual element's anchor point,
20587  * resulting in the tooltip being below it and at its left.
20588  * 
20589  * @value 'ne'
20590  */
20591 pvc.options.varia.TooltipGravity.prototype.NorthEast = 'ne';
20592 /**
20593  * Upper-left tooltip corner is placed at the 
20594  * visual element's anchor point,
20595  * resulting in the tooltip being below it and at its right.
20596  * 
20597  * @value 'nw'
20598  */
20599 pvc.options.varia.TooltipGravity.prototype.NorthWest = 'nw';
20600 /**
20601  * Bottom tooltip side is placed at the 
20602  * visual element's anchor point,
20603  * resulting in the tooltip being above it.  
20604  * 
20605  * @value 's'
20606  */
20607 pvc.options.varia.TooltipGravity.prototype.South = 's';
20608 /**
20609  * Lower-right tooltip corner is placed at the

20615 pvc.options.varia.TooltipGravity.prototype.SouthEast = 'se';

20623 pvc.options.varia.TooltipGravity.prototype.SouthWest = 'sw';

20916 /**
20917  * This type is a documentation type and 
20918  * really just documents the format of color strings.
20919  * <p>
20920  * Colors can be specified as a string that follows one of the following formats:
20921  * 
20922  * <ul>
20923  * 
20924  * <li>
20925  * an RGB or HSL color, as defined in {@link http://www.w3.org/TR/css3-color/}:
20926  * 
20927  * <ul>
20928  * 
20929  * <li>
20930  * 
20931  * <tt>'#AE7'</tt>
20932  * </li>
20933  * 
20934  * <li>
20935  * 
20936  * <tt>'#A0E070'</tt>
20937  * </li>
20938  * 
20939  * <li>
20940  * 
20941  * <tt>rgb(255, 0, 0)</tt>
20942  * </li>
20943  * 
20944  * <li>
20945  * 
20946  * <tt>rgba(100%, 0, 0, 0.5)</tt>
20947  * </li>
20948  * 
20949  * <li>
20950  * 
20951  * <tt>hsl(100, 50%, 20%)</tt>
20952  * </li>
20953  * 
20954  * <li>
20955  * 
20956  * <tt>hsla(100, 50%, 20%, 0.5)</tt>
20957  * </li>
20958  * </ul>
20959  * </li>
20960  * 
20961  * <li>
20962  * an SVG named color, as defined in {@link http://www.w3.org/TR/SVG/types.html#ColorKeywords}:
20963  * 
20964  * <ul>
20965  * 
20966  * <li>
20967  * <tt>'aliceblue'</tt></li>
20968  * 
20969  * <li>
20970  * <tt>'aquamarine'</tt></li>
20971  * </ul>
20972  * </li>
20973  * 
20974  * <li>
20975  * a subset of the CSS3 gradients format,
20976  * as defined in {@link http://www.w3.org/TR/css3-images/#gradients}:
20977  * 
20978  * <ul>
20979  * 
20980  * <li>
20981  * <tt>'linear-gradient(90deg, green, blue)'</tt></li>
20982  * 
20983  * <li>
20984  * <tt>'linear-gradient(to bottom left, red, yellow 20%, green, blue)'</tt></li>
20985  * 
20986  * <li>
20987  * <tt>'linear-gradient(red, rgb(0,0,255))'</tt></li>
20988  * 
20989  * <li>
20990  * <tt>'radial-gradient(red, yellow 40%, red)'</tt></li>
20991  * </ul>
20992  * </li>
20993  * 
20994  * <li>
20995  * 
20996  * <tt>'transparent'</tt> for a transparent background
20997  * </li>
20998  * </ul>
20999  * <p>
21000  * See the associated protovis documentation at
21001  * {@link http://mbostock.github.com/protovis/jsdoc/symbols/pv.html#.color}.
21002  * 
21003  * @class
21004  * @enum
21005  * @extends string
21006  */
21007 pvc.options.varia.ColorString = function(){};

21391 /**
21392  * The presented string should be the code of a standard precision,
21393  * optionally immediately preceded by an integer multiple.
21394  * <p>
21395  * E.g. 
21396  * <tt>'25d'</tt> means twenty five days.
21397  * 
21398  * <h2>The standard time precisions and codes:</h2>
21399  * 
21400  * <ul>
21401  * 
21402  * <li>
21403  * <tt>31536e6</tt> ms - 'y' or 'year' (pvc.time.intervals.y)  </li>
21404  * 
21405  * <li>
21406  * <tt>2592e6</tt> ms - 'm' or 'month' (pvc.time.intervals.m or pvc.time.intervals.d30)</li>
21407  * 
21408  * <li>
21409  * <tt>6048e5</tt> ms - 'w' or 'week' (pvc.time.intervals.w or pvc.time.intervals.d7)</li>
21410  * 
21411  * <li>
21412  * <tt>864e5</tt> ms - 'd' or 'day' (pvc.time.intervals.d)</li>
21413  * 
21414  * <li>
21415  * <tt>36e5</tt> ms - 'h' or 'hour' (pvc.time.intervals.h)</li>
21416  * 
21417  * <li>
21418  * <tt>6e4</tt> ms - 'M' or 'minute' (pvc.time.intervals.M)</li>
21419  * 
21420  * <li>
21421  * <tt>1e3</tt> ms - 's' or 'second' (pvc.time.intervals.s)</li>
21422  * 
21423  * <li>
21424  * <tt>1</tt> ms - 'ms' or 'millisecond' (pvc.time.intervals.ms)</li>
21425  * </ul>
21426  * 
21427  * @class
21428  * @enum
21429  * @extends string
21430  */
21431 pvc.options.varia.TimeInterval = function(){};
21432         
21433         
21434         
21435 /**
21436  * The presented string should be composed by a number of pixels and a time interval,
21437  * as described in {@link pvc.options.varia.TimeInterval},
21438  * separated by the character '/'.
21439  * <p>
21440  * E.g. 
21441  * <tt>'100 / 25d'</tt> means the specified ratio is of 100 pixels per twenty five days.
21442  * E.g. 
21443  * <tt>'100 / 2592e6'</tt> means the specified ratio is of 100 pixels per month.
21444  * 
21445  * @class
21446  * @enum
21447  * @extends string
21448  */
21449 pvc.options.varia.TimeRatio = function(){};

21451         
21452

21456  * legend panel dimensions.

21462 pvc.options.varia.LegendOverflow = function(){};

21468  * the legend panel is hidden.
21469  * <p>

21471  * of legend items exceeds {@link pvc.options.panels.LegendPanel#itemCountMax}.
21472  * <p>

21477 pvc.options.varia.LegendOverflow.prototype.Clip = 'clip';

21479  * When overflow is detected, the whole legend panel
21480  * is collapsed and the legend is not displayed.
21481  * 
21482  * @value 'collapse'
21483  */
21484 pvc.options.varia.LegendOverflow.prototype.Collapse = 'collapse';
21485 /**
21486  * Describes the distances from
21487  * each of the four sides of a rectangle:
21488  * "left", "right", "top" and "bottom".
21489  * <p>
21490  * It is used to describe the margins and the paddings of panels.
21491  * <p>
21492  * It is possible to specify any combination of the side properties.
21493  * <p>
21494  * All side properties support values in absolute or relative units:
21495  * 
21496  * <dl>
21497  * 
21498  * <dt>absolute</dt>
21499  * 
21500  * <dd>
21501  * if it is a 
21502  * <tt>number</tt> or a numeric 
21503  * <tt>string</tt>,
21504  * the measure is in pixel units
21505  * </dd>
21506  * 
21507  * <dt>relative</dt>
21508  * 
21509  * <dd>
21510  * if it is a numeric 
21511  * <tt>string</tt> with a "%" suffix,
21512  * the measure is a percentage of some reference size;
21513  * usually, the reference size is
21514  * the size of the corresponding container panel side
21515  * ("width" if side is "left" or "right", or "height" otherwise)
21516  * </dd>
21517  * </dl>
21518  * 
21519  * <h3>Special properties</h3>
21520  * 
21521  * <p>The special property, 
21522  * <tt>all</tt>, affects all unspecified properties at once.</p>
21523  * 
21524  * <p>The special property, 
21525  * <tt>width</tt>, is interpreted as if both "left" and "right" had been specified, with half the value.</p>
21526  * 
21527  * <p>The special property, 
21528  * <tt>height</tt>, is interpreted as if both "top" and "bottom" had been specified, with half the value.</p>
21529  * 
21530  * <p>When all, width, or height are specified, they are evaluated in that order, and before normal properties.</p>
21531  * 
21532  * <h3>JSON syntax example</h3>
21533  * 
21534  * <p>
21535  * The following is an example of a 
21536  * <i>sides</i>-structured object,
21537  * the hypothetical margins of a legend panel:
21538  * 
21539  * <pre>
21540  * var legendMargins = {left: 10, right: '20', all: '15%'};
21541  *                 
21542  * </pre>
21543  * It says that
21544  * the left margin has 10 pixels,
21545  * the right margin has 20 pixels, and
21546  * the top and bottom margins have each
21547  * the size of 15 percent of the legend panel's parent client height.
21548  * 
21549  * <p>
21550  * 
21551  * <h3>Single number or numeric string interpretation</h3>
21552  * All chart options of type {@link pvc.options.varia.Sides}
21553  * allow specifying
21554  * a 
21555  * <tt>number</tt> or
21556  * a 
21557  * <tt>string</tt> of a single number, possibly followed by a "%" sign,
21558  * instead of the JSON form,
21559  * as meaning 
21560  * <i>all</i> properties.
21561  * 
21562  * <h3>String syntax</h3>
21563  * All chart options of type {@link pvc.options.varia.Sides}
21564  * also allow specifying a CSS2-like margins string,
21565  * {@link http://www.w3.org/TR/CSS21/box.html#propdef-margin}.
21566  * 
21567  * <p>
21568  * The following shows the equivalence between the string and JSON syntax:
21569  * 
21570  * <pre>
21571  * var margins1 = '1';       // {all: '1'}
21572  * var margins2 = '1 2';     // {top: '1', bottom: '1', right: '2', left: '2'}
21573  * var margins3 = '1 2 3';   // {top: '1', bottom: '3', right: '2', left: '2'}
21574  * var margins4 = '1 2 3 4'; // {top: '1', bottom: '3', right: '2', left: '4'}
21575  *                 
21576  * </pre>
21577  * 
21578  * <p>
21579  * 
21580  * @class
21581  */
21582 pvc.options.varia.Sides = function(){};
21583         
21584         
21585         
21586         
21587 /**
21588  * @type number|string
21589  */
21590 pvc.options.varia.Sides.prototype.all = undefined;
21591 /**
21592  * @type number|string
21593  */
21594 pvc.options.varia.Sides.prototype.bottom = undefined;
21595 /**
21596  * @type number|string
21597  */
21598 pvc.options.varia.Sides.prototype.height = undefined;
21599 /**
21600  * @type number|string
21601  */
21602 pvc.options.varia.Sides.prototype.left = undefined;

21604  * @type number|string
21605  */
21606 pvc.options.varia.Sides.prototype.right = undefined;

21615 /**
21616  * Describes the size
21617  * of the horizontal and vertical dimensions
21618  * of an axis aligned box.
21619  * It is used to describe the margins and the paddings of panels.
21620  * <p>
21621  * It is possible to specify any combination of the size properties.
21622  * <p>
21623  * All size properties support values in absolute or relative units:
21624  * 
21625  * <dl>
21626  * 
21627  * <dt>absolute</dt>
21628  * 
21629  * <dd>
21630  * if it is a 
21631  * <tt>number</tt> or a numeric 
21632  * <tt>string</tt>,
21633  * the measure is in pixel units
21634  * </dd>
21635  * 
21636  * <dt>relative</dt>
21637  * 
21638  * <dd>
21639  * if it is a numeric 
21640  * <tt>string</tt> with a "%" suffix,
21641  * the measure is a percentage of some reference size;
21642  * usually,
21643  * the reference size is
21644  * the container panel's corresponding size
21645  * </dd>
21646  * </dl>
21647  * <p>
21648  * The special property, 
21649  * <tt>all</tt>, affects all unspecified properties at once.
21650  * 
21651  * <p>
21652  * The following is an example of a 
21653  * <i>size</i>-structured object,
21654  * the hypothetical size of a title panel:
21655  * 
21656  * <pre>
21657  * var titleSize = {width: '80%', all: 100};
21658  *                 
21659  * </pre>
21660  * It says that
21661  * the height has 100 pixels,
21662  * and that the width is 80 percent of the base panel's width.
21663  * 
21664  * <p>
21665  * 
21666  * <h3>Single number or numeric string interpretation</h3>
21667  * All chart options of type {@link pvc.options.varia.Size}
21668  * allow specifying
21669  * a 
21670  * <tt>number</tt> or
21671  * a 
21672  * <tt>string</tt> of a single number, possibly followed by a "%" sign,
21673  * instead of the JSON form.
21674  * <p>
21675  * The interpretation of what the number or percentage stand
21676  * for depends on the specific option.
21677  * In the legend and title panels, for example,
21678  * it is the size of the dimension orthogonal to the anchored to side.
21679  * So if a legend is anchored to the 
21680  * <tt>'left'</tt> side,
21681  * the number or percentage is the legend's width.
21682  * 
21683  * <h3>String syntax</h3>
21684  * All chart options of type {@link pvc.options.varia.Size}
21685  * also allow specifying a string with a fixed structure.
21686  * 
21687  * <p>
21688  * The following shows the equivalence between the string and JSON syntax:
21689  * 
21690  * <pre>
21691  * var size1 = '1';   // {all: '1'}
21692  * var size2 = '1 2'; // {width: '1', height: '2'}
21693  *                 
21694  * </pre>
21695  * 
21696  * <p>
21697  * 
21698  * @class
21699  */
21700 pvc.options.varia.Size = function(){};
21701

21894 /**
21895  * A list of dimension names and respective
21896  * sort orders.
21897  * <p>
21898  * A dimensions string is similar to an SQL 'order by' clause,
21899  * like the following examples show:
21900  * 
21901  * <dl>
21902  * 
21903  * <dt>
21904  * 
21905  * <tt>"productType"</tt>
21906  * </dt>
21907  * 
21908  * <dd>
21909  * the visual role is bound to the single dimension named 
21910  * <tt>"productType"</tt>,
21911  * and data will be sorted in ascending order
21912  * </dd>
21913  * </dl>
21914  * 
21915  * <dl>
21916  * 
21917  * <dt>
21918  * 
21919  * <tt>"sales"</tt>
21920  * </dt>
21921  * 
21922  * <dd>
21923  * the visual role is bound to the single dimension named 
21924  * <tt>"sales"</tt>,
21925  * and data will be sorted in ascending order
21926  * </dd>
21927  * </dl>
21928  * 
21929  * <dl>
21930  * 
21931  * <dt>
21932  * 
21933  * <tt>"country, productType"</tt>
21934  * </dt>
21935  * 
21936  * <dd>
21937  * the visual role is bound to the dimensions
21938  * named 
21939  * <tt>"country"</tt> and 
21940  * <tt>"productType"</tt>,
21941  * and data will be sorted first by
21942  * 
21943  * <tt>"country"</tt>, in ascending order,
21944  * and then by
21945  * 
21946  * <tt>"productType"</tt>, in ascending order
21947  * </dd>
21948  * </dl>
21949  * 
21950  * <dl>
21951  * 
21952  * <dt>
21953  * 
21954  * <tt>"country desc, productType asc"</tt>
21955  * </dt>
21956  * 
21957  * <dd>
21958  * the visual role is bound to the dimensions
21959  * named 
21960  * <tt>"country"</tt> and 
21961  * <tt>"productType"</tt>,
21962  * and data will be sorted first by
21963  * 
21964  * <tt>"country"</tt>, in descending order,
21965  * and then by
21966  * 
21967  * <tt>"productType"</tt>, in ascending order
21968  * </dd>
21969  * </dl>
21970  * 
21971  * @type string
21972  */
